{"title_page": "Fiat 126", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox automobile\n| image = 1973 Fiat 126 IMG 7855.jpg\n| name = Fiat 126<br>Polski Fiat 126p\n| manufacturer = [[Fiat]] (1972\u20131980)<ref name=\"fiat126.co.uk\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.fiat126.co.uk/|title=Fiat 126 Key Dates Time Line - illustrating the life of the original Fiat 126 from 72', the Fiat 126 de ville and the Fiat 126 BIS|accessdate=9 May 2009|work=fiat126.co.uk}}</ref><br>[[Fabryka Samochod\u00f3w Ma\u0142olitra\u017cowych|FSM]] (Polski Fiat 126p, 1973\u20131992)<br>Fiat Auto Poland (1992\u20132000)\n| production = 1972\u20132000<br />4,673,655 units\n| aka = Zastava 126 (Yugoslavia)<br>Steyr Puch Fiat 126 (Austria)<br>\nFiat 126 Maluch (Poland)<br />FSM Niki (Australia)\n| class = [[City car]] ([[A-segment|A]])\n| layout = [[Rear-engine, rear-wheel drive layout|RR layout]]\n| body_style = 2-door [[Sedan (automobile)|saloon]]<br>3-door [[hatchback]] (PF 126 BIS)\n| engine = 594&nbsp;cc [[Straight-twin engine|Straight-2]]<br>652&nbsp;cc Straight-2<br>704&nbsp;cc Straight-2\n| transmission =\n| length = {{Convert|3054|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"carfolio.com\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.carfolio.com/specifications/models/car/?car=38016|title=1973 Fiat 126 Technical specifications|accessdate=25 February 2010|work=carfolio.com}}</ref>\n| width = {{Convert|1378|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"carfolio.com\"/>\n| height = {{Convert|1302|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"carfolio.com\"/>\n| weight = {{Convert|580|-|619|kg|abbr=on}}\n| wheelbase = {{Convert|1840|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"carfolio.com\"/>\n| predecessor = [[Fiat 500]]\n| successor = [[Fiat Panda]], [[Fiat Cinquecento]]\n| related = [[SEAT 133|Fiat 133]]<br>[[SEAT 133]]\n| assembly = [[Alfa Romeo Cassino Plant|Cassino]], Italy<br>[[Termini Imerese]], Italy<br>[[Tychy]], Poland ([[Polski Fiat]])<br>[[Kragujevac]], Yugoslavia ([[Zastava Automobiles|Zastava]])<br>[[Steyr]], Austria ([[Steyr-Daimler-Puch|Steyr Puch]])\n| designer = [[Sergio Sartorelli]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Fiat 126''' (Type 126) is a four passenger, [[Rear-engine design|rear-engined]] [[city car]], introduced by Fiat in October 1972 at the [[Turin Auto Show#1972|Turin Auto Show]]<ref name=\"fiat126.co.uk\"/> as a replacement for the [[Fiat 500]]. The majority of 126s were produced in [[Bielsko-Bia\u0142a]], [[Poland]], as the '''[[Polski Fiat]] 126p''', where production continued until 2000. In many markets Fiat stopped sales of the 126 in 1993 in favour of their new front-engined [[Fiat Cinquecento|Cinquecento]]. At a length of 3.05 metres, total production reach almost 4.7 million units. In Poland the car became a [[cultural icon]]and earned the nickname ''Maluch'', meaning \"The Little One\" or \"Toddler\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://metro.co.uk/2017/02/18/residents-in-polish-city-save-up-and-buy-tom-hanks-a-vintage-car-6456766/|title=Residents in Polish city save up and buy Tom Hanks a vintage car|first=Hannah Lawrence for|last=Metro.co.uk|date=18 February 2017|publisher=|accessdate=12 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-people-hanks-poland-fiat-idUSKBN15F2CD|title=Polish fans buy Tom Hanks iconic 'toddler' car|date=31 January 2017|publisher=|accessdate=12 July 2017|via=Reuters}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\nThe 126 shared its wheelbase and much of the same mechanical underpinnings and layout with the Fiat 500, featuring an revised, slightly larger bodyshell designed by [[Sergio Sartorelli]] and offering improved safety and interior space.\n\n[[File:Trunk of a white left hand drive Fiat 126 produced in 1973.jpg|thumb|left|The front footwells, suspension, battery and spare wheel left little room for luggage in the 126 front trunk.]]\nEngine capacity was increased from 594&nbsp;cc to 652&nbsp;cc at the end of 1977 when the cylinder bore was increased from 73.5 to 77&nbsp;mm.<ref name=AutoMotoruSport197724>{{cite journal| author = Ferdinand Simoneit (Ed)| title = Mehr Hubraum und Drehmoment fuer den Fiat 126| journal = [[Auto, Motor und Sport]] | volume = 24 | page = 20 | date = 23 November 1977}}</ref> Claimed power output was unchanged at {{convert|23|HP|kW|0|abbr=on}}, but torque was increased from {{convert|39|N\u00b7m|lb.ft|0|abbr=on}} to {{convert|43|N\u00b7m|lb.ft|0}}.<ref name=AutoMotoruSport197724/>\nThe 594&nbsp;cc engines were still available in early 1983 production.\n\nA subsequent increase took the engine size to 704&nbsp;cc in new \"restyling\" model Fiat 126 Bis (1987\u20131991), with {{Convert|26|HP|kW|0|abbr=on}} of motive power.\n\n[[File:Auto Italia Stanford Hall June 2010 IMG 9616 (4680343746).jpg|thumb|left|Fiat 126 (second from left) at the Auto Italia, Stanford Hall, 2010]]\n\nThe 126 was manufactured at Fiat's [[Cassino]] and [[Termini Imerese]] plants, until 1979 &mdash; with an overall production of 1,352,912 manuactured in Italy.\n\nThe 126 was also manufactured under licence by [[Zastava Automobiles|Zastava]] in [[Yugoslavia]]. In [[Austria]], it was briefly assembled by [[Steyr-Daimler-Puch|Steyr Puch]] as a successor to the successful [[Puch 500]], with assembly lasting until 1975 &mdash; and production of 2069 examples.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.steyrpuch.at/puch126.htm|title=STEYR-PUCH-FREUNDE OBERK\u00c4RNTEN|website=www.steyrpuch.at|access-date=19 December 2018}}</ref> In [[Greece]], there was an attempt to produce a small car named [[DIM (automobiles)|DIM]] whose technical layout was largely based on the 126, but only ten were produced before the project was abandoned.{{cn}}\n\nThe 126 never achieved the popularity of the 500 in Western Europe, as the rear-engined layout lost favor to [[Front-engine, front-wheel-drive layout|front-engine, front-wheel drive]], nonetheless becoming one of the last and longest-living rear-engine small cars manufactured in Europe, survived only by the [[Volkswagen Beetle|VW Beetle]] whose production lasted until 1978 (2003, globally).  The 126 was the last rear-engine small car to be manufactured in Europe until the advent of the [[Smart Fortwo]].\n\nFor a brief period in the early 1990s, a German company called POP also offered convertible versions of the 126 BIS. Two models were offered: a lesser equipped one called the \"POP 650\" and a more luxurious model called the \"POP 2000\".\n\n{{clear_left}}\n\n== Polski Fiat 126p ==\n[[File:Polski Fiat 126p rocznik 1973.jpg|thumb|right|1973 Polski Fiat 126p (Poland)]]\n\nIn [[Poland]], the car was produced under licence by [[Fabryka Samochod\u00f3w Ma\u0142olitra\u017cowych]] (FSM) (En: Small-Engined Car Factory) in [[Bielsko-Bia\u0142a]] and [[Tychy]] under the brand [[Polski Fiat]] 126p (literally in English: ''Polish Fiat 126p'') between 1973 and 2000.\n\nDue to a relatively low price it was very popular in Poland and was arguably the most popular Polish car in the 1980s. Its very small size gave it the nickname '''''maluch''''' (\"the small one\", \"small child\", pronounced {{IPA-pl|\u02c8malux|}}). The nickname became so popular that in 1997 it was accepted by the manufacturer as the official name of the car.\n[[File:FSM Niki 650 (14821160718).jpg|thumb|A 126 in Australia, sold locally as the FSM Niki.]]\nAt first it was almost identical with the basic model: differences included a higher chassis, a modified grille on the back, and the front indicator lenses that were clear white in Italy but orange in other markets. To distinguish it from the original Italian car, the letter \"p\" was added to its name.\n\nThroughout the 1980s the 126p was continuously modified. First it received upgraded brakes and new wheels from Italian Fiat, then hazard warning lights were added to meet new lighting requirements.\n\nIn 1984, the 126 received a facelift, giving it plastic bumpers (for all versions) and a new dashboard. This model was named the Fiat 126p FL. In 1985 a single rear fog light and reversing light (on opposite sides) were added to the standard plastic bumpers; an electronic ignition system and alternator replaced the undersized generator in around 1987. In 1994, the 126p received another facelift, and some parts from the [[Fiat Cinquecento]]; this version was named 126 EL. The 126 ELX introduced a catalytic converter.\n\nIn 1987 the 126 BIS went into production, featuring a water-cooled 704&nbsp;cc engine of Polish construction. However, the original model continued to be produced for the Polish market. BIS used some of parts from [[Fiat cinquecento]].\n\nThe factory battery in 126p had only a 35 Amp-hour capacity, which, combined with undersized generator, resulted in the car never having a fully charged battery unless driven for an extended time. Some owners upgraded to a 45 Amp-hour battery from the Fiat 125p (1.5 Liter engine) to improve the cold start reliability.\n\n[[File:GeneralLeeFiat.JPG|thumb|right|A modified Fiat 126]]\n\nThe 126p was exported to many [[Eastern Bloc]] countries and for several years it was one of the most popular cars in [[Poland]] and in [[Hungary]] as well. It also found a minor market in Australia between 1989 and 1992, under the name '''FSM Niki'''. During that period it was Australia's cheapest car.<ref>{{cite web|title=FSM Niki 650, too little, too late|url=http://www.transeum.com/worlds-worst-cars/fsm-niki-650-too-little-too-late.html|publisher=Transeum|accessdate=29 August 2011}}</ref> There was a convertible version developed for the Australian market.{{Citation needed|date=December 2018}} It was also successful in [[Cuba]] where it was one of the best-selling cars of its time and an estimated 10.000 still exist today.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/polish-fiat-126p-sees-unlikely-cuban-revival/a-19464887|title=Polish Fiat 126p sees unlikely Cuban revival {{!}} DW {{!}} 11 August 2016|last=Welle (www.dw.com)|first=Deutsche|website=DW.COM|language=en-GB|access-date=19 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nThroughout the 1980s, there were several experimental prototypes developed in Poland. A cargo version called \"Bombel\" (literally \"bubble\", but also a colloquial term for \"small child\") because of its fibreglass bubble-shaped cargo area; an off-road version propelled by caterpillar tracks and a front wheel drive, front engined model, with a longer front end and a flat cargo area in the rear where the original 126 had its engine. The rear of this prototype was similar to the 126 Bis which also had a rear hatch for accessing a cargo space created by mounting its flat water-cooled engine under the floor.\n\nThere was also an attempt at installing a small diesel engine (due to gasoline rationing) in the classic 126p body. It is also a popular platform for electric engine and motorcycle engine swaps.\n\n=== History of PF 126p ===\n[[File:Fiat 126 BIS during \u201eXXX lat motoryzacji PRL\u201d exhibition at Bonarka City Center in Krak\u00f3w.JPG|thumb|From 1987 the 126 became available as a hatchback, in spite of having the engine in the rear.]]\n* 1972 \u2013 the FSM car factory was built in [[Bielsko-Bia\u0142a]].\n* 6 June 1973 \u2013 the first Polski Fiat 126p constructed from Italian parts. The official price was 69,000 [[Polish z\u0142oty]]s with [[PKO Bank Polski]] accepting pre-payments on savings books starting 5 February 1973.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.auto-swiat.pl/1-polski-fiat-126p-przez-ksiazeczke-do-fiata |first=Adam |last=W\u0142odarz |title=Polski Fiat 126p - Przez ksi\u0105\u017ceczk\u0119 do Fiata |language=Polish |publisher=Auto Swiat |date=18 December 2006 |accessdate=5 November 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425141831/http://www.auto-swiat.pl/1-polski-fiat-126p-przez-ksiazeczke-do-fiata |archivedate=25 April 2012  }}</ref>\n* 22 July 1973 \u2013 the official opening of the factory's production line (by the end of that year over 1500 Fiats were manufactured).\n* September 1975 \u2013 production started in a factory in [[Tychy]].\n* 1977 \u2013 engine capacity increased from 594&nbsp;cc to 652&nbsp;cc. Engine power increased to about {{Convert|24|hp}}.\n* 1978 \u2013 production of types with engine capacity 594 cc ended.\n* 1979 \u2013 production of Polski Fiat 126p continued only in Bielsko-Bia\u0142a.\n* 1981 \u2013 1,000,000th Polski Fiat 126p produced.\n* December 1984 \u2013 technical changes in the construction and body. Type ''FL'' introduced.\n* 1987 \u2013 beginning of the production of the water-cooled  ''Polski Fiat 126p Bis'' version \u2013 a three-door hatchback with 704&nbsp;cc capacity.\n* May 1993 \u2013 3,000,000th Polish Fiat 126p produced.\n* September 1994 \u2013 body improvement, creating type \"el\" with parts similar to those used in [[Fiat Cinquecento]].\n* January 1997 \u2013 introduction of a [[catalytic converter]].\n* 22 September 2000 \u2013 production ended after a production run of 3,318,674 units. All Fiats of the last limited ''Happy End'' series were yellow or red (500 cars in red and 500 cars in yellow).\n\nThe global production of the car was 4,673,655 units: 1,352,912 in Italy, 2,069 in Austria by Fiat-Steyr and 3,318,674 in Poland.\n\n=== Political connotations ===\n[[File:PF126p.jpg|thumb|A Fiat 126p in Poland, 1973 - with the car having attracted the curiosity of passers-by]]\n\nThe PF 126p has special meaning for Poles and its story had a connection with Polish politics during the communist period ([[Polish People's Republic]], up to 1989). During the absolute rule of the [[PZPR]], a private car was considered a luxury item, due to limited availability and low salaries. In 1971 there were only 556,000 passenger cars in Poland.<ref>{{cite journal | first = Marcin | last = Zaremba | url = http://archiwum.polityka.pl/art/good-bye-gierek,395534.html| title = Good bye, Gierek! | journal = [[Polityka]] | volume = 45 | year = 2004 | issue = 2477 | page = 79 | language = Polish }}</ref> In a top-down [[planned economy]], decisions on whether a state-owned factory could produce a car were taken on political and not just economic grounds. The authorities themselves initially did not find the idea of private cars attractive. The first relatively cheap Polish car was the [[FSO Syrena|Syrena]], but it was outdated and its production was limited. Limited numbers of cars were also imported from other Eastern Bloc countries. It was difficult to buy a Western car because the [[Polish z\u0142oty]], like other currencies in communist states, was not convertible to Western funds and there was no free market in the country.\n\nThus, the PF 126p was intended to be the first real, popular and affordable car, to provide mobility for ordinary families. The licence was bought after the rise to power of a new [[PZPR]] leader, [[Edward Gierek]], who wanted to gain popular favour by increasing consumer spending after the austerity period under [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Gomu\u0142ka]]. Despite the fact that it was a very small [[city car]], it was the only choice for most families, filling the role of a [[family car]]. During holidays, it was common to see families of four driving PF-126s abroad with huge suitcases on a [[roof rack]]; sightings of PF-126s towing a small [[:pl:Niewiad\u00f3w N126|Niewiad\u00f3w N126]] caravan especially designed for the PF 126 were also occasionally reported.<ref name=zakrz/> PF 126p production, however, was not sufficient and the PF 126p was on sale with a waiting list. Usually families had to wait a couple of years to buy a car.<ref name=zakrz>Zakrzewski, Adam (2010). pp.72-83</ref> A coupon for a car could also be given by the authorities based on merit.\n\n== Nicknames ==\n\nIn Poland it is called ''Maluch'', which literally means \"small one\" or toddler,<ref>{{cite book|last=Turnock|first=David|title=The East European economy in context: communism and transition|year=1997|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-0-415-08626-4|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qej-6dP5e74C&pg=PA307&dq=126p+Maluch|accessdate=6 November 2010|page=307}}</ref> as well as ''ma\u0142y Fiat'' (\"small Fiat\"), in contrast to [[Fiat 125p]], called ''du\u017cy Fiat'' (\"big Fiat\").<ref>{{cite book|last=Swan|first=Oscar E.|title=Intermediate Polish|year=1986|publisher=Slavica Publishers|isbn=978-0-89357-165-8|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mD8IAAAAIAAJ&q=ma\u0142y+Fiat&dq=ma\u0142y+Fiat|accessdate=6 November 2010|page=71}}</ref> In some regions, it is also called ''Kaszlak'',<ref>{{cite book|last=Czeszewski|first=Maciej|title=S\u0142ownik polszczyzny potocznej|year=2006|publisher=Wydawn. Naukowe PWN|isbn=978-83-01-14631-3|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xCUZAQAAIAAJ&q=Kaszlak+Fiat+126&dq=Kaszlak+Fiat+126|accessdate=6 November 2010|page=129|language=Polish}}</ref> literally \"cougher\" (derived from ''[[wikt:kaszel#Polish|kaszel]]'', \"[[cough]]\", as its engine's sound resembles a cough when it is started).\n[[File:Cuba, Havana, FIAT 126p Polski.jpg|thumb|Fiat 126p in [[Havana]], Cuba, March 2014]]\nIn [[Albania]] and [[Kosovo]] it is known as ''Kikirez'', in Serbian meaning a \"little rooster\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.autocentrum.pl/skarbnica-wiedzy/fiat/126p-maluch/|title=Fiat 126p \"Maluch\" \u2022 Skarbnica wiedzy \u2022 AutoCentrum.pl|website=www.autocentrum.pl|accessdate=12 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Serbian language|Serbian]], [[Croatian language|Croatian]] and [[Bosnian language|Bosnian]] it is known as ''Peglica'' (meaning \"little [[Iron (appliance)|iron]]\").<ref>{{cite book|last=Labourdette|first=Jean-Paul, Dominique Auzias|title=Przewodnik Chorwacja|year=2007|publisher=Petit Fute|isbn=978-83-60496-20-6|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=h11ayWWvvl8C&pg=PA222&dq=126+Peglica|accessdate=6 November 2010|page=222|language=Polish}}</ref>\n\nIn Slovene the 126 is also called ''Bolha'' (\"[[flea]]\"),<ref>{{cite book|last=Weiss|first=Peter|title=Slovar govorov Zadre\u010dke doline med Gornjim gradom in Nazarjami|year=1998|publisher=Znanstvenoraziskovalni center SAZU|isbn=978-961-6182-47-8|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=I5jlAAAAMAAJ&q=Fiat+126+Bolha&dq=Fiat+126+Bolha|accessdate=6 November 2010|page=206}}</ref> Pi\u010di-poki (loosely translated as \"fast-and-loud\") or ''Kalimero'' on [[Slovenian Littoral|Slovenian coast]] after a cartoon character [[Calimero]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://forums.bistudio.com/forums/topic/20164-fiat-126/|title=Fiat 126|website=Bohemia Interactive Forums|accessdate=12 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Hungarian language|Hungarian]], it is known as ''kispolszki'' (\"Little Polish\", while the [[Polski Fiat 125p|125p]] is the ''nagypolszki'', meaning \"Big Polish\"), ''kispol\u00e1k'' (\"Little [[Poles|Pole]]\") or ''kisp''\u00f3''k'' (\"Little spider\"); also, the car was nicknamed ''eg\u00e9rkamion'', meaning \"a mouse's truck\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vezess.hu/vezetunk/2015/03/18/igazi-gyongyszem-lanctalpas-kispolak/|title=Igazi gy\u00f6ngyszem \u2013 L\u00e1nctalpas kispol\u00e1k|date=18 March 2015|publisher=|accessdate=12 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn Germany the Fiat 126 was known as the ''Bambino'', the Italian word for child.<ref>{{cite book|last=Deiss|first=Richard|title=Silberling und B\u00fcgeleisen - 1000 Spitznamen in Transport und Verkehr und was dahinter steckt|year=2010|publisher=Ausstattung/Bilder|isbn=978-3-8391-6269-9|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=L0Tc7aZUh3QC&pg=PA50&dq=Fiat+126+Bambino|accessdate=6 November 2010|page=50|language=German}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Cuba]] it is known as the \"Polqi\" or \"Polaquito\", meaning \"Little [[Poles|Pole]]\" or \"Little Polish man\", and in [[Chile]] as \"Bototo\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slaskie.naszemiasto.pl/artykul/fiat-126p-podbil-kube-nazywaja-go-polaquito,3850064,artgal,t,id,tm.html|title=Fiat 126p podbi\u0142 Kub\u0119... nazywaj\u0105 go \"polaquito\"|first=P.|last=Ciastek|date=7 September 2016|publisher=|accessdate=12 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VfypBAAAQBAJ&pg=PT212&lpg=PT212&dq=bototo+fiat&source=bl&ots=m3cfUQZex-&sig=bIOMsL8AVd4DFjdG5comX0u93IA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi4_e2DhYPVAhVDybwKHUkVCsY4ChDoAQhVMAY#v=onepage&q=bototo+fiat&f=false|title=Maluch. Biografia|first=Przemys\u0142aw|last=Semczuk|date=1 October 2014|publisher=Otwarte|accessdate=12 July 2017|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* {{cite book |title=Polski FIAT 126P: technika jazdy, obs\u0142uga i usprawnienia |first=Zbigniew |last=Klimecki |first2=Roman |last2=Podolak |publisher=Wydawnictwa Komunikacji i \u0141\u0105czno\u015bci |year=1982 |isbn=978-83-206-0092-6 |language=Polish}}\n* {{cite book |title=Fiat 126p Ma\u0142y Wielki Samoch\u00f3d |first=Aleksander |last=Sowa |publisher=Z\u0142ot My\u015bli |year=2008 |isbn=978-83-7582-550-3 |language=Polish}}\n* Zakrzewski, Adam (2010) {{in lang|pl}}. ''Auto-moto PRL: w\u0142adcy dr\u00f3g i poboczy'', Demart, Warsaw, {{ISBN|978-83-7427-484-5}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{dmoz|Recreation/Autos/Makes_and_Models/Fiat|Fiat}}\n{{Fiat}}\n{{Early European Fiat vehicles}}\n{{Modern European Fiat vehicles}}\n\n[[Category:Fiat vehicles|126]]\n[[Category:Rear-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:Rear-engined vehicles]]\n[[Category:City cars]]\n[[Category:Hatchbacks]]\n[[Category:1970s cars]]\n[[Category:1980s cars]]\n[[Category:1990s cars]]\n[[Category:2000s cars]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 1972]]\n[[Category:Science and technology in Poland]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox automobile\n| image = 1973 Fiat 126 IMG 7855.jpg\n| name = Fiat 126<br>Polski Fiat 126p\n| manufacturer = [[Fiat]] (1972\u20131980)<ref name=\"fiat126.co.uk\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.fiat126.co.uk/|title=Fiat 126 Key Dates Time Line - illustrating the life of the original Fiat 126 from 72', the Fiat 126 de ville and the Fiat 126 BIS|accessdate=9 May 2009|work=fiat126.co.uk}}</ref><br>[[Fabryka Samochod\u00f3w Ma\u0142olitra\u017cowych|FSM]] (Polski Fiat 126p, 1973\u20131992)<br>Fiat Auto Poland (1992\u20132000)\n| production = 1972\u20132000<br />4,673,655 units\n| aka = Zastava 126 (Yugoslavia)<br>Steyr Puch Fiat 126 (Austria)<br>\nFiat 126 Maluch (Poland)<br />FSM Niki (Australia)\n| class = [[City car]] ([[A-segment|A]])\n| layout = [[Rear-engine, rear-wheel drive layout|RR layout]]\n| body_style = 2-door [[Sedan (automobile)|saloon]]<br>3-door [[hatchback]] (PF 126 BIS)\n| engine = 594&nbsp;cc [[Straight-twin engine|Straight-2]]<br>652&nbsp;cc Straight-2<br>704&nbsp;cc Straight-2\n| transmission =\n| length = {{Convert|3054|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"carfolio.com\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.carfolio.com/specifications/models/car/?car=38016|title=1973 Fiat 126 Technical specifications|accessdate=25 February 2010|work=carfolio.com}}</ref>\n| width = {{Convert|1378|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"carfolio.com\"/>\n| height = {{Convert|1302|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"carfolio.com\"/>\n| weight = {{Convert|580|-|619|kg|abbr=on}}\n| wheelbase = {{Convert|1840|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"carfolio.com\"/>\n| predecessor = [[Fiat 500]]\n| successor = [[Fiat Panda]], [[Fiat Cinquecento]]\n| related = [[SEAT 133|Fiat 133]]<br>[[SEAT 133]]\n| assembly = [[Alfa Romeo Cassino Plant|Cassino]], Italy<br>[[Termini Imerese]], Italy<br>[[Tychy]], Poland ([[Polski Fiat]])<br>[[Kragujevac]], Yugoslavia ([[Zastava Automobiles|Zastava]])<br>[[Steyr]], Austria ([[Steyr-Daimler-Puch|Steyr Puch]])\n| designer = [[Sergio Sartorelli]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Fiat 126''' (Type 126) is a four passenger, [[Rear-engine design|rear-engined]] [[city car]], introduced by Fiat in October 1972 at the [[Turin Auto Show#1972|Turin Auto Show]]<ref name=\"fiat126.co.uk\"/> as a replacement for the [[Fiat 500]]. The majority of 126s were produced in [[Bielsko-Bia\u0142a]], [[Poland]], as the '''[[Polski Fiat]] 126p''', where production continued until 2000. In many markets Fiat stopped sales of the 126 in 1993 in favour of their new front-engined [[Fiat Cinquecento|Cinquecento]]. At a length of 3.05 metres, total production reach almost 4.7 million units. In Poland the car became a [[cultural icon]]and earned the nickname ''Maluch'', meaning \"The Little One\" or \"Toddler\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://metro.co.uk/2017/02/18/residents-in-polish-city-save-up-and-buy-tom-hanks-a-vintage-car-6456766/|title=Residents in Polish city save up and buy Tom Hanks a vintage car|first=Hannah Lawrence for|last=Metro.co.uk|date=18 February 2017|publisher=|accessdate=12 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-people-hanks-poland-fiat-idUSKBN15F2CD|title=Polish fans buy Tom Hanks iconic 'toddler' car|date=31 January 2017|publisher=|accessdate=12 July 2017|via=Reuters}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\nThe 126 shared its wheelbase and much of the same mechanical underpinnings and layout with the Fiat 500, featuring an revised, slightly larger bodyshell designed by [[Sergio Sartorelli]] and offering improved safety and interior space.\n\n[[File:Trunk of a white left hand drive Fiat 126 produced in 1973.jpg|thumb|left|The front footwells, suspension, battery and spare wheel left little room for luggage in the 126 front trunk.]]\nEngine capacity was increased from 594&nbsp;cc to 652&nbsp;cc at the end of 1977 when the cylinder bore was increased from 73.5 to 77&nbsp;mm.<ref name=AutoMotoruSport197724>{{cite journal| author = Ferdinand Simoneit (Ed)| title = Mehr Hubraum und Drehmoment fuer den Fiat 126| journal = [[Auto, Motor und Sport]] | volume = 24 | page = 20 | date = 23 November 1977}}</ref> Claimed power output was unchanged at {{convert|23|HP|kW|0|abbr=on}}, but torque was increased from {{convert|39|N\u00b7m|lb.ft|0|abbr=on}} to {{convert|43|N\u00b7m|lb.ft|0}}.<ref name=AutoMotoruSport197724/>\nThe 594&nbsp;cc engines were still available in early 1983 production.\n\nA subsequent increase took the engine size to 704&nbsp;cc in new \"restyling\" model Fiat 126 Bis (1987\u20131991), with {{Convert|26|HP|kW|0|abbr=on}} of motive power.\n\n[[File:Auto Italia Stanford Hall June 2010 IMG 9616 (4680343746).jpg|thumb|left|Fiat 126 (second from left) at the Auto Italia, Stanford Hall, 2010]]\n\nIn Italy, the car was produced in the plants of [[Cassino]] and [[Termini Imerese]] until 1979. By this time 1,352,912 of the cars had been produced in Italy.\n\nThe car was also produced under licence by [[Zastava Automobiles|Zastava]] in [[Yugoslavia]]. In [[Austria]], it was briefly assembled by [[Steyr-Daimler-Puch|Steyr Puch]] as a successor to the successful [[Puch 500]], but assembly only lasted until 1975 with only 2069 having been built.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.steyrpuch.at/puch126.htm|title=STEYR-PUCH-FREUNDE OBERK\u00c4RNTEN|website=www.steyrpuch.at|access-date=19 December 2018}}</ref> In [[Greece]], there was an attempt to produce a small car named [[DIM (automobiles)|DIM]] whose technical layout was largely based on the 126, but only ten were produced before the project was abandoned.\n\nThe 126 never achieved the frenzied popularity of the 500 in Western Europe, partly due to the fact that rear-engined small cars were considered outdated by the time it arrived as the Mini had paved the way for [[Front-engine, front-wheel-drive layout|front-engine, front-wheel drive]] small cars. Despite this, it still proved popular in Eastern Europe and remained in production for a long time, thus becoming one of the last and longest-living rear-engine small cars manufactured in Europe. In fact, it was only survived by the [[Volkswagen Beetle|VW Beetle]] whose production lasted until 2003, although production in Europe ceased in 1978, making the 126 the last rear-engine small car to be manufactured in Europe.{{Dubious|Rear-engined small cars still being made in Europe |reason=Various Smart models are rear-engined, small and manufactured in Europe even at the time of this tagging|date=September 2019}}\n\nFor a brief period in the early 1990s, a German company called POP also offered convertible versions of the 126 BIS. Two models were offered: a lesser equipped one called the \"POP 650\" and a more luxurious model called the \"POP 2000\".\n\n{{clear_left}}\n\n== Polski Fiat 126p ==\n[[File:Polski Fiat 126p rocznik 1973.jpg|thumb|right|1973 Polski Fiat 126p (Poland)]]\n\nIn [[Poland]], the car was produced under licence by [[Fabryka Samochod\u00f3w Ma\u0142olitra\u017cowych]] (FSM) (En: Small-Engined Car Factory) in [[Bielsko-Bia\u0142a]] and [[Tychy]] under the brand [[Polski Fiat]] 126p (literally in English: ''Polish Fiat 126p'') between 1973 and 2000.\n\nDue to a relatively low price it was very popular in Poland and was arguably the most popular Polish car in the 1980s. Its very small size gave it the nickname '''''maluch''''' (\"the small one\", \"small child\", pronounced {{IPA-pl|\u02c8malux|}}). The nickname became so popular that in 1997 it was accepted by the manufacturer as the official name of the car.\n[[File:FSM Niki 650 (14821160718).jpg|thumb|A 126 in Australia, sold locally as the FSM Niki.]]\nAt first it was almost identical with the basic model: differences included a higher chassis, a modified grille on the back, and the front indicator lenses that were clear white in Italy but orange in other markets. To distinguish it from the original Italian car, the letter \"p\" was added to its name.\n\nThroughout the 1980s the 126p was continuously modified. First it received upgraded brakes and new wheels from Italian Fiat, then hazard warning lights were added to meet new lighting requirements.\n\nIn 1984, the 126 received a facelift, giving it plastic bumpers (for all versions) and a new dashboard. This model was named the Fiat 126p FL. In 1985 a single rear fog light and reversing light (on opposite sides) were added to the standard plastic bumpers; an electronic ignition system and alternator replaced the undersized generator in around 1987. In 1994, the 126p received another facelift, and some parts from the [[Fiat Cinquecento]]; this version was named 126 EL. The 126 ELX introduced a catalytic converter.\n\nIn 1987 the 126 BIS went into production, featuring a water-cooled 704&nbsp;cc engine of Polish construction. However, the original model continued to be produced for the Polish market. BIS used some of parts from [[Fiat cinquecento]].\n\nThe factory battery in 126p had only a 35 Amp-hour capacity, which, combined with undersized generator, resulted in the car never having a fully charged battery unless driven for an extended time. Some owners upgraded to a 45 Amp-hour battery from the Fiat 125p (1.5 Liter engine) to improve the cold start reliability.\n\n[[File:GeneralLeeFiat.JPG|thumb|right|A modified Fiat 126]]\n\nThe 126p was exported to many [[Eastern Bloc]] countries and for several years it was one of the most popular cars in [[Poland]] and in [[Hungary]] as well. It also found a minor market in Australia between 1989 and 1992, under the name '''FSM Niki'''. During that period it was Australia's cheapest car.<ref>{{cite web|title=FSM Niki 650, too little, too late|url=http://www.transeum.com/worlds-worst-cars/fsm-niki-650-too-little-too-late.html|publisher=Transeum|accessdate=29 August 2011}}</ref> There was a convertible version developed for the Australian market.{{Citation needed|date=December 2018}} It was also successful in [[Cuba]] where it was one of the best-selling cars of its time and an estimated 10.000 still exist today.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/polish-fiat-126p-sees-unlikely-cuban-revival/a-19464887|title=Polish Fiat 126p sees unlikely Cuban revival {{!}} DW {{!}} 11 August 2016|last=Welle (www.dw.com)|first=Deutsche|website=DW.COM|language=en-GB|access-date=19 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nThroughout the 1980s, there were several experimental prototypes developed in Poland. A cargo version called \"Bombel\" (literally \"bubble\", but also a colloquial term for \"small child\") because of its fibreglass bubble-shaped cargo area; an off-road version propelled by caterpillar tracks and a front wheel drive, front engined model, with a longer front end and a flat cargo area in the rear where the original 126 had its engine. The rear of this prototype was similar to the 126 Bis which also had a rear hatch for accessing a cargo space created by mounting its flat water-cooled engine under the floor.\n\nThere was also an attempt at installing a small diesel engine (due to gasoline rationing) in the classic 126p body. It is also a popular platform for electric engine and motorcycle engine swaps.\n\n=== History of PF 126p ===\n[[File:Fiat 126 BIS during \u201eXXX lat motoryzacji PRL\u201d exhibition at Bonarka City Center in Krak\u00f3w.JPG|thumb|From 1987 the 126 became available as a hatchback, in spite of having the engine in the rear.]]\n* 1972 \u2013 the FSM car factory was built in [[Bielsko-Bia\u0142a]].\n* 6 June 1973 \u2013 the first Polski Fiat 126p constructed from Italian parts. The official price was 69,000 [[Polish z\u0142oty]]s with [[PKO Bank Polski]] accepting pre-payments on savings books starting 5 February 1973.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.auto-swiat.pl/1-polski-fiat-126p-przez-ksiazeczke-do-fiata |first=Adam |last=W\u0142odarz |title=Polski Fiat 126p - Przez ksi\u0105\u017ceczk\u0119 do Fiata |language=Polish |publisher=Auto Swiat |date=18 December 2006 |accessdate=5 November 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425141831/http://www.auto-swiat.pl/1-polski-fiat-126p-przez-ksiazeczke-do-fiata |archivedate=25 April 2012  }}</ref>\n* 22 July 1973 \u2013 the official opening of the factory's production line (by the end of that year over 1500 Fiats were manufactured).\n* September 1975 \u2013 production started in a factory in [[Tychy]].\n* 1977 \u2013 engine capacity increased from 594&nbsp;cc to 652&nbsp;cc. Engine power increased to about {{Convert|24|hp}}.\n* 1978 \u2013 production of types with engine capacity 594 cc ended.\n* 1979 \u2013 production of Polski Fiat 126p continued only in Bielsko-Bia\u0142a.\n* 1981 \u2013 1,000,000th Polski Fiat 126p produced.\n* December 1984 \u2013 technical changes in the construction and body. Type ''FL'' introduced.\n* 1987 \u2013 beginning of the production of the water-cooled  ''Polski Fiat 126p Bis'' version \u2013 a three-door hatchback with 704&nbsp;cc capacity.\n* May 1993 \u2013 3,000,000th Polish Fiat 126p produced.\n* September 1994 \u2013 body improvement, creating type \"el\" with parts similar to those used in [[Fiat Cinquecento]].\n* January 1997 \u2013 introduction of a [[catalytic converter]].\n* 22 September 2000 \u2013 production ended after a production run of 3,318,674 units. All Fiats of the last limited ''Happy End'' series were yellow or red (500 cars in red and 500 cars in yellow).\n\nThe global production of the car was 4,673,655 units: 1,352,912 in Italy, 2,069 in Austria by Fiat-Steyr and 3,318,674 in Poland.\n\n=== Political connotations ===\n[[File:PF126p.jpg|thumb|A Fiat 126p in Poland, 1973 - with the car having attracted the curiosity of passers-by]]\n\nThe PF 126p has special meaning for Poles and its story had a connection with Polish politics during the communist period ([[Polish People's Republic]], up to 1989). During the absolute rule of the [[PZPR]], a private car was considered a luxury item, due to limited availability and low salaries. In 1971 there were only 556,000 passenger cars in Poland.<ref>{{cite journal | first = Marcin | last = Zaremba | url = http://archiwum.polityka.pl/art/good-bye-gierek,395534.html| title = Good bye, Gierek! | journal = [[Polityka]] | volume = 45 | year = 2004 | issue = 2477 | page = 79 | language = Polish }}</ref> In a top-down [[planned economy]], decisions on whether a state-owned factory could produce a car were taken on political and not just economic grounds. The authorities themselves initially did not find the idea of private cars attractive. The first relatively cheap Polish car was the [[FSO Syrena|Syrena]], but it was outdated and its production was limited. Limited numbers of cars were also imported from other Eastern Bloc countries. It was difficult to buy a Western car because the [[Polish z\u0142oty]], like other currencies in communist states, was not convertible to Western funds and there was no free market in the country.\n\nThus, the PF 126p was intended to be the first real, popular and affordable car, to provide mobility for ordinary families. The licence was bought after the rise to power of a new [[PZPR]] leader, [[Edward Gierek]], who wanted to gain popular favour by increasing consumer spending after the austerity period under [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Gomu\u0142ka]]. Despite the fact that it was a very small [[city car]], it was the only choice for most families, filling the role of a [[family car]]. During holidays, it was common to see families of four driving PF-126s abroad with huge suitcases on a [[roof rack]]; sightings of PF-126s towing a small [[:pl:Niewiad\u00f3w N126|Niewiad\u00f3w N126]] caravan especially designed for the PF 126 were also occasionally reported.<ref name=zakrz/> PF 126p production, however, was not sufficient and the PF 126p was on sale with a waiting list. Usually families had to wait a couple of years to buy a car.<ref name=zakrz>Zakrzewski, Adam (2010). pp.72-83</ref> A coupon for a car could also be given by the authorities based on merit.\n\n== Nicknames ==\n\nIn Poland it is called ''Maluch'', which literally means \"small one\" or toddler,<ref>{{cite book|last=Turnock|first=David|title=The East European economy in context: communism and transition|year=1997|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-0-415-08626-4|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qej-6dP5e74C&pg=PA307&dq=126p+Maluch|accessdate=6 November 2010|page=307}}</ref> as well as ''ma\u0142y Fiat'' (\"small Fiat\"), in contrast to [[Fiat 125p]], called ''du\u017cy Fiat'' (\"big Fiat\").<ref>{{cite book|last=Swan|first=Oscar E.|title=Intermediate Polish|year=1986|publisher=Slavica Publishers|isbn=978-0-89357-165-8|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mD8IAAAAIAAJ&q=ma\u0142y+Fiat&dq=ma\u0142y+Fiat|accessdate=6 November 2010|page=71}}</ref> In some regions, it is also called ''Kaszlak'',<ref>{{cite book|last=Czeszewski|first=Maciej|title=S\u0142ownik polszczyzny potocznej|year=2006|publisher=Wydawn. Naukowe PWN|isbn=978-83-01-14631-3|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xCUZAQAAIAAJ&q=Kaszlak+Fiat+126&dq=Kaszlak+Fiat+126|accessdate=6 November 2010|page=129|language=Polish}}</ref> literally \"cougher\" (derived from ''[[wikt:kaszel#Polish|kaszel]]'', \"[[cough]]\", as its engine's sound resembles a cough when it is started).\n[[File:Cuba, Havana, FIAT 126p Polski.jpg|thumb|Fiat 126p in [[Havana]], Cuba, March 2014]]\nIn [[Albania]] and [[Kosovo]] it is known as ''Kikirez'', in Serbian meaning a \"little rooster\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.autocentrum.pl/skarbnica-wiedzy/fiat/126p-maluch/|title=Fiat 126p \"Maluch\" \u2022 Skarbnica wiedzy \u2022 AutoCentrum.pl|website=www.autocentrum.pl|accessdate=12 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Serbian language|Serbian]], [[Croatian language|Croatian]] and [[Bosnian language|Bosnian]] it is known as ''Peglica'' (meaning \"little [[Iron (appliance)|iron]]\").<ref>{{cite book|last=Labourdette|first=Jean-Paul, Dominique Auzias|title=Przewodnik Chorwacja|year=2007|publisher=Petit Fute|isbn=978-83-60496-20-6|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=h11ayWWvvl8C&pg=PA222&dq=126+Peglica|accessdate=6 November 2010|page=222|language=Polish}}</ref>\n\nIn Slovene the 126 is also called ''Bolha'' (\"[[flea]]\"),<ref>{{cite book|last=Weiss|first=Peter|title=Slovar govorov Zadre\u010dke doline med Gornjim gradom in Nazarjami|year=1998|publisher=Znanstvenoraziskovalni center SAZU|isbn=978-961-6182-47-8|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=I5jlAAAAMAAJ&q=Fiat+126+Bolha&dq=Fiat+126+Bolha|accessdate=6 November 2010|page=206}}</ref> Pi\u010di-poki (loosely translated as \"fast-and-loud\") or ''Kalimero'' on [[Slovenian Littoral|Slovenian coast]] after a cartoon character [[Calimero]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://forums.bistudio.com/forums/topic/20164-fiat-126/|title=Fiat 126|website=Bohemia Interactive Forums|accessdate=12 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Hungarian language|Hungarian]], it is known as ''kispolszki'' (\"Little Polish\", while the [[Polski Fiat 125p|125p]] is the ''nagypolszki'', meaning \"Big Polish\"), ''kispol\u00e1k'' (\"Little [[Poles|Pole]]\") or ''kisp''\u00f3''k'' (\"Little spider\"); also, the car was nicknamed ''eg\u00e9rkamion'', meaning \"a mouse's truck\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vezess.hu/vezetunk/2015/03/18/igazi-gyongyszem-lanctalpas-kispolak/|title=Igazi gy\u00f6ngyszem \u2013 L\u00e1nctalpas kispol\u00e1k|date=18 March 2015|publisher=|accessdate=12 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn Germany the Fiat 126 was known as the ''Bambino'', the Italian word for child.<ref>{{cite book|last=Deiss|first=Richard|title=Silberling und B\u00fcgeleisen - 1000 Spitznamen in Transport und Verkehr und was dahinter steckt|year=2010|publisher=Ausstattung/Bilder|isbn=978-3-8391-6269-9|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=L0Tc7aZUh3QC&pg=PA50&dq=Fiat+126+Bambino|accessdate=6 November 2010|page=50|language=German}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Cuba]] it is known as the \"Polqi\" or \"Polaquito\", meaning \"Little [[Poles|Pole]]\" or \"Little Polish man\", and in [[Chile]] as \"Bototo\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slaskie.naszemiasto.pl/artykul/fiat-126p-podbil-kube-nazywaja-go-polaquito,3850064,artgal,t,id,tm.html|title=Fiat 126p podbi\u0142 Kub\u0119... nazywaj\u0105 go \"polaquito\"|first=P.|last=Ciastek|date=7 September 2016|publisher=|accessdate=12 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VfypBAAAQBAJ&pg=PT212&lpg=PT212&dq=bototo+fiat&source=bl&ots=m3cfUQZex-&sig=bIOMsL8AVd4DFjdG5comX0u93IA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi4_e2DhYPVAhVDybwKHUkVCsY4ChDoAQhVMAY#v=onepage&q=bototo+fiat&f=false|title=Maluch. Biografia|first=Przemys\u0142aw|last=Semczuk|date=1 October 2014|publisher=Otwarte|accessdate=12 July 2017|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* {{cite book |title=Polski FIAT 126P: technika jazdy, obs\u0142uga i usprawnienia |first=Zbigniew |last=Klimecki |first2=Roman |last2=Podolak |publisher=Wydawnictwa Komunikacji i \u0141\u0105czno\u015bci |year=1982 |isbn=978-83-206-0092-6 |language=Polish}}\n* {{cite book |title=Fiat 126p Ma\u0142y Wielki Samoch\u00f3d |first=Aleksander |last=Sowa |publisher=Z\u0142ot My\u015bli |year=2008 |isbn=978-83-7582-550-3 |language=Polish}}\n* Zakrzewski, Adam (2010) {{in lang|pl}}. ''Auto-moto PRL: w\u0142adcy dr\u00f3g i poboczy'', Demart, Warsaw, {{ISBN|978-83-7427-484-5}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{dmoz|Recreation/Autos/Makes_and_Models/Fiat|Fiat}}\n{{Fiat}}\n{{Early European Fiat vehicles}}\n{{Modern European Fiat vehicles}}\n\n[[Category:Fiat vehicles|126]]\n[[Category:Rear-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:Rear-engined vehicles]]\n[[Category:City cars]]\n[[Category:Hatchbacks]]\n[[Category:1970s cars]]\n[[Category:1980s cars]]\n[[Category:1990s cars]]\n[[Category:2000s cars]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 1972]]\n[[Category:Science and technology in Poland]]\n", "name_user": "842U", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fiat_126"}
{"title_page": "Red-tailed tropicbird", "text_new": "{{short description|seabird of the tropical Indian and Pacific Oceans}}\n{{redirect|Amokura|text=For the New Zealand training ship, see [[NZS Amokura]]}}\n{{featured article}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| name = Red-tailed tropicbird\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=IUCN>{{cite iucn |author1= [[BirdLife International]]|title= ''Phaethon rubricauda'' |volume= 2018|year= 2018|journal= [[IUCN Red List of Threatened Species]] |publisher= [[IUCN]]|page= e.T22696641A132586227 |doi= 10.2305/IUCN.UK.2018-2.RLTS.T22696641A132586227.en |url= https://www.iucnredlist.org/species/22696641/132586227 |access-date= 3 December 2019}}</ref>\n| image = Red-tailed Tropicbird RWD2.jpg\n| image_caption = In flight, Kilauea Point, Kauai, Hawaii \n| taxon = Phaethon rubricauda\n| authority = [[Pieter Boddaert|Boddaert]], 1783\n|synonyms_ref = <ref name=checklistNZ>{{cite book | last= Gill | first=B.J.| last2= Bell| first2= B.D.| last3=Chambers| first3=G.K.| last4=Medway| first4=D.G.| last5=Palma| first5= R.L.| last6= Scofield| first6= R.P.| last7=Tennyson| first7= A.J.D.| last8= Worthy| first8= T.H. | year=2010| title= Checklist of the birds of New Zealand, Norfolk and Macquarie Islands, and the Ross Dependency, Antarctica | edition= 4th | location=Wellington, New Zealand | publisher=Te Papa Press and Ornithological Society of New Zealand |pages =136\u201337 | isbn=9781877385599}}</ref>\n|synonyms =''Phaethon phoenicuros'' <small>Gmelin 1789</small><br> \n''Pha\u00ebthon novae-hollandiae'' <small>Brandt, 1840</small>\n| range_map = Redtailedtropicbirdrge.png\n| range_map_caption = Range (in pink)\n}}\n\nThe '''red-tailed tropicbird''' (''Phaethon rubricauda'') is a [[seabird]] native to tropical parts of the [[Indian Ocean|Indian]] and [[Pacific Ocean|Pacific Oceans]]. One of three closely related species of [[tropicbird]] (Phaethontidae), it was described by [[Pieter Boddaert]] in 1783. Superficially resembling a [[tern]] in appearance, it has almost all-white plumage with a black mask and a red bill. The sexes have similar plumage. As referenced in the common name, adults have red {{birdgloss|tail streamers}} that are about twice their body length. Four subspecies are recognised, but there is evidence of [[Cline (biology)|clinal]] variation in body size\u2014with smaller birds in the north and larger in the south\u2014and hence no grounds for subspecies.\n\nThe red-tailed tropicbird eats fish\u2014mainly [[flying fish]] and squid\u2014after catching them by plunge-diving into the ocean. [[Nesting instinct|Nesting]] takes place in loose [[bird colony|colonies]] on oceanic islands; the nest itself is a [[Bird nest#Scrape|scrape]] found on a cliff face, in a crevice, or on a sandy beach. A single egg is laid, then is incubated by both sexes for about six weeks. The parents make long food-foraging trips of about 150 hours during incubation, but once the chick has hatched, the parents specialize their foraging: one forages for the chick for a few hours at a time, while the other makes much longer trips to feed themselves.\n\nThis bird is considered to be a [[least-concern species]] according to the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] (IUCN), though it is adversely affected by human contact. Rats and feral cats prey on eggs and young at nesting sites. The bird's tail streamers were once prized by some [[Native Hawaiians|Hawaiian]] and [[M\u0101ori people|Maori]] peoples.\n\n==Taxonomy==\nThe British naturalist [[Joseph Banks|Sir Joseph Banks]] encountered the red-tailed tropicbird on the Pacific Ocean in March 1769 on [[First voyage of James Cook|James Cook's first voyage]], noting that it was a different species to the familiar [[red-billed tropicbird]]. He gave it the name ''Phaeton erubescens''.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Banks|first1=Sir Joseph|title=Journal of the Right Hon. Sir Joseph Banks Bart., K.B., P.R.S.: During Captain Cook's First Voyage in HMS Endeavour in 1768\u201371 to Terra Del Fuego, Otahite, New Zealand, Australia, the Dutch East Indies, Etc.|date=1896|publisher=Macmillan | location=London |pages=65, 67|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/38211333 }}</ref> It was the French polymath [[Georges-Louis Leclerc, Comte de Buffon]] who formally [[species description|described]] the species in his ''Histoire Naturelle des Oiseaux'' in 1781, noting it was a native of  [[Isle de France (Mauritius)|Isle de France]] (Mauritius).<ref>{{ cite book | last=Buffon | first=Georges-Louis Leclerc de | author-link=Georges-Louis Leclerc, Comte de Buffon | year=1781 | title=Histoire Naturelle des Oiseaux | volume=Volume 16 | place=Paris | publisher=De L'Imprimerie Royale | pages=116\u201318| chapter=Le Paille en Queue a Brins Rouges | language=French  | chapter-url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/42296359}}</ref> The bird was also illustrated in a hand-coloured plate engraved by [[Fran\u00e7ois-Nicolas Martinet]] in the ''Planches Enlumin\u00e9es D'Histoire Naturelle'' which was produced under the supervision of [[Edme-Louis Daubenton]] to accompany Buffon's text.<ref>{{ cite book | last1=Buffon | first1=Georges-Louis Leclerc de | author1-link=Georges-Louis Leclerc, Comte de Buffon | last2=Martinet | first2=Fran\u00e7ois-Nicolas | author2-link=Fran\u00e7ois-Nicolas Martinet | last3=Daubenton | first3=Edme-Louis  | author3-link=Edme-Louis Daubenton | last4=Daubenton | first4=Louis-Jean-Marie | author4-link=Louis-Jean-Marie Daubenton | year=1765\u20131783 | chapter=Paille en Queue d'Isle de France | title=Planches Enlumin\u00e9es D'Histoire Naturelle | volume=Volume 10 | place=Paris | publisher=De L'Imprimerie Royale | at=Plate 979 | chapter-url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/35223703}}</ref>  Buffon did not include a scientific name with his description but in 1783 the Dutch naturalist [[Pieter Boddaert]] coined the [[binomial name]] ''Phaethon rubricauda'' in his catalogue of the ''Planches Enlumin\u00e9es''.<ref>{{cite book |last= Boddaert |first= Pieter |year= 1783 |title= Table des Planches Enlumin\u00e9ez d'Histoire Naturelle, de M. d'Aubenton. Avec les denominations de M.M. de Buffon, Brisson, Edwards, Linnaeus et Latham, prec\u00e9d\u00e9 d'une Notice des Principaux Ouvrages Zoologiques enlumin\u00e9es |location= Utrecht |publisher= Boddaert |page= 57 |url= https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/27822677 |url-status= live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20171107175333/https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/27822677 |archivedate= 2017-11-07 }}</ref> The genus name is derived from [[Ancient Greek]] ''phaethon'', \"sun\", while the species epithet comes from the Latin words ''ruber'' \"red\" and ''cauda'' \"tail\".{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=935}}<!-- cites previous 1.5 sentences --> English ornithologist [[John Latham (ornithologist)|John Latham]] wrote about the red-tailed tropicbird in 1785 in his ''General Synopsis of Birds'', recording it as common in Mauritius and the South Pacific. He also reported a black-billed tropicbird collected from [[Palmerston Island]] that ended up in Banks' collection.<ref>{{cite book | last=Latham | first=John | year=1785 | title=A General Synopsis of Birds | volume=3 | pages=619\u201321 | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/40079445 | publisher=Benj. White | location=London, United Kingdom | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180227090337/https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/40079445 | archivedate=2018-02-27 }}</ref> Latham did not give them binomial names, however. It was left to German naturalist [[Johann Friedrich Gmelin]] to describe the species, which he did as ''Phaeton phoenicuros'' and ''P. melanorhynchos'' respectively in the 13th edition of ''[[Systema Naturae]]'' in 1788.<ref>{{cite book|last=Gmelin|first=Johann Friedrich|title=Systema naturae per regna tria naturae :secundum classes, ordines, genera, species, cum characteribus, differentiis, synonymis, locis /Caroli a Linn\u00e9|publisher=Impensis Georg. Emanuel. Beer|location=Leipzig, Germany|date=1788|volume=1 Part 2|pages=582\u201383|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/2656075|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160416182212/http://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/2656075|archivedate=2018-02-27}}</ref> Latham later described this black-billed specimen as the New Holland tropicbird,<ref>{{cite book | last=Latham | first=John | year=1824 | title=A General History of Birds | volume=10 | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/40978190 | page=448 | location=Winchester | publisher=Jacob and Johnson | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180227090337/https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/40978190 | archivedate=2018-02-27 }}</ref> giving it the name ''Phaethon novae-hollandiae''.<ref name=rothschild/>\n\nThe British naturalist [[Walter Rothschild, 2nd Baron Rothschild|Walter Rothschild]] reviewed the described names and specimens in 1900 and concluded that the original use of ''P. erubescens'' was a ''[[nomen nudum]]''. He concluded that the populations of [[Lord Howe Island|Lord Howe]], [[Norfolk Island|Norfolk]] and [[Kermadec Islands]] belonged to a distinct subspecies which he named ''P. rubicauda erubescens'', due to their larger overall size, more robust bill and prominent reddish tinge to their plumage. He also classified ''P. melanorhynchus'' and ''P. novae-hollandiae'' as juveniles.<ref name=rothschild>{{cite book | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/44039603 | title=The avifauna of Laysan and the neighbouring islands : with a complete history to date of the birds of the Hawaiian possessions | last=Rothschild | first=Walter | year=1900 | location=London | publisher=R.H. Porter | page=296 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180227090337/https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/44039603 | archivedate=2018-02-27 }}</ref> The Australian amateur ornithologist [[Gregory Mathews]] then applied the name ''P. rubicauda roseotinctus'' to Rothschild's ''P. rubicauda erubescens''.<ref>{{cite journal | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/40498721 | journal=Bulletin of the British Ornithologists' Club | year=1923 | volume=46 | page=60 | title=On some changes in names | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180227090337/https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/40498721 | archivedate=2018-02-27 }}</ref>\n\n\"Red-tailed tropicbird\" has been designated the official name by the [[International Ornithologists' Union]] (IOC).<ref name=\"ioclist\">{{cite web | editor1-last=Gill | editor1-first=Frank | editor1-link=Frank Gill (ornithologist) | editor2-last=Donsker | editor2-first=David | year=2017 | title=Grebes, flamingos, tropicbirds | work=World Bird List Version 7.1 | url=http://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/grebes/ | publisher=International Ornithologists' Union | accessdate=9 February 2018 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170904110252/http://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/grebes/ | archivedate=4 September 2017 }}</ref> Other common names include red-tailed bos'nbird or silver bos'nbird, the names derived from the semblance of the tail feathers to a boatswain's marlin spikes, and strawtail.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=935}} The New Zealand [[M\u0101ori people|M\u0101ori]] call it ''amokura'',<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |last=Williams |first=Herbert W. |title=Amokura |dictionary=A Dictionary of the Maori Language |date=1971 |publisher=A. R. Shearer, Government Printer |location=Wellington |edition=7th}}</ref> and the [[native Hawaiians]] ''koa{{okina}}e {{okina}}ula''.<ref name=hawaii>{{cite web | url= https://dlnr.hawaii.gov/wildlife/files/2013/09/Fact-Sheet-Red-tailed-Tropicbird.pdf | title= Koa\u2018e \u2018ula or Red-tailed Tropicbird | work= Hawaii\u2019s Comprehensive Wildlife Conservation Strategy | date= 1 October 2005 | accessdate= 19 February 2018 | url-status= live | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20170207132552/http://dlnr.hawaii.gov/wildlife/files/2013/09/Fact-Sheet-Red-tailed-Tropicbird.pdf | archivedate= 7 February 2017 }}</ref>\n\nIts closest relative is the [[white-tailed tropicbird]] (''P. lepturus''), the split between their ancestors taking place about four million years ago.<ref name=\"KennedySpencer2004\">{{cite journal|last1=Kennedy|first1=Martyn|last2=Spencer|first2=Hamish G|title=Phylogenies of the frigatebirds (Fregatidae) and tropicbirds (Phaethonidae), two divergent groups of the traditional order Pelecaniformes, inferred from mitochondrial DNA sequences|journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution|volume=31|issue=1|year=2004|pages=31\u201338|pmid=15019606|doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2003.07.007}}</ref>\n\nFour subspecies are recognised by the IOC:<ref name=\"ioclist\"/>\n\n*''P. r. rubricauda'' Boddaert, 1783 the nominate subspecies, from the western Indian Ocean. Subsequent specimens from the [[Cocos (Keeling) Islands]] were allocated to this [[taxon]].<ref name=tarburton89/>\n*''P. r. westralis'' Mathews, 1912 from the eastern Indian Ocean. Mathews described it as separate on account of its larger wings.<ref>{{cite journal | last= Mathews | first= G.M. | year= 1912 | title= Additions and corrections to my Reference List to the Birds of Australia | journal= Austral Avian Records | volume= 1 | pages= 81\u2013103 [88] | url= https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/33339667 | url-status= live | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180227090335/https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/33339667 | archivedate= 2018-02-27 }}</ref> More extensive analysis in 1989 showed that the wing and beak size overlap between this and the nominate subspecies, leaving intensity of colour as the only distinguishing feature.<ref name=tarburton89/>\n*''P. r. roseotinctus'' Mathews, 1926 from the southwestern Pacific Ocean, including populations on Kermadec, Lord Howe, Norfolk and [[Raine Island]]s.<ref name=tarburton89/>\n*''P. r. melanorhynchos''  Gmelin, 1789 from the western, central and southern Pacific Ocean, including populations on the Cook Islands, Tonga, Samoa, the [[Marquesas Islands|Marquesas]] and the Society Islands.<ref name=tarburton89/>\n\nThe ornithologist Mike Tarburton reviewed the known subspecies in 1989 and concluded that none were valid, noting that there was a [[Cline (biology)|clinal]] change in size in the species: those from [[Kure Atoll]] in the North Pacific being the smallest; ranging to those from the Kermadec Islands in the South Pacific being the largest. He also noted that the pink colouration was more intense in new plumage and faded after a few years in museum specimens.<ref name=tarburton89>{{cite journal | url=https://notornis.osnz.org.nz/system/files/Notornis_36_1.pdf#page=43 | last=Tarburton | first=Michael Kenneth | year=1989 | volume=36 | issue=1 | journal=Notornis | title=Subspeciation in the red-tailed tropicbird | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171213201604/https://notornis.osnz.org.nz/system/files/Notornis_36_1.pdf#page=43 | archivedate=2017-12-13 }}</ref>\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Starr 080607-7135 Plumeria rubra.jpg|thumb|left|Closeup of head showing comma-shaped markings]]\n\nThe red-tailed tropicbird measures {{convert|95|to|104|cm|in|abbr=on}} on average, which includes the {{convert|35|cm|in|abbr=on}} {{birdgloss|tail streamers}}, and weighs around {{convert|800|g|oz|sigfig=1|abbr=on}}. It has a wingspan of {{convert|111|to|119|cm|in|abbr=on}}. It has a streamlined but solid build with almost all-white [[plumage]],{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=935}} often with a pink tinge.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=936}} The sexes are similar in plumage.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=935}} A dark brown comma-shaped stripe extends back from the [[Lore (anatomy)|lores]], through and over the eyes and reaching the ear [[Covert feather|coverts]].{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=936}} The iris is dark brown.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=943}} The bill is bright red, slightly paler at the base and black around the nostrils. The legs and base of the toes are pale blue-mauve, while the webbing and rest of the toes are black.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=943}} The white feathers of the head and rump have concealed dark brown bases, while those of the mantle, back, tail [[Flight feather#Rectrices|rectrices]] and tail coverts have dark brown shaft bases. The two long tail feathers are orange or red with white bases for around a tenth of their length,{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=942}} and can be hard to see when the bird is flying. The white wings are marked by dark [[Chevron (insignia)|chevron]]-shaped patches on the [[Flight feather#Tertial|tertials]], and the dark shafts of the [[Flight feather#Primaries|primary]] flight feathers are visible.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=936}} The pink tinge is often more pronounced in the [[Flight feather#Remiges|remiges]] of the upper wing.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=942}} Moulting takes place outside the breeding season, the streamers being replaced before the rest of the feathers. Streamers are replaced at any time, one growing while the other is shed, and old streamers may litter the area around a breeding colony.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=943}}\n\nNewly-hatched chicks are covered in thin, long, grey-white [[Down feather|down]], which is paler on the head. The lores are bare. The down is greyer in older chicks. The primaries, rectrices and scapulars are evident in the third week, and chicks are mostly feathered with residual down on underparts and under the wings after six weeks, and fully feathered by 11 weeks.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=942}} Juvenile birds have a glossy white forehead, chin, throat and underparts,{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=943}} and prominent black barring and scaling on their crown, nape, mantle, back, rump and upper wing coverts.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=936}} Their bills are blackish grey with a light blue-grey base, and grey legs and feet.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=943}}\n\nIn Australian waters the red-tailed tropicbird could be confused with the [[silver gull]] (''Chroicocephalus novaehollandiae'') or various tern species, though it is larger and heavier-set, with a wedge-shaped tail. Its red bill and more wholly white wings distinguish it from the adult white-tailed tropicbird. Immature red-tailed tropicbirds likewise can be distinguished from immature white-tailed tropicbirds by their partly red rather than yellow bills.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=936}}<!-- cites previous two sentences -->\n\nThe red-tailed tropicbird is generally silent while flying. Aside from during courtship displays, birds may give a short greeting squawk to their mate when arriving or leaving the nest. Birds give a low growling call as a defence call, and young chatter repetitively as a begging call\u2014made whenever the parents are nearby.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=941}}\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nThe red-tailed tropicbird ranges across the southern Indian, and western and central Pacific Oceans, from the African coast to Indonesia, the waters around the southern reaches of Japan, across to Chile,{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=937}} and the [[Hawaiian Islands]], where they are more common on the northwestern islands.<ref name=vanderwerf07>{{cite journal | last=Vanderwerf | first=Eric A. | first2=Lindsay C. | last2=Young | title=The Red-billed Tropicbird ''Phaethon rubricauda'' in Hawaii, with notes on interspecific behavior of tropicbirds | journal=Marine Ornithology | volume=35 | year=2007 | pages=81\u201384 | url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Lindsay_Young/publication/237377707_The_Red-billed_Tropicbird_Phaethon_rubricauda_in_Hawaii_with_notes_on_interspecific_behavior_of_tropicbirds/links/00b7d52c271783ce39000000.pdf | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180217202830/https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Lindsay_Young/publication/237377707_The_Red-billed_Tropicbird_Phaethon_rubricauda_in_Hawaii_with_notes_on_interspecific_behavior_of_tropicbirds/links/00b7d52c271783ce39000000.pdf | archivedate=2018-02-17 }}</ref> There are large breeding colonies on [[Europa Island|Europa]],<ref>{{cite journal | last=Le Corre | first= M.| last2=Jouventin | first2=  P. | year=1997 | title= Ecological significance and conservation priorities of Europa Island (western Indian Ocean), with special reference to seabirds | journal= Revue d'Ecologie (Terre et Vie) | volume=52| pages=205\u201320 }}</ref> [[Aldabra]]<ref>{{cite journal | last=Diamond | first= A. W. | year=1975| volume=92 | issue=1 |pages= 16\u201339 | title=The biology of tropicbirds at Aldabra Atoll, Indian Ocean | journal= Auk | url=https://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/auk/v092n01/p0016-p0039.pdf | doi=10.2307/4084415| jstor= 4084415 }}</ref> and [[Christmas Island]] in the Indian Ocean, with smaller colonies in [[Madagascar]]\u2014where it nests on the tiny island of Nosy Ve<ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=jMjjDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA118 | page=118 | title=Wildlife of Madagascar | first1=Ken | last1=Behrens | first12=Keith | last2=Barnes | publisher=Princeton University Press | year=2016 | isbn=9781400880676 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180220033155/https://books.google.com.au/books?id=jMjjDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA118 | archivedate=2018-02-20 }}</ref>\u2014the Seychelles, and Mauritius.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=937}}  In Australia, it nests on  [[Queensland]]'s coral islands (including Raine Island and [[Lady Elliot Island]]), and Ashmore Reef and Rottnest Island off [[Western Australia]], as well as Sugarloaf Rock at Cape Naturaliste and Busselton on the Western Australian coastline itself, and the offshore territories of the Cocos (Keeling) Islands, Norfolk and Lord Howe islands. In New Zealand territory it  breeds on the Kermadec Islands.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=938}} Elsewhere in the Pacific it breeds in Fiji, New Caledonia, French Polynesia, Hawaii{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=937}}\u2014with a large colony on Kure Atoll<ref name=woodward72/>\u2014the Cook Islands, Pitcairn Island, and islands off Japan and Chile.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=937}}\n\nIt frequents areas of ocean with water temperatures from {{convert|24|to|30|C|F|abbr=on}} and salinity under 35% in the southern hemisphere and 33.5% in the northern hemisphere. In the Pacific Ocean, the southern boundary of its range runs along the {{convert|22|C|F|abbr=on}} summer surface isotherm.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=936}} The warm waters of the [[Leeuwin Current]] facilitate the species nesting at [[Cape Leeuwin]] in southwestern Australia, yet is only a rare visitor to New South Wales at corresponding latitudes on the Australian east coast.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=936}}\n\nIt is an occasional visitor to [[Palau]], breeding being recorded from the [[Southwest Islands (Palau)|Southwest Islands]],<ref>{{cite journal| journal=Micronesica| last=VanderWerf| first=E.A.| first2=G.J.| last2=Wiles| first3=A.P.| last3=Marshall| first4=M.| last4=Knecht| year=2006| title=Observations of migrants and other birds in Palau, April\u2013May 2005, including the first Micronesian record of a Richard\u2019s Pipit| volume=39| issue=1| pages=11\u201329| url=http://micronesica.org/sites/default/files/2_vanderwerf-palau.pdf| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160302195732/http://micronesica.org/sites/default/files/2_vanderwerf-palau.pdf| archivedate=2016-03-02}}</ref> and was first recorded from Guam in 1992.<ref>{{cite journal | journal=Micronesica | last=Wiles | first=Gary J. | last2=Beck, Jr | first2=Robert E. | last3=Aguon | first3=Celestino F. | year=1993 | title=Recent bird records for the southern Mariana Islands, with notes on a colony of Black Noddies on Cocos Island, Guam | volume=26 | issue=2 | pages=199\u2013215 | url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Gary_Wiles/publication/263275985_Recent_bird_records_for_the_southern_Mariana_Islands_with_notes_on_a_colony_of_Black_Noddies_on_Cocos_Island_Guam/links/0c96053be129d86a0c000000.pdf | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180218210306/https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Gary_Wiles/publication/263275985_Recent_bird_records_for_the_southern_Mariana_Islands_with_notes_on_a_colony_of_Black_Noddies_on_Cocos_Island_Guam/links/0c96053be129d86a0c000000.pdf | archivedate=2018-02-18 }}</ref> It is an uncommon vagrant to New Zealand proper, where it has been recorded from the northern reaches of North Island, especially [[Three Kings Islands]].<ref name=checklistNZ/> It is a very rare vagrant to North America, with records from California and [[Vancouver Island]].<ref>{{cite book | title=Rare Birds of North America | url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=-YqGAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA111 | page=111 | first=Steve N. G. | last=Howell | first2=Ian | last2=Lewington | first3=Will | last3=Russell | publisher=Princeton University Press | year=2014 | isbn=9781400848072 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180210002259/https://books.google.com.au/books?id=-YqGAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA111 | archivedate=2018-02-10 }}</ref>\n\nThe birds disperse widely after breeding. Evidence suggests birds in the Indian Ocean follow prevailing winds westwards, young individuals banded in Sumatra and Sugarloaf Reserve, Western Australia, being recovered at Mauritius and Reunion respectively.<ref>{{cite journal | url =https://www.researchgate.net/publication/248900262_Transoceanic_dispersion_of_the_Red-tailed_Tropicbird_in_the_Indian_Ocean | title= Transoceanic dispersion of the Red-tailed Tropicbird in the Indian Ocean | first=  Matthieu | last=Le Corre |first2= Marc | last2=Salamolard |first3=Marie Claude | last3=Portier | year=2003| journal=Emu | volume=103| issue=2| pages=183\u201384 | doi=10.1071/MU02026}}</ref> Banding on Kure Atoll suggests birds in the North Pacific disperse in an easterly direction, following prevailing winds there.<ref name=woodward72/> Strong winds can blow them inland on occasions, which explains some sighting records away from the coast and their preferred habitats.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=935}}\n\n==Behaviour==\nThe red-tailed tropicbird is a strong flyer, and walks on land with difficulty using a shuffling gait.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=935}}\n\n===Breeding===\n[[File:Red-tailed tropicbird (Phaethon rubricauda rubricauda) nesting.jpg|thumb|''P. r. rubricuada'' nesting on Nosy Ve]]\n\nThe red-tailed tropicbird is thought to be monogamous, pairs remaining bonded over successive breeding seasons, although such information as age at first breeding and pair-formation is not known.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=939}} It nests in loose colonies,<ref name=\"hbw\"/> on offshore islands and stacks, rocky cliffs, coral atolls and cays. It rarely nests on large bodies of land, though has done so in southern Western Australia.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=936}} The nest itself is a shallow [[Bird nest#Scrape|scrape]], in either shaded sand<ref name=\"HowellBartholomew1962\">{{cite journal|last1=Howell|first1=Thomas R.|last2=Bartholomew|first2=George A.|title=Temperature regulation in the red-tailed tropic bird and the red-footed booby|url=https://sora.unm.edu/node/101356|jstor=1365438|journal= Condor|volume=64|issue=1|year=1962|pages=6\u201318|doi=10.2307/1365438}}</ref> or a rocky crevice,<ref name=\"hbw\"/> or under a shrub. Because the red-tailed tropicbird does not walk well, it lands by flying into the wind, stalling and dropping to the ground. The nest is often located within {{convert|1|m|ft|spell=in}} of the edge of the shrub (or other shaded area) to minimise walking distance. The tropicbird often chooses shrubs with fewer stems for accessibility.<ref name=\"ClarkRicklefs1983\">{{Cite journal|  volume = 100| issue = 4| pages = 953\u2013959| last1 = Clark| first1 = L.| last2 = Ricklefs| first2 = R. E.| last3 = Schreiber| first3 = R. W.| title = Nest-site selection by the red-tailed tropicbird| journal=Auk|year = 1983 | url=https://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/auk/v100n04/p0953-p0959.pdf}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:Rtailedtropicbird8.jpg|thumb|left|Nesting and sheltering chick under its wing]]\n[[File:Phaethon rubricauda MHNT.ZOO.2010.11.2.14.jpg|thumb|Egg \u2013 [[Mus\u00e9um de Toulouse]]]]\n[[File:Starr 080612-8667 Calophyllum inophyllum.jpg|thumb|right| Young chick with down]]\n[[Image:Red-tailed tropic Bird (young).JPG|thumb|right|Young bird on Nosy Ve, Madagascar]]\n\nThe species is territorial to a degree, aggressively defending the nest site and pecking radius around it, commencing around three months before breeding.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=939}} Birds are more aggressive at crowded colonies, where numbers are large or suitable nest sites less common. They adopt a defence posture, which consists of raising the [[humerus|humeri]] up and bringing the wrists together, drawing the neck into the body and shaking the head sideways, fluffing up the head feathers and squawking. Bill-jabbing and fights can break out, the two combatants locking bills and wrestling for up to 90 minutes.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=940}}\n\n[[Sexual selection|Mate choice]] is likely to be based partially on the length of the tail streamers, a bird having longer tail streamers being more attractive as a mate. This tropicbird also probably mates [[Assortative mating|assortatively]] for tail streamer length, meaning mates likely have streamers of about equal length.<ref name=\"BolandDouble2004\">{{cite journal|last1=Boland|first1=C. R. J.|last2=Double|first2=M. C.|last3=Baker|first3=G. B.|title=Assortative mating by tail streamer length in red-tailed tropicbirds ''Phaethon rubricauda'' breeding in the Coral Sea|journal=Ibis|volume=146|issue=4|year=2004|pages=687\u2013690|doi=10.1111/j.1474-919x.2004.00310.x}}</ref>\n\nIn the leadup to breeding, males initiate an aerial courtship display of flying in large circles, alternating between gliding, short periods of rapid wing-beating, and low flight within a few metres of the water, while making sharp cackling calls. Initially flying in small groups, birds then pair off to repeat the display in pairs before bonding. Once pairs have established a nest, they do not perform the display.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=940}}\n\nThe timing of breeding depends on location; in some places, birds breed in a defined breeding season, whereas in others, there is none. South of the equator, the latter is likely to be true. On islands near the equator, laying usually occurs from June to November, the majority of chicks fledging around January to February.<ref name=\"hbw\"/> On Christmas Island, breeding takes place at different times on different parts of the island due to prevailing weather conditions.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=941}} Some birds may remain at the breeding site year-round.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=940}}\n\nThe female red-tailed tropicbird lays one egg, which both parents incubate<ref name=\"HowellBartholomew1962\"/> for 42 to 46 days.<ref name=\"hbw\">{{cite web |last1=Orta|first1=J.|last2=Christie|first2=David A.|last3=Jutglar|first3=F.|last4=Garcia|first4=E. F. J.|last5=Kirwan|first5=G. M.|last6=Boesman|first6=P.|editor1-last=del Hoyo |editor1-first=Josep |editor2-last=Elliott |editor2-first=Andrew |editor3-last=Sargatal |editor3-first=Jordi |editor4-last=Christie |editor4-first=David A. |editor5-last=de Juana |editor5-first=Eduardo |year=2018 |title=Red-tailed Tropicbird (''Phaethon rubricauda'') |work=Handbook of the Birds of the World Alive |url=https://www.hbw.com/species/red-tailed-tropicbird-phaethon-rubricauda |publisher=Lynx Edicions |location=Barcelona, Spain |accessdate=11 February 2018 |url-access=subscription }}</ref> The male generally takes the first turn on the egg after it is laid.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=940}} Ranging from {{convert|5.4|to|7.7|cm|in}} long (averaging between {{convert|6.3|and|6.8|cm|in}}, depending on location) and {{convert|4.5|to|4.8|cm|in}} wide, the oval eggs are pale tan with brown and red-black markings that are more prominent on the larger end.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=941}}\n\nBorn helpless and unable to move around ([[nidicolous]] and semi-[[altricial]]), the chicks are initially blind, opening their eyes after 2\u20133 days. Until they are a week old, they open their beak only upon touch, so the parents have to stroke the base of the bill to initiate feeding. Feeding takes place once or twice a day, generally around midday. They are constantly brooded by the parents until they are a week old, after which time they are sheltered under the parents\u2019 wings. They also rise up and gape at any nearby bird for food.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=942}}<!-- cites previous five sentences--> Both parents feed the young,{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=939}} by shoving its beak into the chick's gullet and then regurgitating food.<ref name=\"HowellBartholomew1969\">{{cite journal|last1=Howell|first1=Thomas R.|last2=Bartholomew|first2=George A.|title=Experiments on nesting behavior of the red-tailed tropicbird, ''Phaethon rubricauda''|journal=The Condor |url=https://sora.unm.edu/node/101836|volume=71|issue=2|year=1969|pages=113\u2013119|doi=10.2307/1366072}}</ref> Initially covered with grey or white down, they grow their first feathers\u2014scapulars\u2014at 16\u201320 days. Their feet and beaks grow rapidly, outpacing the rest of their bodies.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=942}}<!-- cites previous 2 sentences--> Chicks remain in the nest for 67 to 91 days until they fledge.<ref name=\"hbw\"/>\n\n===Feeding===\nThe red-tailed tropicbird is mostly a {{birdgloss|plunge diver}}, diving anywhere from an above-water height of {{convert|6|to|50|m|ft}},<ref name=\"hbw\"/> to a depth of about {{convert|4.5|m|ft}}, although this may change seasonally.<ref name=\"LeCorre1997\">{{cite journal|last1=Le Corre|first1=Matthieu|title=Diving depths of two tropical Pelecaniformes: The red-tailed tropicbird and the red-footed booby|journal=Condor|volume=99|issue=4|year=1997|pages=1004\u20131007 |doi=10.2307/1370157 | url=https://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/condor/v099n04/p1004-p1007.pdf |jstor=1370157}}</ref> When diving, it remains briefly submerged\u2014one study on Christmas Island came up with an average time of 26.6 seconds\u2014generally swallowing its prey before surfacing.<ref name=GH47>{{cite journal | title=The Normal Food of Tropic\u2010birds (''Pha\u00ebthon'' spp.) | last=Gibson\u2010Hill | first= C. A. | journal=Ibis | year= 1947 |volume=89| issue=4| pages=658\u201361 | doi=10.1111/j.1474-919X.1947.tb03901.x}}</ref> The red-tailed tropicbird sometimes catches [[flying fish]] in the air.<ref name=\"hbw\"/>\n\nDuring incubation, foraging trips are relatively long, with an average excursion taking about 153 hours. These trips are to very productive areas. After the chicks hatch, on the other hand, the parents adopt a strategy where one takes long trips (these averaging about 57 hours) for self feeding, and the other takes short trips (about three hours long) to feed the chicks. The [[Multimodal distribution|bimodality]] of the length of foraging trips is likely to be because of the fact that it is the optimal balance of self-feeding and provisioning for chicks.<ref name=\"SommerfeldHennicke2016\">{{cite journal|last1=Sommerfeld|first1=Julia|last2=Hennicke|first2=Janos C.|title=Comparison of trip duration, activity pattern and diving behaviour by red-tailed tropicbirds (''Phaethon rubricauda'') during incubation and chick-rearing|journal=Emu |volume=110|issue=1|year=2016|pages=78\u201386|doi=10.1071/MU09053}}</ref> On Christmas Island, birds generally forage far out to sea in the early morning and closer to shore in the afternoon.<ref name=GH47/>\n\nSquid and flying fish make up a large portion of this bird's diet, along with some crustaceans, depending on location.<ref name=\"hbw\"/> Fieldwork in the [[Mozambique Channel]] revealed the diet of birds there to be mostly fish by mass but equal numbers of fish and squid caught. Fish recorded include the [[mirrorwing flyingfish]] (''Hirundichthys speculiger'') and [[spotfin flyingfish]] (''Cheilopogon furcatus'') and several other unidentified species of the flying fish family Exocoetidae, the [[pompano dolphinfish]] (''Coryphaena equiselis'') and [[Mahi-mahi|common dolphinfish]] (''C. hippurus''), needleflish including the [[houndfish]] (''Tylosurus crocodilus''), and unidentified members of [[Hemiramphidae]], [[Scombridae]], and [[Carangidae]]. The [[Sthenoteuthis oualaniensis|purpleback flying squid]] (''Sthenoteuthis oualaniensis'') was by far the most common cephalopod eaten, followed by the [[common blanket octopus]] (''Tremoctopus violaceus'').<ref name=lecorre03>{{cite journal | title=Seasonal and inter-annual variation in the feeding ecology of a tropical oceanic seabird, the red-tailed tropicbird ''Phaethon rubricauda'' | first=M. | last=Le Corre | first2=Y. | last2=Cherel | first3=F. | last3=Lagarde | first4=H. | last4=Lorm\u00e9e | first5=P. | last5=Jouventin | journal=Marine Ecology Progress Series | volume=255 | year=2003 | pages=289\u2013301 | url=https://www.int-res.com/articles/meps2003/255/m255p289.pdf | jstor=24866967 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121210001950/https://www.int-res.com/articles/meps2003/255/m255p289.pdf | archivedate=2012-12-10 | doi=10.3354/meps255289}}</ref> A field study in Hawaii found flying fish dominated the prey species, the tropical two-wing flyingfish (''[[Exocoetus volitans]]'') and members of the genus ''[[Cypselurus]]'' prominent, followed by squid of the family [[Ommastrephidae]] including the purpleback flying squid and the glass squid (''[[Hyaloteuthis pelagica]]''), and carangid fish including the [[shortfin scad]] (''Decapterus macrosoma'').<ref>{{cite journal | title=Hawaiian Seabird Feeding Ecology | first= Craig S. |last=Harrison| first2= Thomas S. |last2=Hida | first3=Michael P. |last3=Seki | journal=Wildlife Monographs No. 85| year= 1983| pages= 3\u201371 [27\u201328]| jstor=3830593}}</ref> The red-tailed tropicbird has also been recorded eating [[porcupinefish]] (Diodontidae), although adults have been troubled when the victim fish inflates resulting in it being urgently regurgitated.<ref>{{cite journal | title=Comparative Feeding Ecology of Sea Birds of a Tropical Oceanic Island | journal=Bulletin of the Peabody Museum of Natural History Yale University | issue=24 | last1=Ashmole | first1=N. Philip | last2=Ashmole | first2=Myrtle | url=http://peabody.yale.edu/sites/default/files/documents/scientific-publications/ypmB24_1967.pdf | pages=1\u2013139 [19\u201326] | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160624104651/http://peabody.yale.edu/sites/default/files/documents/scientific-publications/ypmB24_1967.pdf | archivedate=2016-06-24 }}</ref>\n\nA strong flyer with large mouth and bill, the red-tailed tropicbird can carry relatively large prey for its size, parent birds commonly bearing dolphin fish that weighed 120 g\u201416% of their own weight\u2014to their chicks.<ref name=lecorre03/>\n\n===Temperature regulation===\nWhen incubating during the day in a shaded nest, this bird has an average temperature of {{convert|39|C|F}}, compared to its average temperature when incubating at night of {{convert|37.1|C|F}}. The difference is likely due to activity levels, as the air temperature during these times does not differ significantly with a bird in the nest. After flying, the average body temperature is {{convert|40.9|C|F}}. The temperature of the feet is always lower than that of the body temperature during flight, but always higher than the air temperature. Thus, the feet are likely used to dissipate heat during flight.<ref name=\"HowellBartholomew1962\"/>\n\n==Relationship with humans==\nThe red-tailed tropicbird's tail streamers were highly prized by the Maori. The [[Ng\u0101puhi]] tribe of the [[Northland Region]] would look for and collect them off dead or stray birds blown ashore after easterly gales, trading them for greenstone with tribes from the south.<ref>{{cite book | title=A History of the Birds of New Zealand | first= Walter Lawry | last= Buller | year=1888 | publisher=Self | location=Westminster, United Kingdom | page=187 | url=http://nzetc.victoria.ac.nz/tm/scholarly/tei-BulBird-t1-g1-t2-body1-d5-d2.html}}</ref> English naturalist [[Andrew Bloxam]] reported that the feathers were valued in Hawaii, where the locals would pull them off the birds as they nested.<ref>{{cite book | url=https://archive.org/details/voyagehmsblonde01bloxgoog | chapter=Appendix | page=[https://archive.org/details/voyagehmsblonde01bloxgoog/page/n297 251] | title=Voyage of H.M.S. Blonde to the Sandwich islands, in the years 1824\u20131825 |\n year=1826 | first=George Anson | last=Byron | publisher=John Murray, Albemarle-Street. | location=London }}</ref>\n\n==Status==\n[[File:Red-tailed tropic bird swarmed by yellow crazy ants.jpg|thumb|right|Being swarmed by yellow crazy ants, Johnston Atoll]]\nThe red-tailed tropicbird is classified as a [[least-concern species]] according to the [[IUCN]] on account of its large range of up to {{convert|20|e3km2|mi2}}.<ref name=\"IUCN\"/> The population in the eastern Pacific has been estimated to be as high as 80,000 birds with a minimum of 41,000 birds.<ref>{{ cite journal | last1=Spear | first1=Larry B. | last2=Ainley | first2=David G. | year=2005 | title=At-sea distributions and abundance of tropicbirds in the eastern Pacific | journal=Ibis  | volume=147 | issue=2 | pages=353\u201366 | doi=10.1111/j.1474-919x.2005.00411.x }}</ref> Around 9,000 birds breed on Europa Island,<ref>{{ cite journal | title=Breeding seasons of seabirds at Europa Island (southern Mozambique Channel) in relation to seasonal changes in the marine environment | last= Le Corre | first= Matthieu | journal=Journal of Zoology | year= 2001|volume=254 | issue= 2 |pages=239\u201349 | doi=10.1017/S0952836901000759}}</ref> and 9,000\u201312,000 breed on the Hawaiian islands.<ref name=hawaii/> Human presence generally affects the species adversely, by the destruction of habitat or introduction of pests.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=937}} Within Australia, it is classified as ''near threatened'', due to unexpected declines in some populations, the impact of humans, and the [[yellow crazy ant]] overrunning Christmas Island.<ref>{{cite book | url=http://155.187.2.69/biodiversity/threatened/publications/action/birds2000/pubs/rt-tropicbird.pdf | chapter=Red-tailed Tropicbird | pages=152\u201353 | title=The Action Plan For Australian Birds 2000 | first1=Stephen T. | last1=Garnett | first2=Gabriel M. | last2=Crowley | isbn=0- 6425-4683-5 | publisher=Environment Australia | location=Canberra, ACT | year=2000 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180220033251/http://155.187.2.69/biodiversity/threatened/publications/action/birds2000/pubs/rt-tropicbird.pdf | archivedate=2018-02-20 | access-date=2018-02-19 }}</ref> It is listed as vulnerable in New South Wales.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.environment.nsw.gov.au/determinations/RedtailedTropicbirdVulSpListing.htm | title=Red-tailed tropicbird \u2013 vulnerable species listing | author=NSW Threatened Species Scientific Committee | work=Determinations | date=28 February 2011 | accessdate=19 February 2018 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180210065337/http://www.environment.nsw.gov.au/determinations/RedtailedTropicbirdVulSpListing.htm | archivedate=10 February 2018 }}</ref>\n\nPredators recorded in Western Australia include large raptors such as the [[white-bellied sea eagle]] (''Haliaeetus leucogaster'') and the [[eastern osprey]] (''Pandion cristatus''); while silver gulls, and crows and ravens (''[[Corvus]]'' spp.) raid nests for eggs and young.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=942}} Vagrant [[red-billed tropicbird]]s (''P. aethereus'') have been implicated in egg loss of nests in Hawaii.<ref name=vanderwerf07/> Feral dogs and [[feral cat|cats]] prey on nesting birds on Christmas Island,{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=942}} while feral cats are a severe problem on Norfolk Island.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=942}} Rats have been a serious problem on Kure Atoll, causing heavy losses.<ref name=woodward72>{{cite journal | last=Woodward | first=Paul W. | year=1972 | title=The natural history of Kure Atoll, Northwestern Hawaiian Islands |journal =Atoll Research Bulletin | issue=164 | pages=1\u2013318 [78\u201379, 134\u201347] | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/39954202 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180227090337/https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/39954202 | archivedate=2018-02-27 }}</ref> Yellow crazy ants were discovered on [[Johnston Atoll]] in the north Pacific Ocean in 2010, hordes of which overrun nesting areas and can blind victims with their spray.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.audubon.org/magazine/july-august-2015/one-remote-islands-battle-against-acid | title=One Remote Island's Battle Against Acid-Spewing Ants | first=Alisa | last=Opar | date=July\u2013August 2015 | accessdate=19 February 2018 | work=Audubon Magazine | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180220033443/http://www.audubon.org/magazine/july-august-2015/one-remote-islands-battle-against-acid | archivedate=20 February 2018 }}</ref>\n\nAlso on Johnston Atoll, the [[Johnston Atoll Chemical Agent Disposal System]] (JACADS) was burning stockpiled chemical weapons until 2000.  It was studied over eight years to see if there were effects from potential contaminants. There appeared to be no impact on survival during the study period, although young birds from downwind of the plant were less likely to return there than those upwind of the plant\u2014possibly due to the more intact vegetation at the latter site.<ref>{{cite journal | year=2004 | journal=Animal Biodiversity and Conservation | title=Dispersal and survival rates of adult and juvenile Red-tailed tropicbirds (''Phaethon rubricauda'') exposed to potential contaminants | last=Schreiber | first=E. A. | last2=Doherty | first2=P. F. Jr. | last3=Schenk | first3=G. A | volume=27.1 | pages=531\u201340 | url=http://abc.museucienciesjournals.cat/files/ABC-27-1-pp-531-540.pdf | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171202094603/http://abc.museucienciesjournals.cat/files/ABC-27-1-pp-531-540.pdf | archivedate=2017-12-02 }}</ref>\n\n==References== \n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Cited text===\n* {{cite book |editor1-last=Marchant |editor1-first=S. |editor2-last=Higgins |editor2-first=P.G. | year=1990 | chapter=''Phaethon rubricauda'' Red-tailed Tropicbird |title=Handbook of Australian, New Zealand & Antarctic Birds. Volume 1: Ratites to ducks; Part B, Australian pelican to ducks |place=Melbourne, Victoria |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-553068-1| pages=935\u201344 | chapter-url=http://www.nzbirdsonline.org.nz/sites/all/files/121_Red-tailed%20Tropicbird.pdf |ref={{sfnRef|Marchant|Higgins|1990}} }}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Commons category inline|Phaethon rubricauda}}\n\n{{tropicbirds}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q756640}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:tropicbird, red-tailed}}\n[[Category:Phaethontidae|red-tailed tropicbird]]\n[[Category:Birds of Christmas Island]]\n[[Category:Birds of Norfolk Island]]\n[[Category:Birds of Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Birds of the Indian Ocean]]\n[[Category:Birds of the Maluku Islands]]\n[[Category:Birds of Mauritius]]\n[[Category:Birds of the Pacific Ocean]]\n[[Category:Birds of Palau]]\n[[Category:Birds of Queensland]]\n[[Category:Birds of R\u00e9union]]\n[[Category:Birds of Western Australia]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1783|red-tailed tropicbird]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Pieter Boddaert|red-tailed tropicbird]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|seabird of the tropical Indian and Pacific Oceans}}\n{{redirect|Amokura|text=For the New Zealand training ship, see [[NZS Amokura]]}}\n{{featured article}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| name = Red-tailed tropicbird\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=IUCN>{{cite iucn |author1= [[BirdLife International]]|title= ''Phaethon rubricauda'' |volume= 2018|year= 2018|journal= [[IUCN Red List of Threatened Species]] |publisher= [[IUCN]]|page= e.T22696641A132586227 |doi= 10.2305/IUCN.UK.2018-2.RLTS.T22696641A132586227.en |url= https://www.iucnredlist.org/species/22696641/132586227 |access-date= 3 December 2019}}</ref>\n| image = Red-tailed Tropicbird RWD2.jpg\n| image_caption = In flight, Kilauea Point, Kauai, Hawaii \n| taxon = Phaethon rubricauda\n| authority = [[Pieter Boddaert|Boddaert]], 1783\n|synonyms_ref = <ref name=checklistNZ>{{cite book | last= Gill | first=B.J.| last2= Bell| first2= B.D.| last3=Chambers| first3=G.K.| last4=Medway| first4=D.G.| last5=Palma| first5= R.L.| last6= Scofield| first6= R.P.| last7=Tennyson| first7= A.J.D.| last8= Worthy| first8= T.H. | year=2010| title= Checklist of the birds of New Zealand, Norfolk and Macquarie Islands, and the Ross Dependency, Antarctica | edition= 4th | location=Wellington, New Zealand | publisher=Te Papa Press and Ornithological Society of New Zealand |pages =136\u201337 | isbn=9781877385599}}</ref>\n|synonyms =''Phaethon phoenicuros'' <small>Gmelin 1789</small><br> \n''Pha\u00ebthon novae-hollandiae'' <small>Brandt, 1840</small>\n| range_map = Redtailedtropicbirdrge.png\n| range_map_caption = Range (in pink)\n}}\n\nThe '''red-tailed tropicbird''' (''Phaethon rubricauda'') is a [[seabird]] native to tropical parts of the [[Indian Ocean|Indian]] and [[Pacific Ocean|Pacific Oceans]]. One of three closely related species of [[tropicbird]] (Phaethontidae), it was described by [[Pieter Boddaert]] in 1883. Superficially resembling a [[tern]] in appearance, it has almost all-white plumage with a black mask and a red bill. The sexes have similar plumage. As referenced in the common name, adults have red {{birdgloss|tail streamers}} that are about twice their body length. Four subspecies are recognised, but there is evidence of [[Cline (biology)|clinal]] variation in body size\u2014with smaller birds in the north and larger in the south\u2014and hence no grounds for subspecies.\n\nThe red-tailed tropicbird eats fish\u2014mainly [[flying fish]] and squid\u2014after catching them by plunge-diving into the ocean. [[Nesting instinct|Nesting]] takes place in loose [[bird colony|colonies]] on oceanic islands; the nest itself is a [[Bird nest#Scrape|scrape]] found on a cliff face, in a crevice, or on a sandy beach. A single egg is laid, then is incubated by both sexes for about six weeks. The parents make long food-foraging trips of about 150 hours during incubation, but once the chick has hatched, the parents specialize their foraging: one forages for the chick for a few hours at a time, while the other makes much longer trips to feed themselves.\n\nThis bird is considered to be a [[least-concern species]] according to the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] (IUCN), though it is adversely affected by human contact. Rats and feral cats prey on eggs and young at nesting sites. The bird's tail streamers were once prized by some [[Native Hawaiians|Hawaiian]] and [[M\u0101ori people|Maori]] peoples.\n\n==Taxonomy==\nThe British naturalist [[Joseph Banks|Sir Joseph Banks]] encountered the red-tailed tropicbird on the Pacific Ocean in March 1769 on [[First voyage of James Cook|James Cook's first voyage]], noting that it was a different species to the familiar [[red-billed tropicbird]]. He gave it the name ''Phaeton erubescens''.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Banks|first1=Sir Joseph|title=Journal of the Right Hon. Sir Joseph Banks Bart., K.B., P.R.S.: During Captain Cook's First Voyage in HMS Endeavour in 1768\u201371 to Terra Del Fuego, Otahite, New Zealand, Australia, the Dutch East Indies, Etc.|date=1896|publisher=Macmillan | location=London |pages=65, 67|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/38211333 }}</ref> It was the French polymath [[Georges-Louis Leclerc, Comte de Buffon]] who formally [[species description|described]] the species in his ''Histoire Naturelle des Oiseaux'' in 1781, noting it was a native of  [[Isle de France (Mauritius)|Isle de France]] (Mauritius).<ref>{{ cite book | last=Buffon | first=Georges-Louis Leclerc de | author-link=Georges-Louis Leclerc, Comte de Buffon | year=1781 | title=Histoire Naturelle des Oiseaux | volume=Volume 16 | place=Paris | publisher=De L'Imprimerie Royale | pages=116\u201318| chapter=Le Paille en Queue a Brins Rouges | language=French  | chapter-url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/42296359}}</ref> The bird was also illustrated in a hand-coloured plate engraved by [[Fran\u00e7ois-Nicolas Martinet]] in the ''Planches Enlumin\u00e9es D'Histoire Naturelle'' which was produced under the supervision of [[Edme-Louis Daubenton]] to accompany Buffon's text.<ref>{{ cite book | last1=Buffon | first1=Georges-Louis Leclerc de | author1-link=Georges-Louis Leclerc, Comte de Buffon | last2=Martinet | first2=Fran\u00e7ois-Nicolas | author2-link=Fran\u00e7ois-Nicolas Martinet | last3=Daubenton | first3=Edme-Louis  | author3-link=Edme-Louis Daubenton | last4=Daubenton | first4=Louis-Jean-Marie | author4-link=Louis-Jean-Marie Daubenton | year=1765\u20131783 | chapter=Paille en Queue d'Isle de France | title=Planches Enlumin\u00e9es D'Histoire Naturelle | volume=Volume 10 | place=Paris | publisher=De L'Imprimerie Royale | at=Plate 979 | chapter-url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/35223703}}</ref>  Buffon did not include a scientific name with his description but in 1783 the Dutch naturalist [[Pieter Boddaert]] coined the [[binomial name]] ''Phaethon rubricauda'' in his catalogue of the ''Planches Enlumin\u00e9es''.<ref>{{cite book |last= Boddaert |first= Pieter |year= 1783 |title= Table des Planches Enlumin\u00e9ez d'Histoire Naturelle, de M. d'Aubenton. Avec les denominations de M.M. de Buffon, Brisson, Edwards, Linnaeus et Latham, prec\u00e9d\u00e9 d'une Notice des Principaux Ouvrages Zoologiques enlumin\u00e9es |location= Utrecht |publisher= Boddaert |page= 57 |url= https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/27822677 |url-status= live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20171107175333/https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/27822677 |archivedate= 2017-11-07 }}</ref> The genus name is derived from [[Ancient Greek]] ''phaethon'', \"sun\", while the species epithet comes from the Latin words ''ruber'' \"red\" and ''cauda'' \"tail\".{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=935}}<!-- cites previous 1.5 sentences --> English ornithologist [[John Latham (ornithologist)|John Latham]] wrote about the red-tailed tropicbird in 1785 in his ''General Synopsis of Birds'', recording it as common in Mauritius and the South Pacific. He also reported a black-billed tropicbird collected from [[Palmerston Island]] that ended up in Banks' collection.<ref>{{cite book | last=Latham | first=John | year=1785 | title=A General Synopsis of Birds | volume=3 | pages=619\u201321 | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/40079445 | publisher=Benj. White | location=London, United Kingdom | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180227090337/https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/40079445 | archivedate=2018-02-27 }}</ref> Latham did not give them binomial names, however. It was left to German naturalist [[Johann Friedrich Gmelin]] to describe the species, which he did as ''Phaeton phoenicuros'' and ''P. melanorhynchos'' respectively in the 13th edition of ''[[Systema Naturae]]'' in 1788.<ref>{{cite book|last=Gmelin|first=Johann Friedrich|title=Systema naturae per regna tria naturae :secundum classes, ordines, genera, species, cum characteribus, differentiis, synonymis, locis /Caroli a Linn\u00e9|publisher=Impensis Georg. Emanuel. Beer|location=Leipzig, Germany|date=1788|volume=1 Part 2|pages=582\u201383|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/2656075|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160416182212/http://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/2656075|archivedate=2018-02-27}}</ref> Latham later described this black-billed specimen as the New Holland tropicbird,<ref>{{cite book | last=Latham | first=John | year=1824 | title=A General History of Birds | volume=10 | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/40978190 | page=448 | location=Winchester | publisher=Jacob and Johnson | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180227090337/https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/40978190 | archivedate=2018-02-27 }}</ref> giving it the name ''Phaethon novae-hollandiae''.<ref name=rothschild/>\n\nThe British naturalist [[Walter Rothschild, 2nd Baron Rothschild|Walter Rothschild]] reviewed the described names and specimens in 1900 and concluded that the original use of ''P. erubescens'' was a ''[[nomen nudum]]''. He concluded that the populations of [[Lord Howe Island|Lord Howe]], [[Norfolk Island|Norfolk]] and [[Kermadec Islands]] belonged to a distinct subspecies which he named ''P. rubicauda erubescens'', due to their larger overall size, more robust bill and prominent reddish tinge to their plumage. He also classified ''P. melanorhynchus'' and ''P. novae-hollandiae'' as juveniles.<ref name=rothschild>{{cite book | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/44039603 | title=The avifauna of Laysan and the neighbouring islands : with a complete history to date of the birds of the Hawaiian possessions | last=Rothschild | first=Walter | year=1900 | location=London | publisher=R.H. Porter | page=296 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180227090337/https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/44039603 | archivedate=2018-02-27 }}</ref> The Australian amateur ornithologist [[Gregory Mathews]] then applied the name ''P. rubicauda roseotinctus'' to Rothschild's ''P. rubicauda erubescens''.<ref>{{cite journal | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/40498721 | journal=Bulletin of the British Ornithologists' Club | year=1923 | volume=46 | page=60 | title=On some changes in names | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180227090337/https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/40498721 | archivedate=2018-02-27 }}</ref>\n\n\"Red-tailed tropicbird\" has been designated the official name by the [[International Ornithologists' Union]] (IOC).<ref name=\"ioclist\">{{cite web | editor1-last=Gill | editor1-first=Frank | editor1-link=Frank Gill (ornithologist) | editor2-last=Donsker | editor2-first=David | year=2017 | title=Grebes, flamingos, tropicbirds | work=World Bird List Version 7.1 | url=http://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/grebes/ | publisher=International Ornithologists' Union | accessdate=9 February 2018 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170904110252/http://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/grebes/ | archivedate=4 September 2017 }}</ref> Other common names include red-tailed bos'nbird or silver bos'nbird, the names derived from the semblance of the tail feathers to a boatswain's marlin spikes, and strawtail.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=935}} The New Zealand [[M\u0101ori people|M\u0101ori]] call it ''amokura'',<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |last=Williams |first=Herbert W. |title=Amokura |dictionary=A Dictionary of the Maori Language |date=1971 |publisher=A. R. Shearer, Government Printer |location=Wellington |edition=7th}}</ref> and the [[native Hawaiians]] ''koa{{okina}}e {{okina}}ula''.<ref name=hawaii>{{cite web | url= https://dlnr.hawaii.gov/wildlife/files/2013/09/Fact-Sheet-Red-tailed-Tropicbird.pdf | title= Koa\u2018e \u2018ula or Red-tailed Tropicbird | work= Hawaii\u2019s Comprehensive Wildlife Conservation Strategy | date= 1 October 2005 | accessdate= 19 February 2018 | url-status= live | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20170207132552/http://dlnr.hawaii.gov/wildlife/files/2013/09/Fact-Sheet-Red-tailed-Tropicbird.pdf | archivedate= 7 February 2017 }}</ref>\n\nIts closest relative is the [[white-tailed tropicbird]] (''P. lepturus''), the split between their ancestors taking place about four million years ago.<ref name=\"KennedySpencer2004\">{{cite journal|last1=Kennedy|first1=Martyn|last2=Spencer|first2=Hamish G|title=Phylogenies of the frigatebirds (Fregatidae) and tropicbirds (Phaethonidae), two divergent groups of the traditional order Pelecaniformes, inferred from mitochondrial DNA sequences|journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution|volume=31|issue=1|year=2004|pages=31\u201338|pmid=15019606|doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2003.07.007}}</ref>\n\nFour subspecies are recognised by the IOC:<ref name=\"ioclist\"/>\n\n*''P. r. rubricauda'' Boddaert, 1783 the nominate subspecies, from the western Indian Ocean. Subsequent specimens from the [[Cocos (Keeling) Islands]] were allocated to this [[taxon]].<ref name=tarburton89/>\n*''P. r. westralis'' Mathews, 1912 from the eastern Indian Ocean. Mathews described it as separate on account of its larger wings.<ref>{{cite journal | last= Mathews | first= G.M. | year= 1912 | title= Additions and corrections to my Reference List to the Birds of Australia | journal= Austral Avian Records | volume= 1 | pages= 81\u2013103 [88] | url= https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/33339667 | url-status= live | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180227090335/https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/33339667 | archivedate= 2018-02-27 }}</ref> More extensive analysis in 1989 showed that the wing and beak size overlap between this and the nominate subspecies, leaving intensity of colour as the only distinguishing feature.<ref name=tarburton89/>\n*''P. r. roseotinctus'' Mathews, 1926 from the southwestern Pacific Ocean, including populations on Kermadec, Lord Howe, Norfolk and [[Raine Island]]s.<ref name=tarburton89/>\n*''P. r. melanorhynchos''  Gmelin, 1789 from the western, central and southern Pacific Ocean, including populations on the Cook Islands, Tonga, Samoa, the [[Marquesas Islands|Marquesas]] and the Society Islands.<ref name=tarburton89/>\n\nThe ornithologist Mike Tarburton reviewed the known subspecies in 1989 and concluded that none were valid, noting that there was a [[Cline (biology)|clinal]] change in size in the species: those from [[Kure Atoll]] in the North Pacific being the smallest; ranging to those from the Kermadec Islands in the South Pacific being the largest. He also noted that the pink colouration was more intense in new plumage and faded after a few years in museum specimens.<ref name=tarburton89>{{cite journal | url=https://notornis.osnz.org.nz/system/files/Notornis_36_1.pdf#page=43 | last=Tarburton | first=Michael Kenneth | year=1989 | volume=36 | issue=1 | journal=Notornis | title=Subspeciation in the red-tailed tropicbird | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171213201604/https://notornis.osnz.org.nz/system/files/Notornis_36_1.pdf#page=43 | archivedate=2017-12-13 }}</ref>\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Starr 080607-7135 Plumeria rubra.jpg|thumb|left|Closeup of head showing comma-shaped markings]]\n\nThe red-tailed tropicbird measures {{convert|95|to|104|cm|in|abbr=on}} on average, which includes the {{convert|35|cm|in|abbr=on}} {{birdgloss|tail streamers}}, and weighs around {{convert|800|g|oz|sigfig=1|abbr=on}}. It has a wingspan of {{convert|111|to|119|cm|in|abbr=on}}. It has a streamlined but solid build with almost all-white [[plumage]],{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=935}} often with a pink tinge.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=936}} The sexes are similar in plumage.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=935}} A dark brown comma-shaped stripe extends back from the [[Lore (anatomy)|lores]], through and over the eyes and reaching the ear [[Covert feather|coverts]].{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=936}} The iris is dark brown.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=943}} The bill is bright red, slightly paler at the base and black around the nostrils. The legs and base of the toes are pale blue-mauve, while the webbing and rest of the toes are black.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=943}} The white feathers of the head and rump have concealed dark brown bases, while those of the mantle, back, tail [[Flight feather#Rectrices|rectrices]] and tail coverts have dark brown shaft bases. The two long tail feathers are orange or red with white bases for around a tenth of their length,{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=942}} and can be hard to see when the bird is flying. The white wings are marked by dark [[Chevron (insignia)|chevron]]-shaped patches on the [[Flight feather#Tertial|tertials]], and the dark shafts of the [[Flight feather#Primaries|primary]] flight feathers are visible.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=936}} The pink tinge is often more pronounced in the [[Flight feather#Remiges|remiges]] of the upper wing.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=942}} Moulting takes place outside the breeding season, the streamers being replaced before the rest of the feathers. Streamers are replaced at any time, one growing while the other is shed, and old streamers may litter the area around a breeding colony.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=943}}\n\nNewly-hatched chicks are covered in thin, long, grey-white [[Down feather|down]], which is paler on the head. The lores are bare. The down is greyer in older chicks. The primaries, rectrices and scapulars are evident in the third week, and chicks are mostly feathered with residual down on underparts and under the wings after six weeks, and fully feathered by 11 weeks.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=942}} Juvenile birds have a glossy white forehead, chin, throat and underparts,{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=943}} and prominent black barring and scaling on their crown, nape, mantle, back, rump and upper wing coverts.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=936}} Their bills are blackish grey with a light blue-grey base, and grey legs and feet.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=943}}\n\nIn Australian waters the red-tailed tropicbird could be confused with the [[silver gull]] (''Chroicocephalus novaehollandiae'') or various tern species, though it is larger and heavier-set, with a wedge-shaped tail. Its red bill and more wholly white wings distinguish it from the adult white-tailed tropicbird. Immature red-tailed tropicbirds likewise can be distinguished from immature white-tailed tropicbirds by their partly red rather than yellow bills.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=936}}<!-- cites previous two sentences -->\n\nThe red-tailed tropicbird is generally silent while flying. Aside from during courtship displays, birds may give a short greeting squawk to their mate when arriving or leaving the nest. Birds give a low growling call as a defence call, and young chatter repetitively as a begging call\u2014made whenever the parents are nearby.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=941}}\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nThe red-tailed tropicbird ranges across the southern Indian, and western and central Pacific Oceans, from the African coast to Indonesia, the waters around the southern reaches of Japan, across to Chile,{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=937}} and the [[Hawaiian Islands]], where they are more common on the northwestern islands.<ref name=vanderwerf07>{{cite journal | last=Vanderwerf | first=Eric A. | first2=Lindsay C. | last2=Young | title=The Red-billed Tropicbird ''Phaethon rubricauda'' in Hawaii, with notes on interspecific behavior of tropicbirds | journal=Marine Ornithology | volume=35 | year=2007 | pages=81\u201384 | url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Lindsay_Young/publication/237377707_The_Red-billed_Tropicbird_Phaethon_rubricauda_in_Hawaii_with_notes_on_interspecific_behavior_of_tropicbirds/links/00b7d52c271783ce39000000.pdf | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180217202830/https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Lindsay_Young/publication/237377707_The_Red-billed_Tropicbird_Phaethon_rubricauda_in_Hawaii_with_notes_on_interspecific_behavior_of_tropicbirds/links/00b7d52c271783ce39000000.pdf | archivedate=2018-02-17 }}</ref> There are large breeding colonies on [[Europa Island|Europa]],<ref>{{cite journal | last=Le Corre | first= M.| last2=Jouventin | first2=  P. | year=1997 | title= Ecological significance and conservation priorities of Europa Island (western Indian Ocean), with special reference to seabirds | journal= Revue d'Ecologie (Terre et Vie) | volume=52| pages=205\u201320 }}</ref> [[Aldabra]]<ref>{{cite journal | last=Diamond | first= A. W. | year=1975| volume=92 | issue=1 |pages= 16\u201339 | title=The biology of tropicbirds at Aldabra Atoll, Indian Ocean | journal= Auk | url=https://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/auk/v092n01/p0016-p0039.pdf | doi=10.2307/4084415| jstor= 4084415 }}</ref> and [[Christmas Island]] in the Indian Ocean, with smaller colonies in [[Madagascar]]\u2014where it nests on the tiny island of Nosy Ve<ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=jMjjDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA118 | page=118 | title=Wildlife of Madagascar | first1=Ken | last1=Behrens | first12=Keith | last2=Barnes | publisher=Princeton University Press | year=2016 | isbn=9781400880676 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180220033155/https://books.google.com.au/books?id=jMjjDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA118 | archivedate=2018-02-20 }}</ref>\u2014the Seychelles, and Mauritius.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=937}}  In Australia, it nests on  [[Queensland]]'s coral islands (including Raine Island and [[Lady Elliot Island]]), and Ashmore Reef and Rottnest Island off [[Western Australia]], as well as Sugarloaf Rock at Cape Naturaliste and Busselton on the Western Australian coastline itself, and the offshore territories of the Cocos (Keeling) Islands, Norfolk and Lord Howe islands. In New Zealand territory it  breeds on the Kermadec Islands.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=938}} Elsewhere in the Pacific it breeds in Fiji, New Caledonia, French Polynesia, Hawaii{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=937}}\u2014with a large colony on Kure Atoll<ref name=woodward72/>\u2014the Cook Islands, Pitcairn Island, and islands off Japan and Chile.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=937}}\n\nIt frequents areas of ocean with water temperatures from {{convert|24|to|30|C|F|abbr=on}} and salinity under 35% in the southern hemisphere and 33.5% in the northern hemisphere. In the Pacific Ocean, the southern boundary of its range runs along the {{convert|22|C|F|abbr=on}} summer surface isotherm.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=936}} The warm waters of the [[Leeuwin Current]] facilitate the species nesting at [[Cape Leeuwin]] in southwestern Australia, yet is only a rare visitor to New South Wales at corresponding latitudes on the Australian east coast.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=936}}\n\nIt is an occasional visitor to [[Palau]], breeding being recorded from the [[Southwest Islands (Palau)|Southwest Islands]],<ref>{{cite journal| journal=Micronesica| last=VanderWerf| first=E.A.| first2=G.J.| last2=Wiles| first3=A.P.| last3=Marshall| first4=M.| last4=Knecht| year=2006| title=Observations of migrants and other birds in Palau, April\u2013May 2005, including the first Micronesian record of a Richard\u2019s Pipit| volume=39| issue=1| pages=11\u201329| url=http://micronesica.org/sites/default/files/2_vanderwerf-palau.pdf| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160302195732/http://micronesica.org/sites/default/files/2_vanderwerf-palau.pdf| archivedate=2016-03-02}}</ref> and was first recorded from Guam in 1992.<ref>{{cite journal | journal=Micronesica | last=Wiles | first=Gary J. | last2=Beck, Jr | first2=Robert E. | last3=Aguon | first3=Celestino F. | year=1993 | title=Recent bird records for the southern Mariana Islands, with notes on a colony of Black Noddies on Cocos Island, Guam | volume=26 | issue=2 | pages=199\u2013215 | url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Gary_Wiles/publication/263275985_Recent_bird_records_for_the_southern_Mariana_Islands_with_notes_on_a_colony_of_Black_Noddies_on_Cocos_Island_Guam/links/0c96053be129d86a0c000000.pdf | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180218210306/https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Gary_Wiles/publication/263275985_Recent_bird_records_for_the_southern_Mariana_Islands_with_notes_on_a_colony_of_Black_Noddies_on_Cocos_Island_Guam/links/0c96053be129d86a0c000000.pdf | archivedate=2018-02-18 }}</ref> It is an uncommon vagrant to New Zealand proper, where it has been recorded from the northern reaches of North Island, especially [[Three Kings Islands]].<ref name=checklistNZ/> It is a very rare vagrant to North America, with records from California and [[Vancouver Island]].<ref>{{cite book | title=Rare Birds of North America | url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=-YqGAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA111 | page=111 | first=Steve N. G. | last=Howell | first2=Ian | last2=Lewington | first3=Will | last3=Russell | publisher=Princeton University Press | year=2014 | isbn=9781400848072 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180210002259/https://books.google.com.au/books?id=-YqGAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA111 | archivedate=2018-02-10 }}</ref>\n\nThe birds disperse widely after breeding. Evidence suggests birds in the Indian Ocean follow prevailing winds westwards, young individuals banded in Sumatra and Sugarloaf Reserve, Western Australia, being recovered at Mauritius and Reunion respectively.<ref>{{cite journal | url =https://www.researchgate.net/publication/248900262_Transoceanic_dispersion_of_the_Red-tailed_Tropicbird_in_the_Indian_Ocean | title= Transoceanic dispersion of the Red-tailed Tropicbird in the Indian Ocean | first=  Matthieu | last=Le Corre |first2= Marc | last2=Salamolard |first3=Marie Claude | last3=Portier | year=2003| journal=Emu | volume=103| issue=2| pages=183\u201384 | doi=10.1071/MU02026}}</ref> Banding on Kure Atoll suggests birds in the North Pacific disperse in an easterly direction, following prevailing winds there.<ref name=woodward72/> Strong winds can blow them inland on occasions, which explains some sighting records away from the coast and their preferred habitats.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=935}}\n\n==Behaviour==\nThe red-tailed tropicbird is a strong flyer, and walks on land with difficulty using a shuffling gait.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=935}}\n\n===Breeding===\n[[File:Red-tailed tropicbird (Phaethon rubricauda rubricauda) nesting.jpg|thumb|''P. r. rubricuada'' nesting on Nosy Ve]]\n\nThe red-tailed tropicbird is thought to be monogamous, pairs remaining bonded over successive breeding seasons, although such information as age at first breeding and pair-formation is not known.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=939}} It nests in loose colonies,<ref name=\"hbw\"/> on offshore islands and stacks, rocky cliffs, coral atolls and cays. It rarely nests on large bodies of land, though has done so in southern Western Australia.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=936}} The nest itself is a shallow [[Bird nest#Scrape|scrape]], in either shaded sand<ref name=\"HowellBartholomew1962\">{{cite journal|last1=Howell|first1=Thomas R.|last2=Bartholomew|first2=George A.|title=Temperature regulation in the red-tailed tropic bird and the red-footed booby|url=https://sora.unm.edu/node/101356|jstor=1365438|journal= Condor|volume=64|issue=1|year=1962|pages=6\u201318|doi=10.2307/1365438}}</ref> or a rocky crevice,<ref name=\"hbw\"/> or under a shrub. Because the red-tailed tropicbird does not walk well, it lands by flying into the wind, stalling and dropping to the ground. The nest is often located within {{convert|1|m|ft|spell=in}} of the edge of the shrub (or other shaded area) to minimise walking distance. The tropicbird often chooses shrubs with fewer stems for accessibility.<ref name=\"ClarkRicklefs1983\">{{Cite journal|  volume = 100| issue = 4| pages = 953\u2013959| last1 = Clark| first1 = L.| last2 = Ricklefs| first2 = R. E.| last3 = Schreiber| first3 = R. W.| title = Nest-site selection by the red-tailed tropicbird| journal=Auk|year = 1983 | url=https://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/auk/v100n04/p0953-p0959.pdf}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:Rtailedtropicbird8.jpg|thumb|left|Nesting and sheltering chick under its wing]]\n[[File:Phaethon rubricauda MHNT.ZOO.2010.11.2.14.jpg|thumb|Egg \u2013 [[Mus\u00e9um de Toulouse]]]]\n[[File:Starr 080612-8667 Calophyllum inophyllum.jpg|thumb|right| Young chick with down]]\n[[Image:Red-tailed tropic Bird (young).JPG|thumb|right|Young bird on Nosy Ve, Madagascar]]\n\nThe species is territorial to a degree, aggressively defending the nest site and pecking radius around it, commencing around three months before breeding.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=939}} Birds are more aggressive at crowded colonies, where numbers are large or suitable nest sites less common. They adopt a defence posture, which consists of raising the [[humerus|humeri]] up and bringing the wrists together, drawing the neck into the body and shaking the head sideways, fluffing up the head feathers and squawking. Bill-jabbing and fights can break out, the two combatants locking bills and wrestling for up to 90 minutes.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=940}}\n\n[[Sexual selection|Mate choice]] is likely to be based partially on the length of the tail streamers, a bird having longer tail streamers being more attractive as a mate. This tropicbird also probably mates [[Assortative mating|assortatively]] for tail streamer length, meaning mates likely have streamers of about equal length.<ref name=\"BolandDouble2004\">{{cite journal|last1=Boland|first1=C. R. J.|last2=Double|first2=M. C.|last3=Baker|first3=G. B.|title=Assortative mating by tail streamer length in red-tailed tropicbirds ''Phaethon rubricauda'' breeding in the Coral Sea|journal=Ibis|volume=146|issue=4|year=2004|pages=687\u2013690|doi=10.1111/j.1474-919x.2004.00310.x}}</ref>\n\nIn the leadup to breeding, males initiate an aerial courtship display of flying in large circles, alternating between gliding, short periods of rapid wing-beating, and low flight within a few metres of the water, while making sharp cackling calls. Initially flying in small groups, birds then pair off to repeat the display in pairs before bonding. Once pairs have established a nest, they do not perform the display.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=940}}\n\nThe timing of breeding depends on location; in some places, birds breed in a defined breeding season, whereas in others, there is none. South of the equator, the latter is likely to be true. On islands near the equator, laying usually occurs from June to November, the majority of chicks fledging around January to February.<ref name=\"hbw\"/> On Christmas Island, breeding takes place at different times on different parts of the island due to prevailing weather conditions.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=941}} Some birds may remain at the breeding site year-round.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=940}}\n\nThe female red-tailed tropicbird lays one egg, which both parents incubate<ref name=\"HowellBartholomew1962\"/> for 42 to 46 days.<ref name=\"hbw\">{{cite web |last1=Orta|first1=J.|last2=Christie|first2=David A.|last3=Jutglar|first3=F.|last4=Garcia|first4=E. F. J.|last5=Kirwan|first5=G. M.|last6=Boesman|first6=P.|editor1-last=del Hoyo |editor1-first=Josep |editor2-last=Elliott |editor2-first=Andrew |editor3-last=Sargatal |editor3-first=Jordi |editor4-last=Christie |editor4-first=David A. |editor5-last=de Juana |editor5-first=Eduardo |year=2018 |title=Red-tailed Tropicbird (''Phaethon rubricauda'') |work=Handbook of the Birds of the World Alive |url=https://www.hbw.com/species/red-tailed-tropicbird-phaethon-rubricauda |publisher=Lynx Edicions |location=Barcelona, Spain |accessdate=11 February 2018 |url-access=subscription }}</ref> The male generally takes the first turn on the egg after it is laid.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=940}} Ranging from {{convert|5.4|to|7.7|cm|in}} long (averaging between {{convert|6.3|and|6.8|cm|in}}, depending on location) and {{convert|4.5|to|4.8|cm|in}} wide, the oval eggs are pale tan with brown and red-black markings that are more prominent on the larger end.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=941}}\n\nBorn helpless and unable to move around ([[nidicolous]] and semi-[[altricial]]), the chicks are initially blind, opening their eyes after 2\u20133 days. Until they are a week old, they open their beak only upon touch, so the parents have to stroke the base of the bill to initiate feeding. Feeding takes place once or twice a day, generally around midday. They are constantly brooded by the parents until they are a week old, after which time they are sheltered under the parents\u2019 wings. They also rise up and gape at any nearby bird for food.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=942}}<!-- cites previous five sentences--> Both parents feed the young,{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=939}} by shoving its beak into the chick's gullet and then regurgitating food.<ref name=\"HowellBartholomew1969\">{{cite journal|last1=Howell|first1=Thomas R.|last2=Bartholomew|first2=George A.|title=Experiments on nesting behavior of the red-tailed tropicbird, ''Phaethon rubricauda''|journal=The Condor |url=https://sora.unm.edu/node/101836|volume=71|issue=2|year=1969|pages=113\u2013119|doi=10.2307/1366072}}</ref> Initially covered with grey or white down, they grow their first feathers\u2014scapulars\u2014at 16\u201320 days. Their feet and beaks grow rapidly, outpacing the rest of their bodies.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=942}}<!-- cites previous 2 sentences--> Chicks remain in the nest for 67 to 91 days until they fledge.<ref name=\"hbw\"/>\n\n===Feeding===\nThe red-tailed tropicbird is mostly a {{birdgloss|plunge diver}}, diving anywhere from an above-water height of {{convert|6|to|50|m|ft}},<ref name=\"hbw\"/> to a depth of about {{convert|4.5|m|ft}}, although this may change seasonally.<ref name=\"LeCorre1997\">{{cite journal|last1=Le Corre|first1=Matthieu|title=Diving depths of two tropical Pelecaniformes: The red-tailed tropicbird and the red-footed booby|journal=Condor|volume=99|issue=4|year=1997|pages=1004\u20131007 |doi=10.2307/1370157 | url=https://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/condor/v099n04/p1004-p1007.pdf |jstor=1370157}}</ref> When diving, it remains briefly submerged\u2014one study on Christmas Island came up with an average time of 26.6 seconds\u2014generally swallowing its prey before surfacing.<ref name=GH47>{{cite journal | title=The Normal Food of Tropic\u2010birds (''Pha\u00ebthon'' spp.) | last=Gibson\u2010Hill | first= C. A. | journal=Ibis | year= 1947 |volume=89| issue=4| pages=658\u201361 | doi=10.1111/j.1474-919X.1947.tb03901.x}}</ref> The red-tailed tropicbird sometimes catches [[flying fish]] in the air.<ref name=\"hbw\"/>\n\nDuring incubation, foraging trips are relatively long, with an average excursion taking about 153 hours. These trips are to very productive areas. After the chicks hatch, on the other hand, the parents adopt a strategy where one takes long trips (these averaging about 57 hours) for self feeding, and the other takes short trips (about three hours long) to feed the chicks. The [[Multimodal distribution|bimodality]] of the length of foraging trips is likely to be because of the fact that it is the optimal balance of self-feeding and provisioning for chicks.<ref name=\"SommerfeldHennicke2016\">{{cite journal|last1=Sommerfeld|first1=Julia|last2=Hennicke|first2=Janos C.|title=Comparison of trip duration, activity pattern and diving behaviour by red-tailed tropicbirds (''Phaethon rubricauda'') during incubation and chick-rearing|journal=Emu |volume=110|issue=1|year=2016|pages=78\u201386|doi=10.1071/MU09053}}</ref> On Christmas Island, birds generally forage far out to sea in the early morning and closer to shore in the afternoon.<ref name=GH47/>\n\nSquid and flying fish make up a large portion of this bird's diet, along with some crustaceans, depending on location.<ref name=\"hbw\"/> Fieldwork in the [[Mozambique Channel]] revealed the diet of birds there to be mostly fish by mass but equal numbers of fish and squid caught. Fish recorded include the [[mirrorwing flyingfish]] (''Hirundichthys speculiger'') and [[spotfin flyingfish]] (''Cheilopogon furcatus'') and several other unidentified species of the flying fish family Exocoetidae, the [[pompano dolphinfish]] (''Coryphaena equiselis'') and [[Mahi-mahi|common dolphinfish]] (''C. hippurus''), needleflish including the [[houndfish]] (''Tylosurus crocodilus''), and unidentified members of [[Hemiramphidae]], [[Scombridae]], and [[Carangidae]]. The [[Sthenoteuthis oualaniensis|purpleback flying squid]] (''Sthenoteuthis oualaniensis'') was by far the most common cephalopod eaten, followed by the [[common blanket octopus]] (''Tremoctopus violaceus'').<ref name=lecorre03>{{cite journal | title=Seasonal and inter-annual variation in the feeding ecology of a tropical oceanic seabird, the red-tailed tropicbird ''Phaethon rubricauda'' | first=M. | last=Le Corre | first2=Y. | last2=Cherel | first3=F. | last3=Lagarde | first4=H. | last4=Lorm\u00e9e | first5=P. | last5=Jouventin | journal=Marine Ecology Progress Series | volume=255 | year=2003 | pages=289\u2013301 | url=https://www.int-res.com/articles/meps2003/255/m255p289.pdf | jstor=24866967 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121210001950/https://www.int-res.com/articles/meps2003/255/m255p289.pdf | archivedate=2012-12-10 | doi=10.3354/meps255289}}</ref> A field study in Hawaii found flying fish dominated the prey species, the tropical two-wing flyingfish (''[[Exocoetus volitans]]'') and members of the genus ''[[Cypselurus]]'' prominent, followed by squid of the family [[Ommastrephidae]] including the purpleback flying squid and the glass squid (''[[Hyaloteuthis pelagica]]''), and carangid fish including the [[shortfin scad]] (''Decapterus macrosoma'').<ref>{{cite journal | title=Hawaiian Seabird Feeding Ecology | first= Craig S. |last=Harrison| first2= Thomas S. |last2=Hida | first3=Michael P. |last3=Seki | journal=Wildlife Monographs No. 85| year= 1983| pages= 3\u201371 [27\u201328]| jstor=3830593}}</ref> The red-tailed tropicbird has also been recorded eating [[porcupinefish]] (Diodontidae), although adults have been troubled when the victim fish inflates resulting in it being urgently regurgitated.<ref>{{cite journal | title=Comparative Feeding Ecology of Sea Birds of a Tropical Oceanic Island | journal=Bulletin of the Peabody Museum of Natural History Yale University | issue=24 | last1=Ashmole | first1=N. Philip | last2=Ashmole | first2=Myrtle | url=http://peabody.yale.edu/sites/default/files/documents/scientific-publications/ypmB24_1967.pdf | pages=1\u2013139 [19\u201326] | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160624104651/http://peabody.yale.edu/sites/default/files/documents/scientific-publications/ypmB24_1967.pdf | archivedate=2016-06-24 }}</ref>\n\nA strong flyer with large mouth and bill, the red-tailed tropicbird can carry relatively large prey for its size, parent birds commonly bearing dolphin fish that weighed 120 g\u201416% of their own weight\u2014to their chicks.<ref name=lecorre03/>\n\n===Temperature regulation===\nWhen incubating during the day in a shaded nest, this bird has an average temperature of {{convert|39|C|F}}, compared to its average temperature when incubating at night of {{convert|37.1|C|F}}. The difference is likely due to activity levels, as the air temperature during these times does not differ significantly with a bird in the nest. After flying, the average body temperature is {{convert|40.9|C|F}}. The temperature of the feet is always lower than that of the body temperature during flight, but always higher than the air temperature. Thus, the feet are likely used to dissipate heat during flight.<ref name=\"HowellBartholomew1962\"/>\n\n==Relationship with humans==\nThe red-tailed tropicbird's tail streamers were highly prized by the Maori. The [[Ng\u0101puhi]] tribe of the [[Northland Region]] would look for and collect them off dead or stray birds blown ashore after easterly gales, trading them for greenstone with tribes from the south.<ref>{{cite book | title=A History of the Birds of New Zealand | first= Walter Lawry | last= Buller | year=1888 | publisher=Self | location=Westminster, United Kingdom | page=187 | url=http://nzetc.victoria.ac.nz/tm/scholarly/tei-BulBird-t1-g1-t2-body1-d5-d2.html}}</ref> English naturalist [[Andrew Bloxam]] reported that the feathers were valued in Hawaii, where the locals would pull them off the birds as they nested.<ref>{{cite book | url=https://archive.org/details/voyagehmsblonde01bloxgoog | chapter=Appendix | page=[https://archive.org/details/voyagehmsblonde01bloxgoog/page/n297 251] | title=Voyage of H.M.S. Blonde to the Sandwich islands, in the years 1824\u20131825 |\n year=1826 | first=George Anson | last=Byron | publisher=John Murray, Albemarle-Street. | location=London }}</ref>\n\n==Status==\n[[File:Red-tailed tropic bird swarmed by yellow crazy ants.jpg|thumb|right|Being swarmed by yellow crazy ants, Johnston Atoll]]\nThe red-tailed tropicbird is classified as a [[least-concern species]] according to the [[IUCN]] on account of its large range of up to {{convert|20|e3km2|mi2}}.<ref name=\"IUCN\"/> The population in the eastern Pacific has been estimated to be as high as 80,000 birds with a minimum of 41,000 birds.<ref>{{ cite journal | last1=Spear | first1=Larry B. | last2=Ainley | first2=David G. | year=2005 | title=At-sea distributions and abundance of tropicbirds in the eastern Pacific | journal=Ibis  | volume=147 | issue=2 | pages=353\u201366 | doi=10.1111/j.1474-919x.2005.00411.x }}</ref> Around 9,000 birds breed on Europa Island,<ref>{{ cite journal | title=Breeding seasons of seabirds at Europa Island (southern Mozambique Channel) in relation to seasonal changes in the marine environment | last= Le Corre | first= Matthieu | journal=Journal of Zoology | year= 2001|volume=254 | issue= 2 |pages=239\u201349 | doi=10.1017/S0952836901000759}}</ref> and 9,000\u201312,000 breed on the Hawaiian islands.<ref name=hawaii/> Human presence generally affects the species adversely, by the destruction of habitat or introduction of pests.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=937}} Within Australia, it is classified as ''near threatened'', due to unexpected declines in some populations, the impact of humans, and the [[yellow crazy ant]] overrunning Christmas Island.<ref>{{cite book | url=http://155.187.2.69/biodiversity/threatened/publications/action/birds2000/pubs/rt-tropicbird.pdf | chapter=Red-tailed Tropicbird | pages=152\u201353 | title=The Action Plan For Australian Birds 2000 | first1=Stephen T. | last1=Garnett | first2=Gabriel M. | last2=Crowley | isbn=0- 6425-4683-5 | publisher=Environment Australia | location=Canberra, ACT | year=2000 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180220033251/http://155.187.2.69/biodiversity/threatened/publications/action/birds2000/pubs/rt-tropicbird.pdf | archivedate=2018-02-20 | access-date=2018-02-19 }}</ref> It is listed as vulnerable in New South Wales.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.environment.nsw.gov.au/determinations/RedtailedTropicbirdVulSpListing.htm | title=Red-tailed tropicbird \u2013 vulnerable species listing | author=NSW Threatened Species Scientific Committee | work=Determinations | date=28 February 2011 | accessdate=19 February 2018 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180210065337/http://www.environment.nsw.gov.au/determinations/RedtailedTropicbirdVulSpListing.htm | archivedate=10 February 2018 }}</ref>\n\nPredators recorded in Western Australia include large raptors such as the [[white-bellied sea eagle]] (''Haliaeetus leucogaster'') and the [[eastern osprey]] (''Pandion cristatus''); while silver gulls, and crows and ravens (''[[Corvus]]'' spp.) raid nests for eggs and young.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=942}} Vagrant [[red-billed tropicbird]]s (''P. aethereus'') have been implicated in egg loss of nests in Hawaii.<ref name=vanderwerf07/> Feral dogs and [[feral cat|cats]] prey on nesting birds on Christmas Island,{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=942}} while feral cats are a severe problem on Norfolk Island.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=942}} Rats have been a serious problem on Kure Atoll, causing heavy losses.<ref name=woodward72>{{cite journal | last=Woodward | first=Paul W. | year=1972 | title=The natural history of Kure Atoll, Northwestern Hawaiian Islands |journal =Atoll Research Bulletin | issue=164 | pages=1\u2013318 [78\u201379, 134\u201347] | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/39954202 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180227090337/https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/39954202 | archivedate=2018-02-27 }}</ref> Yellow crazy ants were discovered on [[Johnston Atoll]] in the north Pacific Ocean in 2010, hordes of which overrun nesting areas and can blind victims with their spray.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.audubon.org/magazine/july-august-2015/one-remote-islands-battle-against-acid | title=One Remote Island's Battle Against Acid-Spewing Ants | first=Alisa | last=Opar | date=July\u2013August 2015 | accessdate=19 February 2018 | work=Audubon Magazine | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180220033443/http://www.audubon.org/magazine/july-august-2015/one-remote-islands-battle-against-acid | archivedate=20 February 2018 }}</ref>\n\nAlso on Johnston Atoll, the [[Johnston Atoll Chemical Agent Disposal System]] (JACADS) was burning stockpiled chemical weapons until 2000.  It was studied over eight years to see if there were effects from potential contaminants. There appeared to be no impact on survival during the study period, although young birds from downwind of the plant were less likely to return there than those upwind of the plant\u2014possibly due to the more intact vegetation at the latter site.<ref>{{cite journal | year=2004 | journal=Animal Biodiversity and Conservation | title=Dispersal and survival rates of adult and juvenile Red-tailed tropicbirds (''Phaethon rubricauda'') exposed to potential contaminants | last=Schreiber | first=E. A. | last2=Doherty | first2=P. F. Jr. | last3=Schenk | first3=G. A | volume=27.1 | pages=531\u201340 | url=http://abc.museucienciesjournals.cat/files/ABC-27-1-pp-531-540.pdf | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171202094603/http://abc.museucienciesjournals.cat/files/ABC-27-1-pp-531-540.pdf | archivedate=2017-12-02 }}</ref>\n\n==References== \n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Cited text===\n* {{cite book |editor1-last=Marchant |editor1-first=S. |editor2-last=Higgins |editor2-first=P.G. | year=1990 | chapter=''Phaethon rubricauda'' Red-tailed Tropicbird |title=Handbook of Australian, New Zealand & Antarctic Birds. Volume 1: Ratites to ducks; Part B, Australian pelican to ducks |place=Melbourne, Victoria |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-553068-1| pages=935\u201344 | chapter-url=http://www.nzbirdsonline.org.nz/sites/all/files/121_Red-tailed%20Tropicbird.pdf |ref={{sfnRef|Marchant|Higgins|1990}} }}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Commons category inline|Phaethon rubricauda}}\n\n{{tropicbirds}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q756640}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:tropicbird, red-tailed}}\n[[Category:Phaethontidae|red-tailed tropicbird]]\n[[Category:Birds of Christmas Island]]\n[[Category:Birds of Norfolk Island]]\n[[Category:Birds of Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Birds of the Indian Ocean]]\n[[Category:Birds of the Maluku Islands]]\n[[Category:Birds of Mauritius]]\n[[Category:Birds of the Pacific Ocean]]\n[[Category:Birds of Palau]]\n[[Category:Birds of Queensland]]\n[[Category:Birds of R\u00e9union]]\n[[Category:Birds of Western Australia]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1783|red-tailed tropicbird]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Pieter Boddaert|red-tailed tropicbird]]\n", "name_user": "CaptainCookFan", "label": "safe", "comment": "Changed the first mention of the date this bird was described by Pieter Boddaert from 1883 to 1783, which is the date given in the rest of the article, and must be the correct date as he died in 1795.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Red-tailed_tropicbird"}
{"title_page": "1893 Hurricane San Roque", "text_new": "{{Infobox Hurricane\n| Name=Hurricane San Roque\n| Type=hurricane\n| Year=1893\n| Basin=Atl\n| Image location=August 21, 1893 hurricane 3 map.png\n| Image name=[[Surface weather analysis]] of Hurricane Three on August 21, 1893, off the Mid-Atlantic U.S. coast \n| Formed=August 13, 1893\n| Dissipated=August 22, 1893\n| 1-min winds=105\n| Damages=Unknown\n| Fatalities=31\n| Areas=[[Lesser Antilles]], [[Puerto Rico]], [[New England]], [[Atlantic Canada]]\n| Hurricane season=[[1893 Atlantic hurricane season]]\n}}\n\n'''Hurricane San Roque''' was a destructive [[tropical cyclone]] in August 1893 that principally affected [[Puerto Rico]], eastern [[New England]], and [[Nova Scotia]]. Its informal name in Puerto Rico arises from the [[feast day]] of [[Saint Roch]], or San Roque in Spanish, which coincided with the hurricane's landfall on that island.{{#tag:ref|The Puerto Rican tradition of referring to intense hurricanes by the names of Catholic saints being commemorated on the corresponding [[feast day]]s was among the earliest informal [[tropical cyclone naming]] systems, and lasted for centuries prior to the introduction of standardized naming conventions.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tropical Cyclone Naming History and Retired Names|agency=[[National Hurricane Center]]|publisher=[[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]]|accessdate=April 9, 2020|url=https://www.nhc.noaa.gov/aboutnames_history.shtml}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Yanez, Anthony|date=September 7, 2017|title=From Adrian to Zelda: A History of Hurricane Names|newspaper=[[KNBC|NBC4 Southern California]]|url=https://www.nbclosangeles.com/local/how-hurricanes-get-their-names-storms-weather/23317/|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> This was the third storm bearing the local name \"San Roque\".<ref name=\"meta\"/> See also: [[Calendar of saints#Connection to tropical cyclones|Calendar of saints \u00a7 Connection to tropical cyclones]].|group=\"nb\"}} In Nova Scotia, the storm was called the \"Second Great August Gale\". For a short time on August 22, it was one of four simultaneously active hurricanes in the Atlantic Ocean. The system was first observed on August 13 at low latitudes east of the [[Lesser Antilles]]. It grew to be a powerful, slow-moving hurricane in the [[Caribbean Sea]], and at 00:00 [[UTC]] on August 17, it struck Puerto Rico at the equivalence of Category 3 on the modern-day [[Saffir\u2013Simpson scale]]. The [[eye (cyclone)|eye]] crossed the island from southeast to northwest, spending seven hours over the island. This was the first tropical cyclone event in Puerto Rico in which [[History of Atlantic hurricane warnings|warning flags]] were used for communicating the level of danger to the public. A prolonged period of strong winds caused widespread destruction on the island, most notably along the northern coast. A large number of homes sustained varying degrees of damage, with flimsy shacks belonging to poor workers faring the worst; many families were left homeless. Telegraph communications were severed across the island. Around the capital city of [[San Juan, Puerto Rico|San Juan]], many trees and fences were blown down, and two hospitals were unroofed. In addition to the deleterious winds, several days of heavy rainfall in interior sectors triggered extensive river flooding. The combined effects of rain and wind destroyed fields of crops, most notably coffee and sugar cane. Four people were killed in Puerto Rico.\n\nOn August 19, the hurricane began to turn northeastward and accelerate. Although its center remained far away from the [[United States]], heavy rainfall and gale-force winds overspread the country's [[East Coast of the United States|East Coast]] on August 20 and 21. Eastern [[New England]] experienced conditions equivalent to a particularly intense [[nor'easter]], with winds as high as {{convert|72|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} recorded on [[Block Island]]. Across [[Rhode Island]] and [[Massachusetts]], grain crops were flattened and and orchards were stripped of their fruit. The esteemed racing yacht [[Volunteer (yacht)|''Volunteer'']] was badly damaged after crashing upon the rocky shoreline. After passing about {{convert|150|mi|km|abbr=on}} southeast of [[Nantucket]], the now-rapidly moving system weakened and transitioned into an [[extratropical cyclone]], and at 00:00 UTC on August 22, made landfall in Nova Scotia at [[St. Margarets Bay, Nova Scotia|St. Margarets Bay]]. Damage to utility wires in [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]] cut power and communications services, and a child was electrocuted to death by a downed power line. The storm wrought havoc on ships and boats throughout [[Atlantic Canada]], as well as the [[Gasp\u00e9 Peninsula]] of [[Quebec]], becoming \"one of the most notorious marine storms in the history of Nova Scotia\".<ref name=\"wreck\"/> The greatest maritime tragedy was the wreck of the [[steamer]] ''Dorcas'' and its barge, ''Etta Stewart'', which were caught in the gale while underway east of Halifax. The two ships drifted toward shore late at night on August 21, and struck a rocky [[shoal]] near the entrance to [[Three Fathom Harbour, Nova Scotia|Three Fathom Harbour]]. ''Dorcas'' capsized and was driven ashore, while ''Etta Stewart'' broke up in the pounding surf. All crew members and passengers on the two vessels, totaling 24 people, were killed. Two more people died when their boat sank on [[Trinity Bay (Newfoundland and Labrador)|Trinity Bay]] in [[Newfoundland (island)|Newfoundland]], for a storm total of 31 fatalities. \n\n==Meteorological history==\n{{storm path|1893 Atlantic hurricane 3 track.png}}\nBecause of scarce meteorological observations, little is known about Hurricane San Roque's early history. According to contemporaneous accounts, it most likely originated in the [[Intertropical Convergence Zone]] off the northern coast of South America.<ref name=\"mwr\">{{cite journal|title=Atmospheric pressure (expressed in inches and hundredths)|date=August 1893|page=207|journal=[[Monthly Weather Review]]|publisher=[[American Meteorological Society]]|volume=21|number=8|url=ftp://ftp.library.noaa.gov/docs.lib/htdocs/rescue/mwr/021/mwr-021-08-0205c.pdf|issn=0027-0644}}</ref> In the [[Atlantic hurricane database]], its formation as a tropical storm is entered on August 13, corresponding with the first observation of the system, about {{convert|730|mi|km|abbr=on}} east of [[Trinidad and Tobago]]. It crossed the [[Lesser Antilles]] island arc on August 15, passing between [[Dominica]] and [[Guadeloupe]].<ref name=\"hurdat\">{{cite web|url=https://www.aoml.noaa.gov/hrd/hurdat/hurdat2.html|format=Database|agency=[[Hurricane Research Division]]|title=Atlantic hurricane best track (HURDAT version 2)|date=2019|publisher=[[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]]|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The intensifying cyclone moved toward the northwest and by 18:00 [[UTC]] on August 16, it was centered very close to [[St. Croix]].<ref name=\"part\"/> Upon receiving the first report of the storm from [[Saint Thomas, U.S. Virgin Islands|Saint Thomas]], the [[U.S. Weather Bureau]] issued a special bulletin relaying the current position of the hurricane, forecasting its [[recurvature]] by August 21, and advising shipping interests to take necessary precautions.<ref name=\"mwr\"/> At 00:00 UTC on August 17, the cyclone made landfall near [[Patillas, Puerto Rico]], as the equivalent of a Category 3 major hurricane on the modern-day [[Saffir\u2013Simpson scale]].<ref name=\"hurdat\"/><ref name=\"Mujica\">{{Cite report|first=Frank |last=M\u00fajica-Baker |title=Huracanes y Tormentas que han afectadi a Puerto Rico |publisher=Estado Libre Asociado de Puerto Rico, Agencia Estatal para el Manejo de Emergencias, and Administracion de Desastres |url=http://www.gobierno.pr/NR/rdonlyres/49EA64D0-305B-4881-8B85-04B518004BD5/0/Ciclones_en_PR.pdf |page=10 |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |language=Spanish}}</ref> Modern [[HURDAT#Reanalysis projects|reanalysis]] efforts estimated the intensity at landfall through the severity of wind damage in Puerto Rico, which was consistent with F2 on the [[Fujita scale]].<ref name=\"meta\">{{cite web|agency=[[Hurricane Research Division]]|title=Documentation of Atlantic Tropical Cyclones Changes in HURDAT|date=November 2019|publisher=[[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]]|accessdate=March 29, 2020|url=http://www.aoml.noaa.gov/hrd/hurdat/metadata_master.html}}</ref> The [[eye (cyclone)|eye]] was marked by a period of stark calm as it crossed the island such that during its passage, some people believed the storm to be over.<ref name=\"roque\"/> At [[San Juan, Puerto Rico|San Juan]], to the north of the center path, [[barometric pressure]] fell to {{convert|987.8|mbar|inHg|lk=on|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"Mujica\"/> Approximately seven hours after moving ashore, the center exited Puerto Rico between [[Isabela barrio-pueblo|Isabela]] and [[Quebradillas barrio-pueblo|Quebradillas]].<ref name=\"part\"/><ref name=\"Mujica\"/>\n\nOn August 18, the storm system was noted north of [[Hispaniola]]. Around the same time, weather stations along the Atlantic coast of the [[Southeastern U.S.]] started to register its distant influence.<ref name=\"mwr\"/> It passed over or close to the [[Turks and Caicos Islands]].<ref name=\"part\"/> On August 19, while situated northeast of [[the Bahamas]], the hurricane began its [[recurvature]] to the north and ultimately northeast.<ref name=\"hurdat\"/> Late on August 20 into the following day, [[gale]]s and heavy rainfall overspread the [[Mid-Atlantic (United States)|Mid-Atlantic]] and [[Northeastern United States|Northeast]] coasts.<ref name=\"mwr\"/> The hurricane weakened as it gained latitude and early on August 21, it passed approximately {{convert|185|mi|km|abbr=on|sigfig=2}} east of [[Cape Hatteras]]. Later that day, the accelerating storm passed within {{convert|150|mi|km|abbr=on}} of [[Nantucket]]. At 00:00 UTC on August 22, it was one of four active hurricanes in the Atlantic Ocean, and the first of three to impact the [[U.S. East Coast]] in the span of eight days; [[1893 New York hurricane|Hurricane Four]] would strike western [[Long Island]] on August 24, and [[1893 Sea Islands hurricane|Hurricane Six]] ravaged the [[Sea Islands]] on August 28 before moving northward along the Eastern Seaboard.<ref name=\"hurdat\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=The third and last|date=August 30, 1893|page=1|newspaper=Fall River Daily Evening News|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48395855/fall-river-daily-evening-news/|accessdate=April 10, 2020|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> \n\nThough some modern researchers catalogued the system as a hurricane on its final approach to [[Nova Scotia]], the official [[HURDAT#Reanalysis projects|Atlantic hurricane reanalsysis project]] found no conclusive evidence of hurricane-force winds in Canada.<ref name=\"part\"/><ref name=\"meta\"/> In the early morning hours of August 22, the storm made landfall in Nova Scotia via [[St. Margarets Bay, Nova Scotia|St. Margarets Bay]],<ref name=\"ec\"/> as an [[extratropical cyclone]].<ref name=\"hurdat\"/> Its northeasterly path placed greater [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]] in the typically intense right-front quadrant of the storm center; this would not occur again until [[Hurricane Juan]] in 2003.<ref name=\"ec\"/> After rapidly crossing Nova Scotia, the extratropical system impacted the island of [[Newfoundland (island)|Newfoundland]] and continued eastward into the North Atlantic for several more days.<ref name=\"hurdat\"/> \n\n==Impact==\nThe intensifying hurricane brought stormy conditions to the [[Lesser Antilles]] from [[Martinique]] to the [[Virgin Islands]]. In [[Saint Thomas, U.S. Virgin Islands|Saint Thomas]], boats and docks were damaged, trees were blown down, and houses were unroofed.<ref name=\"amagos\"/><ref name=\"historia\"/>\n\n===Puerto Rico===\nFor the first time in Puerto Rico's history, [[History of Atlantic hurricane warnings|warning flags]] were used to alert the public of the approaching hurricane.<ref name=\"Mujica\"/> Officials in San Juan first hoisted cautionary red flags during the mid-morning on August 16, upgraded three hours later to more urgent yellow and blue signals, and finally to black flags to mark the cyclone's onslaught.<ref name=\"pro1867\">{{cite web|author=Rivera, Abimael Castro and Barreto, Amarilys Arocho|title=Los \u00faltimos Santos de categor\u00eda 3|publisher=University of Puerto Rico at Mayag\u00fcez|work=Proyecto 1867|language=Spanish|accessdate=April 1, 2020|url=https://www.proyecto1867.com/los-uacuteltimos-santos-de-categoriacutea-3.html}}</ref> By mid-afternoon the [[Port of San Juan]] was closed; although orders were given to evacuate ships from the port, the short notice and lack of available [[tugboats]] meant some vessels had to ride out the storm at anchor, exposed to the elements.<ref name=\"temporal\">{{cite news|title=El temporal en la Isla|language=Spanish|date=August 18, 1893|newspaper=La Correspondencia de Puerto Rico|page=2|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47647554/la-correspondencia-de-puerto-rico/|accessdate=March 30, 2020|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> Boats at dock were required to be unloaded of their cargo.<ref name=\"amagos\">{{cite news|title=Amagos de temporal|date=August 16, 1893|newspaper=La Correspondencia de Puerto Rico|page=2|language=Spanish|accessdate=March 31, 2020|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47646841/la-correspondencia-de-puerto-rico/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> When the severity of the hurricane became clear, local officials ensured moorings were secure and orchestrated the positioning of ships to minimize risk of collisions.<ref name=\"roque\"/> Bus and tram services were suspended as conditions worsened, leaving many residents unable to reach their homes for the night.<ref name=\"roque\"/> \n\nOn the night of August 16\u201317, winds of {{convert|55|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} and {{convert|50|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} were recorded in San Juan and [[Mayag\u00fcez, Puerto Rico|Mayag\u00fcez]], respectively, before both recording [[anemometers]] were blown away.<ref name=\"part\"/> It was the long duration of the storm, rather than its intensity alone, which made it so destructive.<ref name=\"historia\">{{cite book|author=Salivia, Luis A.|title=Historia de los temporales de Puerto Rico y las Antillas, 1492 a 1970|edition=2nd|language=Spanish|year=1972|publisher=Editorial Edil|oclc=807374|pages=232\u2013234}}</ref> \n\nThe northern coast suffered most harshly as the storm wrought havoc on crops, telegraph infrastructure, and buildings of varying construction quality.<ref name=\"temporal\"/> Poorly built shacks and huts, the residences of impoverished workers, fared the worst.<ref name=\"pro1867\"/> In [[Camuy, Puerto Rico|Camuy]], the storm destroyed up to 20 houses and damaged others, uprooted trees, and resulted in two small fires. In the aftermath, the mayor of Camuy appointed a special commission to facilitate the transfer of relief funds to storm victims. Many of the homeless families received donations from neighbors to help cover basic expenses. The winds unroofed many small huts near the shore of Arecibo, forcing their residents to flee for cover, and knocked down wooden and brick fences. The local telegraph station was rendered inoperative, slowing the initial spread of damage reports.<ref name=\"temporal\"/> Both the city and outlying rural areas of [[Manat\u00ed, Puerto Rico|Manat\u00ed]] incurred widespread damage, with dozens of [[Thatching|thatch roofs]] blown off and some homes left uninhabitable. The basement of a colectur\u00eda, or [[tithe]] barn, was provided as temporary shelter to poor and injured storm victims. Numerous people in [[Hatillo, Puerto Rico|Hatillo]] were left homeless by the hurricane, and reports there described trees being blown some distance from where they once stood.<ref name=\"temporal\"/> Severe damage befell [[Vega Baja, Puerto Rico|Vega Baja]], with at least 28 houses destroyed and many banana, coconut, and other fruit trees toppled.<ref name=\"noticias\"/> Eight houses were destroyed in [[Isabela, Puerto Rico|Isabela]], and one family required rescue there after their home was crushed under the roof of an adjacent building. Many poor families became homeless; some were offered quarters in the homes of local government and Civil Guard officials.<ref name=\"noticias\"/> A church [[atrium]] in the town was destroyed.<ref name=\"demo\">{{cite news|title=Noticias|date=August 24, 1893|newspaper=La Democracia|page=3|language=Spanish|accessdate=March 31, 2020|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47647318/la-democracia/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref>\n\nNumerous [[peasant]] huts were destroyed in [[Bayam\u00f3n, Puerto Rico|Bayam\u00f3n]], along with the roofs of more substantial structures. All telegraph wires and poles in the community were blown down.<ref name=\"temporal\"/> Seven or eight houses were destroyed in [[Trujillo Alto, Puerto Rico|Trujillo Alto]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Noticias generales|date=August 23, 1893|newspaper=La Correspondencia de Puerto Rico|page=2|language=Spanish|accessdate=March 31, 2020|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47647184/la-correspondencia-de-puerto-rico/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> The effects proved less severe than feared in [[Utuado, Puerto Rico|Utuado]], though banana plantations suffered.<ref name=\"noticias\">{{cite news|title=Noticias del temporal|date=August 20, 1893|page=2|newspaper=La Correspondencia de Puerto Rico|language=Spanish|accessdate=March 31, 2020|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47647208/la-correspondencia-de-puerto-rico/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> Several peasant houses were destroyed in [[Toa Baja, Puerto Rico|Toa Baja]]. In [[Dorado, Puerto Rico|Dorado]], numerous houses were damaged and six were destroyed, their residents forced to seek shelter in government buildings.<ref name=\"temporal\"/> The storm was not as severe in San Juan as in other towns, although destruction was still widespread. Notably, one hospital was badly damaged, with the roof over the maternity ward being peeled away. Timbers and metal roofing tiles were blown a great distance from the structure. Patients had to be transferred to a nearby military hospital. Another hospital in the [[Puerta de Tierra]] subbarrio was also unroofed.<ref name=\"del16\"/> With telegraph wires downed in all directions, San Juan initially had no contact with the rest of the island.<ref name=\"roque\"/> Many gas lanterns were broken and an electric light lost its power supply. Palm and fruit trees were uprooted throughout the city, while garden fences and [[awning]]s were blown down. Many houses, huts, businesses, and public facilities around San Juan sustained varying degrees of structural damage.<ref name=\"roque\"/> Several houses in the nearby town of [[Cata\u00f1o]] were demolished.<ref name=\"del16\"/>\n\nHeavy rainfall also occurred in addition to the powerful winds, lasting two to three days in some locations.<ref name=\"del16\">{{cite news|title=El temporal del 16|date=August 21, 1893|newspaper=La Democracia|language=Spanish|page=3|accessdate=March 30, 2020|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47647094/la-democracia/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> The capital city of San Juan recorded {{convert|2.36|in|mm|abbr=on}} of precipitation.<ref name=\"Mujica\"/> Further inland, rivers overflowed their banks with the torrential rainfall, inundating wide tracts of low-lying terrain.<ref name=\"temporal\"/> Among the major rivers flooded were the [[R\u00edo Grande de Arecibo]], [[R\u00edo Grande de Manat\u00ed]], and [[Santiago River (Puerto Rico)|Santiago]]. Floodwaters ruined harvests of crops like rice, corn, and sugar cane.<ref name=\"temporal\"/> One farmer in [[Humacao, Puerto Rico|Humacao]], near the eastern coast, reported the loss of about {{convert|80|acre|ha|lk=on}} of sugar cane fields.<ref name=\"noticias\"/> The neighborhood of Marina in [[Gurabo, Puerto Rico|Gurabo]] had to be evacuated due to river flooding. The mayor of the town started a donation drive for poor families. One worker on a [[hacienda]] died, and his burial was delayed until flooding in the local cemetery receded.<ref name=\"noticias\"/> Many railways and thoroughfares, including the road between [[Cata\u00f1o]] and [[Bayam\u00f3n]], were made impassable by both fallen trees and deep floodwaters.<ref name=\"del16\"/> With mail routes blocked and telegraph communications severed, the full extent of the destruction was slow to be revealed.<ref name=\"pro1867\"/> On the day after the storm, workers began to clear railways and reestablish communications.<ref name=\"temporal\"/> \n\nSeveral ships were destroyed and others left stranded on the beach. The [[schooner]] ''Enriqueta'' broke free and crashed into a pier; the sloop ''Tomasito'' grounded out, crushing its [[keel]]; and another sloop, the ''Maria Artau'', went ashore at [[Palo Seco, Toa Baja, Puerto Rico|Palo Seco]], with all hands saved by another crew.<ref name=\"del16\"/><ref name=\"roque\"/> At [[Arecibo]], the British schooner ''Robbie Godfrey'' broke free from its [[mooring]]s in port while it being loaded with sugar. The ship was driven aground and destroyed, along with its cargo, but all hands were able to reach the shore with the assistance of rescue brigades. One crewman was hospitalized for an arm injury.<ref name=\"temporal\"/><ref name=\"del16\"/> The schooner ''Martiniguesi'', loaded with cattle en route to Martinique, went ashore at [[Maunabo, Puerto Rico|Maunabo]], with one crewman and numerous head of cattle killed.<ref name=\"noticias\"/> The sloop ''Pepito'' was lost at Cata\u00f1o.<ref name=\"del16\"/> [[Sea bathing|Sea baths]] along the shore were destroyed.<ref name=\"roque\"/> \n\nAmong all agricultural losses, that of the year's coffee crop was most significant.<ref name=\"Mujica\"/> Losses to the coffee harvest in [[Lares, Puerto Rico|Lares]] alone were estimated at 500,000 [[Puerto Rican peso]]s. In some localities, only crops in sheltered valleys survived.<ref name=\"noticias\"/> As much as 60% of the coffee harvest was lost to the storm in [[Comer\u00edo, Puerto Rico|Comer\u00edo]].<ref name=\"streetlights\">{{cite news|title=Noticias generales|date=August 23, 1893|newspaper=La Correspondencia de Puerto Rico|language=Spanish|page=3|accessdate=March 31, 2020|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47647486/la-correspondencia-de-puerto-rico/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> The storm was locally referred to as \"San Roque\" since it began on the [[calendar of saints|feast day]] of [[Saint Roch]], known as San Roque in Spanish.<ref name=\"part\">{{cite report|author1=Fern\u00e1ndez-Partag\u00e1s, Jos\u00e9|author2=Diaz, Henry F.|publisher=[[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]]|year=1995|title=A Reconstruction of Historical Tropical Cyclone Frequency in the Atlantic from Documentary and other Historical Sources Part IV: 1891\u20131900: Year 1893|accessdate=March 29, 2020|url=https://www.aoml.noaa.gov/hrd/Landsea/Partagas/1891-1893/1893_1.pdf|pages=40\u201342|agency=[[Hurricane Research Division]]}}</ref><ref name=\"roque\">{{cite news|title=El temporal|date=August 17, 1893|newspaper=La Correspondencia de Puerto Rico|language=Spanish|page=2|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47646814/la-correspondencia-de-puerto-rico/|accessdate=March 30, 2020|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> It was among the last significant tropical cyclones to affect Puerto Rico before the island came under [[History of Puerto Rico#United States rule (1898\u2013present)|United States rule]] in 1898.<ref name=\"historia\"/> Some contemporary accounts drew comparisons to the devastating [[1876 San Felipe hurricane|San Felipe hurricane]] of 1876.<ref name=\"noticias\"/> The hurricane caused four known fatalities in Puerto Rico.<ref name=\"Mujica\"/>\n\n===United States===\n[[File:4a04495v.jpg|right|thumb|upright=1.5|The racing yacht ''[[Volunteer (yacht)|Volunteer]]'' was badly damaged by the storm in Massachusetts.]] \nOn the far western periphery of the hurricane, parts of [[Florida]] experienced gusty winds, reaching {{convert|35|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} in [[Key West, Florida|Key West]] and {{convert|38|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} in [[Jupiter, Florida|Jupiter]], on August 20. A closer pass to [[New England]] the following day resulted in severe [[nor'easter]]-like conditions, with winds peaking at {{convert|72|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} on [[Block Island]] and {{convert|52|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} on [[Nantucket]]. In [[Woods Hole, Massachusetts]], winds to {{convert|60|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} were reported. Tropical storm-force winds extended north to [[Eastport, Maine|Eastport]].<ref name=\"part\"/> It was described as \"the most severe August storm known for many years\" in [[Chatham, Massachusetts|Chatham]];<ref name=\"severe\"/> in [[Oak Bluffs, Massachusetts|Oak Bluffs]] (then called Cottage City) on [[Martha's Vineyard]], \"without a precedent during the summer season\".<ref name=\"cottage\">{{cite news|title=Majestic ocean|date=August 22, 1893|page=5|newspaper=The Boston Globe|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48104386/the-boston-globe/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> The [[U.S. Weather Bureau]] had predicted bad weather days for several days, and [[tropical cyclone watches and warnings|warning signals]] were raised along the coast 24 hours before onset. Consequently, shipping interests generally endured the storm without major losses.<ref name=\"wild\">{{cite news|title=Wild northeaster|date=August 22, 1893|newspaper=The Boston Globe|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}} \n*[https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48161693/the-boston-globe/ Page 1]\n*[https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48166433/the-boston-globe/ Page 8]</ref>\n\nThroughout [[Cape Cod and the Islands]], trees, fences, and utility wires were blown down. Apple and pear trees were stripped of their fruit and vegetable crops suffered. Floodwaters inundated streets and cellars while the driving rain forced inside east-facing walls.<ref name=\"severe\">{{cite news|title=Driven on the rocks|date=August 22, 1893|page=1|newspaper=Hartford Courant|accessdate=April 5, 2020|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48100435/hartford-courant/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref><ref name=\"cottage\"/> Many roads were littered with the broken branches of large trees; some smaller trees and shrubs were uprooted entirely.<ref name=\"wild\"/> The [[racing yacht]] ''[[Volunteer (yacht)|Volunteer]]'', winner of the 1887 [[America's Cup]], broke free from its anchorage and was tossed onto the rocks near the entrance to Hadley's Harbor on [[Naushon Island]], Massachusetts. Pounding seas battered the vessel, breaking up much of its deck and flooding the hull. After an unsuccessful attempt by another yacht to rescue ''Volunteer'' with the storm still raging, a tugboat was able to dislodge the stricken craft and tow it to a nearby wharf.<ref name=\"severe\"/><ref name=\"wild\"/> Nearby, a [[schooner]] dragged anchor and grounded out during the course of the storm.<ref name=\"severe\"/> \n\nThe storm disabled several ships around Martha's Vineyard, including the [[schooners]] ''Sarah Louise'' and ''Clara Jane'', both of which were damaged, and the [[sloop]] ''Cassie'', left stranded on the shore. Numerous other fishing vessels lost their anchors, sails, or [[seine]] boats. The maritime havoc extended westward to [[New Jersey]]'s [[Sandy Hook]], where a yacht was wrecked.<ref name=\"cottage\"/> President [[Grover Cleveland]] sheltered in his summer home of [[Gray Gables]]  during the storm. His yacht was narrowly saved from being swept ashore.<ref name=\"wild\"/> Rainfall in [[Boston]] commended in the late evening of August 20 and continued through the following afternoon, totaling {{convert|1.65|in|mm|abbr=on}}. With these downpours, the [[Charles River]] breached its banks to flood the [[Cambridgeport, Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridgeport]] neighborhood of [[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge]] up to {{convert|3|ft|m|abbr=on|sigfig=1}} deep. At [[Nantasket Beach]] in the town of [[Hull, Massachusetts|Hull]], immense swells drew crowds of onlookers, photographers, and artists before coastal installations began to crumble. Roads in [[Plymouth, Massachusetts|Plymouth]] were littered with broken tree limbs, and several pleasure craft in [[Plymouth Harbor]] were blown aground.<ref name=\"wild\"/> \n\n\"Very great\" damage to grain crops also plagued the neighboring state of [[Rhode Island]].<ref name=\"wild\"/><ref name=\"carnival\">{{cite news|title=High carnival|date=August 21, 1893|page=1|newspaper=The Boston Globe|accessdate=April 6, 2020|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48168611/the-boston-globe/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> Two sailors were rescued after their boat capsized in [[Newport, Rhode Island|Newport Harbor]]. A fishing schooner drifted to sea with its crew aboard, ultimately being rescued by a tug south of the [[Brenton Reef Light]]. Numerous ships rode out the storm in the shelter of [[Dutch Island (Rhode Island)|Dutch Island]] in the West Passage of [[Narragansett Bay]], being \"tossed like cockle shells\" at the height of the storm. One of the schooner ''Ethel Swift''{{'}}s two anchor chains broke, resulting in a wreck on the western shore of the bay. The schooner's crew of four was safely rescued.<ref name=\"gale\">{{cite news|title=An August gale|date=August 22, 1893|newspaper=Fall River Daily Evening News|page=1|accessdate=April 6, 2020|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48167668/fall-river-daily-evening-news/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> Further up the bay, three ships were blown aground on [[Prudence Island]].<ref name=\"carnival\"/>  A yacht race set for August 21 around [[Newport, Rhode Island|Newport]] was postponed because of the bad weather.<ref>{{cite news|title=Race postponed|date=August 21, 1893|page=1|newspaper=The Boston Globe|accessdate=April 6, 2020|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48168706/the-boston-globe/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> Some 17 [[fire alarm call box]]es in [[Charlestown, Rhode Island]], were rendered inoperative, so firefighters had to patrol the town continuously through the night of August 20\u201321.<ref name=\"carnival\"/> \n\n===Atlantic Canada===\nThough in a weakened state, the cyclone still battered the Atlantic provinces of Canada, becoming \"one of the most notorious marine storms in the history of Nova Scotia\".<ref name=\"wreck\">{{cite magazine|author=MacDonald, Michael|date=June 1, 1994|title=Wreck of the Dochas & the Etta Stewart|pages=41\u201352|issue=66|magazine=Cape Brenton's Magazine|accessdate=April 9, 2020|url=http://capebretonsmagazine.com/modules/publisher/item.php?itemid=4670|oclc=67618392}}</ref> There, the storm came to be known as the \"Second Great August Gale\", in reference to a [[1873 Atlantic hurricane season#Hurricane Two|catastrophic hurricane]] in August 1837.<ref name=\"ec\">{{cite web|author=Bowyer, Peter|date=October 29, 2003|title=Hurricane Juan Storm Summary|publisher=[[Environment and Climate Change Canada]]|accessdate=April 8, 2020|url=https://www.ec.gc.ca/ouragans-hurricanes/default.asp?lang=en&n=B1A7B85A-1}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Davey, William J. and MacKinnon, Richard|title=Dictionary of Cape Breton English|year=2016|publisher=University of Toronto Press|isbn=9781442615991|accessdate=April 8, 2020|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=y4RyDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA4#v=onepage&q&f=false|page=4|via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref> Throughout [[the Maritimes]], dozens of large ships were stranded or destroyed.<ref name=\"wreck\"/> Warning signals were hoisted in Nova Scotia on the evening of August 20, and ultimately lowered near midday on August 22.<ref name=\"canada\">{{cite journal|author=Carpmael, Charles|title=Storm warnings|date=December 20, 1893|journal=Monthly Weather Review|volume=16|page=10|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FRdKAQAAMAAJ&pg=RA40-PA14|via=[[Google Books]]|publisher=[[Meteorological Service of Canada]]|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref> \n\nIn [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]], rain and wind began in the early afternoon on August 21 and grew in severity through the night. The city was plunged into darkness and cut off from the outside world as electric and communications wires fell. Severed power lines sparked small fires and posed a hazard to public safety; one young girl was electrocuted and killed by a live wire, and two more people received non-life-threatening shocks while attempting to recover her body. Parks, public gardens, and cemeteries throughout the city suffered extensive damage, with many large trees being destroyed.<ref name=\"night\">{{cite news|title=Night of terror|date=August 22, 1893|newspaper=The Boston Globe|page=5|accessdate=April 8, 2020|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48293798/the-boston-globe/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> Many ships and boats were wrecked or blown ashore in [[Halifax Harbour]]. In one instance, after colliding with a wharf and being struck by two [[pontoon (boat)|pontoon boats]], the schooner ''Janie R.''{{'}}s cargo of [[lime (material)|lime]] swelled with the influx of seawater to the point of breaking the ship apart.<ref name=\"gazette\">{{cite news|title=It was an awful gale|date=August 23, 1893|page=1|newspaper=The Gazette|accessdate=April 8, 2020|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48294534/the-gazette/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> Trees were uprooted and chimneys toppled in [[Liverpool, Nova Scotia|Liverpool]].<ref name=\"canada\"/> The storm was less severe in [[Yarmouth, Nova Scotia|Yarmouth]], at the western end of the province, but still washed out streets and blew down trees there.<ref name=\"gazette\"/> The winds damaged trees, fences, and some buildings in [[Amherst, Nova Scotia|Amherst]], and crops in the surrounding countryside were flattened.<ref name=\"gazette\"/> In [[Cumberland County, Nova Scotia|Cumberland County]], the Palmerston Bridge over the upper [[Pugwash, Nova Scotia|Pugwash Harbor]] was badly damaged, and two [[barque]]s were blown ashore at [[Northport, Nova Scotia|Northport]].<ref name=\"gazette\"/> Several schooners were wrecked along the shores of [[Cape Breton]];<ref name=\"gazette\"/> in [[Ingonish]], two ships were left stranded on the shore and six fishing boats drifted out to sea. Residents of the rural community fled their homes at the height of the storm to sheek shelter in nearby valleys.<ref name=\"canada\"/> \n\nLate on the night of August 21, the [[steamer]] ''Dorcas'', with [[barge]] ''Etta Stewart'' in tow, wrecked on the notoriously hazardous [[reef]] surrounding Shut-In Island, near the entrance to [[Three Fathom Harbour, Nova Scotia|Three Fathom Harbour]].<ref name=\"wreck\"/><ref name=\"pioneer\">{{cite magazine|author=McNeil, Alexander|magazine=The Suburban|volume=5|issue=11|page=4|date=April 13, 1907|title=Pioneers of Nova Scotia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NEo_AAAAYAAJ&pg=RA10-PA4|accessdate=April 9, 2020|oclc=235821506|via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref> Both vessels were loaded with coal en route from [[Sydney, Nova Scotia|Sydney]] to Halifax. It is likely that the barge took on water in the heavy seas, making it impossible to steer and causing both ships to drift toward shore in the strong southerly winds.<ref name=\"wreck\"/> After hitting the rocks, the steamer overturned, losing its engine, boilers, and cargo, and came to rest inverted on the beach. The barge was \"dashed to pieces\", littering the shore with timbers.<ref name=\"wreck\"/><ref name=\"pioneer\"/> All crew-members and passengers, totaling 24 people, were killed: ''Dorcas'' carried a crew of 10, plus the chief engineer's pregnant wife and 4 children in his care, while 8 crewmen and one passenger were on ''Etta Stewart''.<ref name=\"wreck\"/><ref name=\"carbondale\">{{cite news|title=Twenty-four are lost|date=August 24, 1893|page=1|newspaper=The Evening Herald|accessdate=April 9, 2020|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48299494/the-evening-herald/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> All bodies but one were recovered. The small community of [[Louisbourg]], home to 16 of the victims and many of their families, was left reeling, and a rare government inquiry into the disaster was opened; it concluded that the wreck was beyond the control of Captain Angus Ferguson of ''Dorcas'', who \"sacrificed his own life in his endeavour to save those on board the two vessels\". The commissioner of the inquiry acknowledged that cutting the barge free may have increased the chance of survival for the crew and passengers of ''Dorcas'', but dismissed this as a viable option:<ref name=\"wreck\"/> \n\n{{quote|text=\"It may be considered by some that it would have been more prudent and wise for the master of the ''Dorcas'' to have disconnected his steamer from the barge at some safe time before approaching the breakers, in order to enable his vessel to reach off shore and thus have made an effort to save the larger number of people on board the steamer at the sacrifice of the less number of people on board the barge.</br>\"Had Captain Ferguson, however, acted in such a manner and been successful in saving the steamer with those on board, he would have forever been branded as a coward when he reached the land and laid himself open to the serious charge of deliberately and wilfully sacrificing the lives of many human beings for the sake of saving his own. To a brave man this would have been intolerable and it must be acknowledged that in acting as he did he displayed the genuine characteristics of a noble seaman, when, amidst the dangers of such a hurricane and wild sea, he met death at the post of duty.\"}}\n\nDespite the tragedy at Shut-In Island, the loss of life in Nova Scotia was considered low relative to the large number of shipwrecks.<ref name=\"carbondale\"/><ref name=\"seventeen\"/>\n\nExtensive storm damage, including downed trees and telegraph wires, collapsed barns, and sunk vessels along the coast, was reported in parts of [[New Brunswick]].<ref name=\"gazette\"/> At [[Point Escuminac]], winds blew at {{convert|60|to|62|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} for three hours and many fishing boats were whisked ashore. A similar situation presented itself further north in [[Shippagan]].<ref name=\"canada\"/> The cyclone severed communications between [[Prince Edward Island]] and the mainland, and inflicted widespread damage upon the province. Streets in the capital city of [[Charlottetown]] were strewn with downed tree limbs; in rural sectors, barns were destroyed. A stretch of [[breakwater]] in [[Souris, Prince Edward Island|Souris]] was washed out.<ref name=\"gazette\"/> Fishing boats in [[Tignish, Prince Edward Island|Tignish]] were shattered.<ref name=\"canada\"/> In [[Perc\u00e9, Quebec|Perc\u00e9]], on the eastern tip of [[Quebec]]'s [[Gasp\u00e9 Peninsula]], 14 fishing vessels were destroyed.<ref name=\"canada\"/> The extratropical remnants of the cyclone continued to produce strong winds over [[Newfoundland (island)|Newfoundland]], ruining crops and damaging homes that were under construction. The sinking of a boat in [[Trinity Bay (Newfoundland and Labrador)|Trinity Bay]] resulted in the drowning deaths of two men, one of them a local politician.<ref name=\"seventeen\">{{cite news|title=Seventeen were drowned|date=August 24, 1893|page=1|newspaper=The Gazette|accessdate=April 9, 2020|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48299453/the-gazette/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> [[St. John's, Newfoundland and Labrador|St. John's]] reported powerful winds that prostrated trees.<ref name=\"canada\"/> \n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Tropical cyclones}}\n*[[1899 San Ciriaco hurricane]] \u2013 followed a similar path across Puerto Rico, becoming the deadliest hurricane in the island's history<ref name=\"las\">{{cite report|url=http://latinamericanstudies.org/puertorico/hurricane.pdf|title=The Hurricane of San Ciriaco: Disaster, Politics, Society in Puerto Rico, 1899\u20131901|author=Schwartz, Stuart B.|date=1992|work=Latin American Studies|publisher=[[Duke University Press]]|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Climate of Puerto Rico]]\n*[[Hurricane Juan]] \n*[[List of New England hurricanes]]\n*[[List of Canada hurricanes]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=nb}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.aoml.noaa.gov/general/lib/lib1/nhclib/mwreviews/1893.pdf Monthly Weather Review]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:San Roque}}\n[[Category:Category 3 Atlantic hurricanes]]\n[[Category:1893 Atlantic hurricane season|3]]\n[[Category:Hurricanes in Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:Hurricanes in Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:Hurricanes in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Hurricanes in Canada]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 1893]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Hurricane\n| Name=Hurricane San Roque\n| Type=hurricane\n| Year=1893\n| Basin=Atl\n| Image location=August 21, 1893 hurricane 3 map.png\n| Image name=[[Surface weather analysis]] of Hurricane Three on August 21, 1893, off the Mid-Atlantic U.S. coast \n| Formed=August 13, 1893\n| Dissipated=August 22, 1893\n| 1-min winds=105\n| Damages=Unknown\n| Fatalities=31\n| Areas=[[Lesser Antilles]], [[Puerto Rico]], [[New England]], [[Atlantic Canada]]\n| Hurricane season=[[1893 Atlantic hurricane season]]\n}}\n\n'''Hurricane San Roque''' was a destructive [[tropical cyclone]] in August 1893 that principally affected [[Puerto Rico]], eastern [[New England]], and [[Nova Scotia]]. Its informal name in Puerto Rico arises from the [[feast day]] of [[Saint Roch]], or San Roque in Spanish, which coincided with the hurricane's landfall on that island.{{#tag:ref|The Puerto Rican tradition of referring to intense hurricanes by the names of Catholic saints being commemorated on the corresponding [[feast day]]s was among the earliest informal [[tropical cyclone naming]] systems, and lasted for centuries prior to the introduction of standardized naming conventions.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tropical Cyclone Naming History and Retired Names|agency=[[National Hurricane Center]]|publisher=[[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]]|accessdate=April 9, 2020|url=https://www.nhc.noaa.gov/aboutnames_history.shtml}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Yanez, Anthony|date=September 7, 2017|title=From Adrian to Zelda: A History of Hurricane Names|newspaper=[[KNBC|NBC4 Southern California]]|url=https://www.nbclosangeles.com/local/how-hurricanes-get-their-names-storms-weather/23317/|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> This was the third storm bearing the local name \"San Roque\".<ref name=\"meta\"/> See also: [[Calendar of saints#Connection to tropical cyclones|Calendar of saints \u00a7 Connection to tropical cyclones]].|group=\"nb\"}} In Nova Scotia, the storm was called the \"Second Great August Gale\". For a short time on August 22, it was one of four simultaneously active hurricanes in the Atlantic Ocean. The system was first observed on August 13 at low latitudes east of the [[Lesser Antilles]]. It grew to be a powerful, slow-moving hurricane in the [[Caribbean Sea]], and at 00:00 [[UTC]] on August 17, it struck Puerto Rico at the equivalence of Category 3 on the modern-day [[Saffir\u2013Simpson scale]]. The [[eye (cyclone)|eye]] crossed the island from southeast to northwest, spending seven hours over the island. This was the first tropical cyclone event in Puerto Rico in which [[History of Atlantic hurricane warnings|warning flags]] were used for communicating the level of danger to the public. A prolonged period of strong winds caused widespread destruction on the island, most notably along the northern coast. A large number of homes sustained varying degrees of damage, with flimsy shacks belonging to poor workers faring the worst; many families were left homeless. Telegraph communications were severed across the island. Around the capital city of [[San Juan, Puerto Rico|San Juan]], many trees and fences were blown down, and two hospitals were unroofed. In addition to the deleterious winds, several days of heavy rainfall in interior sectors triggered extensive river flooding. The combined effects of rain and wind destroyed fields of crops, most notably coffee and sugar cane. Four people were killed in Puerto Rico.\n\nOn August 19, the hurricane began to turn northeastward and accelerate. Although its center remained far away from the [[United States]], heavy rainfall and gale-force winds overspread the country's [[East Coast of the United States|East Coast]] on August 20 and 21. Eastern [[New England]] experienced conditions equivalent to a particularly intense [[nor'easter]], with winds as high as {{convert|72|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} recorded on [[Block Island]]. Across [[Rhode Island]] and [[Massachusetts]], grain crops were flattened and and orchards were stripped of their fruit. The esteemed racing yacht [[Volunteer (yacht)|''Volunteer'']] was badly damaged after crashing upon the rocky shoreline. After passing about {{convert|150|mi|km|abbr=on}} southeast of [[Nantucket]], the now-rapidly moving system weakened and transitioned into an [[extratropical cyclone]], and at 00:00 UTC on August 22, made landfall in Nova Scotia at [[St. Margarets Bay]]. Damage to utility wires in [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]] cut power and communications services, and a child was electrocuted to death by a downed power line. The storm wrought havoc on ships and boats throughout [[Atlantic Canada]], as well as the [[Gasp\u00e9 Peninsula]] of [[Quebec]], becoming \"one of the most notorious marine storms in the history of Nova Scotia\".<ref name=\"wreck\"/> The greatest maritime tragedy was the wreck of the [[steamer]] ''Dorcas'' and its barge, ''Etta Stewart'', which were caught in the gale while underway east of Halifax. The two ships drifted toward shore late at night on August 21, and struck a rocky [[shoal]] near the entrance to [[Three Fathom Harbour, Nova Scotia|Three Fathom Harbour]]. ''Dorcas'' capsized and was driven ashore, while ''Etta Stewart'' broke up in the pounding surf. All crew members and passengers on the two vessels, totaling 24 people, were killed. Two more people died when their boat sank on [[Trinity Bay (Newfoundland and Labrador)|Trinity Bay]] in [[Newfoundland (island)|Newfoundland]], for a storm total of 31 fatalities. \n\n==Meteorological history==\n{{storm path|1893 Atlantic hurricane 3 track.png}}\nBecause of scarce meteorological observations, little is known about Hurricane San Roque's early history. According to contemporaneous accounts, it most likely originated in the [[Intertropical Convergence Zone]] off the northern coast of South America.<ref name=\"mwr\">{{cite journal|title=Atmospheric pressure (expressed in inches and hundredths)|date=August 1893|page=207|journal=[[Monthly Weather Review]]|publisher=[[American Meteorological Society]]|volume=21|number=8|url=ftp://ftp.library.noaa.gov/docs.lib/htdocs/rescue/mwr/021/mwr-021-08-0205c.pdf|issn=0027-0644}}</ref> In the [[Atlantic hurricane database]], its formation as a tropical storm is entered on August 13, corresponding with the first observation of the system, about {{convert|730|mi|km|abbr=on}} east of [[Trinidad and Tobago]]. It crossed the [[Lesser Antilles]] island arc on August 15, passing between [[Dominica]] and [[Guadeloupe]].<ref name=\"hurdat\">{{cite web|url=https://www.aoml.noaa.gov/hrd/hurdat/hurdat2.html|format=Database|agency=[[Hurricane Research Division]]|title=Atlantic hurricane best track (HURDAT version 2)|date=2019|publisher=[[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]]|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The intensifying cyclone moved toward the northwest and by 18:00 [[UTC]] on August 16, it was centered very close to [[St. Croix]].<ref name=\"part\"/> Upon receiving the first report of the storm from [[Saint Thomas, U.S. Virgin Islands|Saint Thomas]], the [[U.S. Weather Bureau]] issued a special bulletin relaying the current position of the hurricane, forecasting its [[recurvature]] by August 21, and advising shipping interests to take necessary precautions.<ref name=\"mwr\"/> At 00:00 UTC on August 17, the cyclone made landfall near [[Patillas, Puerto Rico]], as the equivalent of a Category 3 major hurricane on the modern-day [[Saffir\u2013Simpson scale]].<ref name=\"hurdat\"/><ref name=\"Mujica\">{{Cite report|first=Frank |last=M\u00fajica-Baker |title=Huracanes y Tormentas que han afectadi a Puerto Rico |publisher=Estado Libre Asociado de Puerto Rico, Agencia Estatal para el Manejo de Emergencias, and Administracion de Desastres |url=http://www.gobierno.pr/NR/rdonlyres/49EA64D0-305B-4881-8B85-04B518004BD5/0/Ciclones_en_PR.pdf |page=10 |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |language=Spanish}}</ref> Modern [[HURDAT#Reanalysis projects|reanalysis]] efforts estimated the intensity at landfall through the severity of wind damage in Puerto Rico, which was consistent with F2 on the [[Fujita scale]].<ref name=\"meta\">{{cite web|agency=[[Hurricane Research Division]]|title=Documentation of Atlantic Tropical Cyclones Changes in HURDAT|date=November 2019|publisher=[[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]]|accessdate=March 29, 2020|url=http://www.aoml.noaa.gov/hrd/hurdat/metadata_master.html}}</ref> The [[eye (cyclone)|eye]] was marked by a period of stark calm as it crossed the island such that during its passage, some people believed the storm to be over.<ref name=\"roque\"/> At [[San Juan, Puerto Rico|San Juan]], to the north of the center path, [[barometric pressure]] fell to {{convert|987.8|mbar|inHg|lk=on|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"Mujica\"/> Approximately seven hours after moving ashore, the center exited Puerto Rico between [[Isabela barrio-pueblo|Isabela]] and [[Quebradillas barrio-pueblo|Quebradillas]].<ref name=\"part\"/><ref name=\"Mujica\"/>\n\nOn August 18, the storm system was noted north of [[Hispaniola]]. Around the same time, weather stations along the Atlantic coast of the [[Southeastern U.S.]] started to register its distant influence.<ref name=\"mwr\"/> It passed over or close to the [[Turks and Caicos Islands]].<ref name=\"part\"/> On August 19, while situated northeast of [[the Bahamas]], the hurricane began its [[recurvature]] to the north and ultimately northeast.<ref name=\"hurdat\"/> Late on August 20 into the following day, [[gale]]s and heavy rainfall overspread the [[Mid-Atlantic (United States)|Mid-Atlantic]] and [[Northeastern United States|Northeast]] coasts.<ref name=\"mwr\"/> The hurricane weakened as it gained latitude and early on August 21, it passed approximately {{convert|185|mi|km|abbr=on|sigfig=2}} east of [[Cape Hatteras]]. Later that day, the accelerating storm passed within {{convert|150|mi|km|abbr=on}} of [[Nantucket]]. At 00:00 UTC on August 22, it was one of four active hurricanes in the Atlantic Ocean, and the first of three to impact the [[U.S. East Coast]] in the span of eight days; [[1893 New York hurricane|Hurricane Four]] would strike western [[Long Island]] on August 24, and [[1893 Sea Islands hurricane|Hurricane Six]] ravaged the [[Sea Islands]] on August 28 before moving northward along the Eastern Seaboard.<ref name=\"hurdat\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=The third and last|date=August 30, 1893|page=1|newspaper=Fall River Daily Evening News|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48395855/fall-river-daily-evening-news/|accessdate=April 10, 2020|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> \n\nThough some modern researchers catalogued the system as a hurricane on its final approach to [[Nova Scotia]], the official [[HURDAT#Reanalysis projects|Atlantic hurricane reanalsysis project]] found no conclusive evidence of hurricane-force winds in Canada.<ref name=\"part\"/><ref name=\"meta\"/> In the early morning hours of August 22, the storm made landfall in Nova Scotia via [[St. Margarets Bay, Nova Scotia|St. Margarets Bay]],<ref name=\"ec\"/> as an [[extratropical cyclone]].<ref name=\"hurdat\"/> Its northeasterly path placed greater [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]] in the typically intense right-front quadrant of the storm center; this would not occur again until [[Hurricane Juan]] in 2003.<ref name=\"ec\"/> After rapidly crossing Nova Scotia, the extratropical system impacted the island of [[Newfoundland (island)|Newfoundland]] and continued eastward into the North Atlantic for several more days.<ref name=\"hurdat\"/> \n\n==Impact==\nThe intensifying hurricane brought stormy conditions to the [[Lesser Antilles]] from [[Martinique]] to the [[Virgin Islands]]. In [[Saint Thomas, U.S. Virgin Islands|Saint Thomas]], boats and docks were damaged, trees were blown down, and houses were unroofed.<ref name=\"amagos\"/><ref name=\"historia\"/>\n\n===Puerto Rico===\nFor the first time in Puerto Rico's history, [[History of Atlantic hurricane warnings|warning flags]] were used to alert the public of the approaching hurricane.<ref name=\"Mujica\"/> Officials in San Juan first hoisted cautionary red flags during the mid-morning on August 16, upgraded three hours later to more urgent yellow and blue signals, and finally to black flags to mark the cyclone's onslaught.<ref name=\"pro1867\">{{cite web|author=Rivera, Abimael Castro and Barreto, Amarilys Arocho|title=Los \u00faltimos Santos de categor\u00eda 3|publisher=University of Puerto Rico at Mayag\u00fcez|work=Proyecto 1867|language=Spanish|accessdate=April 1, 2020|url=https://www.proyecto1867.com/los-uacuteltimos-santos-de-categoriacutea-3.html}}</ref> By mid-afternoon the [[Port of San Juan]] was closed; although orders were given to evacuate ships from the port, the short notice and lack of available [[tugboats]] meant some vessels had to ride out the storm at anchor, exposed to the elements.<ref name=\"temporal\">{{cite news|title=El temporal en la Isla|language=Spanish|date=August 18, 1893|newspaper=La Correspondencia de Puerto Rico|page=2|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47647554/la-correspondencia-de-puerto-rico/|accessdate=March 30, 2020|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> Boats at dock were required to be unloaded of their cargo.<ref name=\"amagos\">{{cite news|title=Amagos de temporal|date=August 16, 1893|newspaper=La Correspondencia de Puerto Rico|page=2|language=Spanish|accessdate=March 31, 2020|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47646841/la-correspondencia-de-puerto-rico/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> When the severity of the hurricane became clear, local officials ensured moorings were secure and orchestrated the positioning of ships to minimize risk of collisions.<ref name=\"roque\"/> Bus and tram services were suspended as conditions worsened, leaving many residents unable to reach their homes for the night.<ref name=\"roque\"/> \n\nOn the night of August 16\u201317, winds of {{convert|55|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} and {{convert|50|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} were recorded in San Juan and [[Mayag\u00fcez, Puerto Rico|Mayag\u00fcez]], respectively, before both recording [[anemometers]] were blown away.<ref name=\"part\"/> It was the long duration of the storm, rather than its intensity alone, which made it so destructive.<ref name=\"historia\">{{cite book|author=Salivia, Luis A.|title=Historia de los temporales de Puerto Rico y las Antillas, 1492 a 1970|edition=2nd|language=Spanish|year=1972|publisher=Editorial Edil|oclc=807374|pages=232\u2013234}}</ref> \n\nThe northern coast suffered most harshly as the storm wrought havoc on crops, telegraph infrastructure, and buildings of varying construction quality.<ref name=\"temporal\"/> Poorly built shacks and huts, the residences of impoverished workers, fared the worst.<ref name=\"pro1867\"/> In [[Camuy, Puerto Rico|Camuy]], the storm destroyed up to 20 houses and damaged others, uprooted trees, and resulted in two small fires. In the aftermath, the mayor of Camuy appointed a special commission to facilitate the transfer of relief funds to storm victims. Many of the homeless families received donations from neighbors to help cover basic expenses. The winds unroofed many small huts near the shore of Arecibo, forcing their residents to flee for cover, and knocked down wooden and brick fences. The local telegraph station was rendered inoperative, slowing the initial spread of damage reports.<ref name=\"temporal\"/> Both the city and outlying rural areas of [[Manat\u00ed, Puerto Rico|Manat\u00ed]] incurred widespread damage, with dozens of [[Thatching|thatch roofs]] blown off and some homes left uninhabitable. The basement of a colectur\u00eda, or [[tithe]] barn, was provided as temporary shelter to poor and injured storm victims. Numerous people in [[Hatillo, Puerto Rico|Hatillo]] were left homeless by the hurricane, and reports there described trees being blown some distance from where they once stood.<ref name=\"temporal\"/> Severe damage befell [[Vega Baja, Puerto Rico|Vega Baja]], with at least 28 houses destroyed and many banana, coconut, and other fruit trees toppled.<ref name=\"noticias\"/> Eight houses were destroyed in [[Isabela, Puerto Rico|Isabela]], and one family required rescue there after their home was crushed under the roof of an adjacent building. Many poor families became homeless; some were offered quarters in the homes of local government and Civil Guard officials.<ref name=\"noticias\"/> A church [[atrium]] in the town was destroyed.<ref name=\"demo\">{{cite news|title=Noticias|date=August 24, 1893|newspaper=La Democracia|page=3|language=Spanish|accessdate=March 31, 2020|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47647318/la-democracia/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref>\n\nNumerous [[peasant]] huts were destroyed in [[Bayam\u00f3n, Puerto Rico|Bayam\u00f3n]], along with the roofs of more substantial structures. All telegraph wires and poles in the community were blown down.<ref name=\"temporal\"/> Seven or eight houses were destroyed in [[Trujillo Alto, Puerto Rico|Trujillo Alto]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Noticias generales|date=August 23, 1893|newspaper=La Correspondencia de Puerto Rico|page=2|language=Spanish|accessdate=March 31, 2020|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47647184/la-correspondencia-de-puerto-rico/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> The effects proved less severe than feared in [[Utuado, Puerto Rico|Utuado]], though banana plantations suffered.<ref name=\"noticias\">{{cite news|title=Noticias del temporal|date=August 20, 1893|page=2|newspaper=La Correspondencia de Puerto Rico|language=Spanish|accessdate=March 31, 2020|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47647208/la-correspondencia-de-puerto-rico/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> Several peasant houses were destroyed in [[Toa Baja, Puerto Rico|Toa Baja]]. In [[Dorado, Puerto Rico|Dorado]], numerous houses were damaged and six were destroyed, their residents forced to seek shelter in government buildings.<ref name=\"temporal\"/> The storm was not as severe in San Juan as in other towns, although destruction was still widespread. Notably, one hospital was badly damaged, with the roof over the maternity ward being peeled away. Timbers and metal roofing tiles were blown a great distance from the structure. Patients had to be transferred to a nearby military hospital. Another hospital in the [[Puerta de Tierra]] subbarrio was also unroofed.<ref name=\"del16\"/> With telegraph wires downed in all directions, San Juan initially had no contact with the rest of the island.<ref name=\"roque\"/> Many gas lanterns were broken and an electric light lost its power supply. Palm and fruit trees were uprooted throughout the city, while garden fences and [[awning]]s were blown down. Many houses, huts, businesses, and public facilities around San Juan sustained varying degrees of structural damage.<ref name=\"roque\"/> Several houses in the nearby town of [[Cata\u00f1o]] were demolished.<ref name=\"del16\"/>\n\nHeavy rainfall also occurred in addition to the powerful winds, lasting two to three days in some locations.<ref name=\"del16\">{{cite news|title=El temporal del 16|date=August 21, 1893|newspaper=La Democracia|language=Spanish|page=3|accessdate=March 30, 2020|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47647094/la-democracia/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> The capital city of San Juan recorded {{convert|2.36|in|mm|abbr=on}} of precipitation.<ref name=\"Mujica\"/> Further inland, rivers overflowed their banks with the torrential rainfall, inundating wide tracts of low-lying terrain.<ref name=\"temporal\"/> Among the major rivers flooded were the [[R\u00edo Grande de Arecibo]], [[R\u00edo Grande de Manat\u00ed]], and [[Santiago River (Puerto Rico)|Santiago]]. Floodwaters ruined harvests of crops like rice, corn, and sugar cane.<ref name=\"temporal\"/> One farmer in [[Humacao, Puerto Rico|Humacao]], near the eastern coast, reported the loss of about {{convert|80|acre|ha|lk=on}} of sugar cane fields.<ref name=\"noticias\"/> The neighborhood of Marina in [[Gurabo, Puerto Rico|Gurabo]] had to be evacuated due to river flooding. The mayor of the town started a donation drive for poor families. One worker on a [[hacienda]] died, and his burial was delayed until flooding in the local cemetery receded.<ref name=\"noticias\"/> Many railways and thoroughfares, including the road between [[Cata\u00f1o]] and [[Bayam\u00f3n]], were made impassable by both fallen trees and deep floodwaters.<ref name=\"del16\"/> With mail routes blocked and telegraph communications severed, the full extent of the destruction was slow to be revealed.<ref name=\"pro1867\"/> On the day after the storm, workers began to clear railways and reestablish communications.<ref name=\"temporal\"/> \n\nSeveral ships were destroyed and others left stranded on the beach. The [[schooner]] ''Enriqueta'' broke free and crashed into a pier; the sloop ''Tomasito'' grounded out, crushing its [[keel]]; and another sloop, the ''Maria Artau'', went ashore at [[Palo Seco, Toa Baja, Puerto Rico|Palo Seco]], with all hands saved by another crew.<ref name=\"del16\"/><ref name=\"roque\"/> At [[Arecibo]], the British schooner ''Robbie Godfrey'' broke free from its [[mooring]]s in port while it being loaded with sugar. The ship was driven aground and destroyed, along with its cargo, but all hands were able to reach the shore with the assistance of rescue brigades. One crewman was hospitalized for an arm injury.<ref name=\"temporal\"/><ref name=\"del16\"/> The schooner ''Martiniguesi'', loaded with cattle en route to Martinique, went ashore at [[Maunabo, Puerto Rico|Maunabo]], with one crewman and numerous head of cattle killed.<ref name=\"noticias\"/> The sloop ''Pepito'' was lost at Cata\u00f1o.<ref name=\"del16\"/> [[Sea bathing|Sea baths]] along the shore were destroyed.<ref name=\"roque\"/> \n\nAmong all agricultural losses, that of the year's coffee crop was most significant.<ref name=\"Mujica\"/> Losses to the coffee harvest in [[Lares, Puerto Rico|Lares]] alone were estimated at 500,000 [[Puerto Rican peso]]s. In some localities, only crops in sheltered valleys survived.<ref name=\"noticias\"/> As much as 60% of the coffee harvest was lost to the storm in [[Comer\u00edo, Puerto Rico|Comer\u00edo]].<ref name=\"streetlights\">{{cite news|title=Noticias generales|date=August 23, 1893|newspaper=La Correspondencia de Puerto Rico|language=Spanish|page=3|accessdate=March 31, 2020|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47647486/la-correspondencia-de-puerto-rico/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> The storm was locally referred to as \"San Roque\" since it began on the [[calendar of saints|feast day]] of [[Saint Roch]], known as San Roque in Spanish.<ref name=\"part\">{{cite report|author1=Fern\u00e1ndez-Partag\u00e1s, Jos\u00e9|author2=Diaz, Henry F.|publisher=[[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]]|year=1995|title=A Reconstruction of Historical Tropical Cyclone Frequency in the Atlantic from Documentary and other Historical Sources Part IV: 1891\u20131900: Year 1893|accessdate=March 29, 2020|url=https://www.aoml.noaa.gov/hrd/Landsea/Partagas/1891-1893/1893_1.pdf|pages=40\u201342|agency=[[Hurricane Research Division]]}}</ref><ref name=\"roque\">{{cite news|title=El temporal|date=August 17, 1893|newspaper=La Correspondencia de Puerto Rico|language=Spanish|page=2|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47646814/la-correspondencia-de-puerto-rico/|accessdate=March 30, 2020|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> It was among the last significant tropical cyclones to affect Puerto Rico before the island came under [[History of Puerto Rico#United States rule (1898\u2013present)|United States rule]] in 1898.<ref name=\"historia\"/> Some contemporary accounts drew comparisons to the devastating [[1876 San Felipe hurricane|San Felipe hurricane]] of 1876.<ref name=\"noticias\"/> The hurricane caused four known fatalities in Puerto Rico.<ref name=\"Mujica\"/>\n\n===United States===\n[[File:4a04495v.jpg|right|thumb|upright=1.5|The racing yacht ''[[Volunteer (yacht)|Volunteer]]'' was badly damaged by the storm in Massachusetts.]] \nOn the far western periphery of the hurricane, parts of [[Florida]] experienced gusty winds, reaching {{convert|35|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} in [[Key West, Florida|Key West]] and {{convert|38|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} in [[Jupiter, Florida|Jupiter]], on August 20. A closer pass to [[New England]] the following day resulted in severe [[nor'easter]]-like conditions, with winds peaking at {{convert|72|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} on [[Block Island]] and {{convert|52|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} on [[Nantucket]]. In [[Woods Hole, Massachusetts]], winds to {{convert|60|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} were reported. Tropical storm-force winds extended north to [[Eastport, Maine|Eastport]].<ref name=\"part\"/> It was described as \"the most severe August storm known for many years\" in [[Chatham, Massachusetts|Chatham]];<ref name=\"severe\"/> in [[Oak Bluffs, Massachusetts|Oak Bluffs]] (then called Cottage City) on [[Martha's Vineyard]], \"without a precedent during the summer season\".<ref name=\"cottage\">{{cite news|title=Majestic ocean|date=August 22, 1893|page=5|newspaper=The Boston Globe|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48104386/the-boston-globe/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> The [[U.S. Weather Bureau]] had predicted bad weather days for several days, and [[tropical cyclone watches and warnings|warning signals]] were raised along the coast 24 hours before onset. Consequently, shipping interests generally endured the storm without major losses.<ref name=\"wild\">{{cite news|title=Wild northeaster|date=August 22, 1893|newspaper=The Boston Globe|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}} \n*[https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48161693/the-boston-globe/ Page 1]\n*[https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48166433/the-boston-globe/ Page 8]</ref>\n\nThroughout [[Cape Cod and the Islands]], trees, fences, and utility wires were blown down. Apple and pear trees were stripped of their fruit and vegetable crops suffered. Floodwaters inundated streets and cellars while the driving rain forced inside east-facing walls.<ref name=\"severe\">{{cite news|title=Driven on the rocks|date=August 22, 1893|page=1|newspaper=Hartford Courant|accessdate=April 5, 2020|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48100435/hartford-courant/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref><ref name=\"cottage\"/> Many roads were littered with the broken branches of large trees; some smaller trees and shrubs were uprooted entirely.<ref name=\"wild\"/> The [[racing yacht]] ''[[Volunteer (yacht)|Volunteer]]'', winner of the 1887 [[America's Cup]], broke free from its anchorage and was tossed onto the rocks near the entrance to Hadley's Harbor on [[Naushon Island]], Massachusetts. Pounding seas battered the vessel, breaking up much of its deck and flooding the hull. After an unsuccessful attempt by another yacht to rescue ''Volunteer'' with the storm still raging, a tugboat was able to dislodge the stricken craft and tow it to a nearby wharf.<ref name=\"severe\"/><ref name=\"wild\"/> Nearby, a [[schooner]] dragged anchor and grounded out during the course of the storm.<ref name=\"severe\"/> \n\nThe storm disabled several ships around Martha's Vineyard, including the [[schooners]] ''Sarah Louise'' and ''Clara Jane'', both of which were damaged, and the [[sloop]] ''Cassie'', left stranded on the shore. Numerous other fishing vessels lost their anchors, sails, or [[seine]] boats. The maritime havoc extended westward to [[New Jersey]]'s [[Sandy Hook]], where a yacht was wrecked.<ref name=\"cottage\"/> President [[Grover Cleveland]] sheltered in his summer home of [[Gray Gables]]  during the storm. His yacht was narrowly saved from being swept ashore.<ref name=\"wild\"/> Rainfall in [[Boston]] commended in the late evening of August 20 and continued through the following afternoon, totaling {{convert|1.65|in|mm|abbr=on}}. With these downpours, the [[Charles River]] breached its banks to flood the [[Cambridgeport, Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridgeport]] neighborhood of [[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge]] up to {{convert|3|ft|m|abbr=on|sigfig=1}} deep. At [[Nantasket Beach]] in the town of [[Hull, Massachusetts|Hull]], immense swells drew crowds of onlookers, photographers, and artists before coastal installations began to crumble. Roads in [[Plymouth, Massachusetts|Plymouth]] were littered with broken tree limbs, and several pleasure craft in [[Plymouth Harbor]] were blown aground.<ref name=\"wild\"/> \n\n\"Very great\" damage to grain crops also plagued the neighboring state of [[Rhode Island]].<ref name=\"wild\"/><ref name=\"carnival\">{{cite news|title=High carnival|date=August 21, 1893|page=1|newspaper=The Boston Globe|accessdate=April 6, 2020|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48168611/the-boston-globe/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> Two sailors were rescued after their boat capsized in [[Newport, Rhode Island|Newport Harbor]]. A fishing schooner drifted to sea with its crew aboard, ultimately being rescued by a tug south of the [[Brenton Reef Light]]. Numerous ships rode out the storm in the shelter of [[Dutch Island (Rhode Island)|Dutch Island]] in the West Passage of [[Narragansett Bay]], being \"tossed like cockle shells\" at the height of the storm. One of the schooner ''Ethel Swift''{{'}}s two anchor chains broke, resulting in a wreck on the western shore of the bay. The schooner's crew of four was safely rescued.<ref name=\"gale\">{{cite news|title=An August gale|date=August 22, 1893|newspaper=Fall River Daily Evening News|page=1|accessdate=April 6, 2020|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48167668/fall-river-daily-evening-news/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> Further up the bay, three ships were blown aground on [[Prudence Island]].<ref name=\"carnival\"/>  A yacht race set for August 21 around [[Newport, Rhode Island|Newport]] was postponed because of the bad weather.<ref>{{cite news|title=Race postponed|date=August 21, 1893|page=1|newspaper=The Boston Globe|accessdate=April 6, 2020|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48168706/the-boston-globe/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> Some 17 [[fire alarm call box]]es in [[Charlestown, Rhode Island]], were rendered inoperative, so firefighters had to patrol the town continuously through the night of August 20\u201321.<ref name=\"carnival\"/> \n\n===Atlantic Canada===\nThough in a weakened state, the cyclone still battered the Atlantic provinces of Canada, becoming \"one of the most notorious marine storms in the history of Nova Scotia\".<ref name=\"wreck\">{{cite magazine|author=MacDonald, Michael|date=June 1, 1994|title=Wreck of the Dochas & the Etta Stewart|pages=41\u201352|issue=66|magazine=Cape Brenton's Magazine|accessdate=April 9, 2020|url=http://capebretonsmagazine.com/modules/publisher/item.php?itemid=4670|oclc=67618392}}</ref> There, the storm came to be known as the \"Second Great August Gale\", in reference to a [[1873 Atlantic hurricane season#Hurricane Two|catastrophic hurricane]] in August 1837.<ref name=\"ec\">{{cite web|author=Bowyer, Peter|date=October 29, 2003|title=Hurricane Juan Storm Summary|publisher=[[Environment and Climate Change Canada]]|accessdate=April 8, 2020|url=https://www.ec.gc.ca/ouragans-hurricanes/default.asp?lang=en&n=B1A7B85A-1}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Davey, William J. and MacKinnon, Richard|title=Dictionary of Cape Breton English|year=2016|publisher=University of Toronto Press|isbn=9781442615991|accessdate=April 8, 2020|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=y4RyDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA4#v=onepage&q&f=false|page=4|via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref> Throughout [[the Maritimes]], dozens of large ships were stranded or destroyed.<ref name=\"wreck\"/> Warning signals were hoisted in Nova Scotia on the evening of August 20, and ultimately lowered near midday on August 22.<ref name=\"canada\">{{cite journal|author=Carpmael, Charles|title=Storm warnings|date=December 20, 1893|journal=Monthly Weather Review|volume=16|page=10|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FRdKAQAAMAAJ&pg=RA40-PA14|via=[[Google Books]]|publisher=[[Meteorological Service of Canada]]|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref> \n\nIn [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]], rain and wind began in the early afternoon on August 21 and grew in severity through the night. The city was plunged into darkness and cut off from the outside world as electric and communications wires fell. Severed power lines sparked small fires and posed a hazard to public safety; one young girl was electrocuted and killed by a live wire, and two more people received non-life-threatening shocks while attempting to recover her body. Parks, public gardens, and cemeteries throughout the city suffered extensive damage, with many large trees being destroyed.<ref name=\"night\">{{cite news|title=Night of terror|date=August 22, 1893|newspaper=The Boston Globe|page=5|accessdate=April 8, 2020|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48293798/the-boston-globe/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> Many ships and boats were wrecked or blown ashore in [[Halifax Harbour]]. In one instance, after colliding with a wharf and being struck by two [[pontoon (boat)|pontoon boats]], the schooner ''Janie R.''{{'}}s cargo of [[lime (material)|lime]] swelled with the influx of seawater to the point of breaking the ship apart.<ref name=\"gazette\">{{cite news|title=It was an awful gale|date=August 23, 1893|page=1|newspaper=The Gazette|accessdate=April 8, 2020|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48294534/the-gazette/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> Trees were uprooted and chimneys toppled in [[Liverpool, Nova Scotia|Liverpool]].<ref name=\"canada\"/> The storm was less severe in [[Yarmouth, Nova Scotia|Yarmouth]], at the western end of the province, but still washed out streets and blew down trees there.<ref name=\"gazette\"/> The winds damaged trees, fences, and some buildings in [[Amherst, Nova Scotia|Amherst]], and crops in the surrounding countryside were flattened.<ref name=\"gazette\"/> In [[Cumberland County, Nova Scotia|Cumberland County]], the Palmerston Bridge over the upper [[Pugwash, Nova Scotia|Pugwash Harbor]] was badly damaged, and two [[barque]]s were blown ashore at [[Northport, Nova Scotia|Northport]].<ref name=\"gazette\"/> Several schooners were wrecked along the shores of [[Cape Breton]];<ref name=\"gazette\"/> in [[Ingonish]], two ships were left stranded on the shore and six fishing boats drifted out to sea. Residents of the rural community fled their homes at the height of the storm to sheek shelter in nearby valleys.<ref name=\"canada\"/> \n\nLate on the night of August 21, the [[steamer]] ''Dorcas'', with [[barge]] ''Etta Stewart'' in tow, wrecked on the notoriously hazardous [[reef]] surrounding Shut-In Island, near the entrance to [[Three Fathom Harbour, Nova Scotia|Three Fathom Harbour]].<ref name=\"wreck\"/><ref name=\"pioneer\">{{cite magazine|author=McNeil, Alexander|magazine=The Suburban|volume=5|issue=11|page=4|date=April 13, 1907|title=Pioneers of Nova Scotia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NEo_AAAAYAAJ&pg=RA10-PA4|accessdate=April 9, 2020|oclc=235821506|via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref> Both vessels were loaded with coal en route from [[Sydney, Nova Scotia|Sydney]] to Halifax. It is likely that the barge took on water in the heavy seas, making it impossible to steer and causing both ships to drift toward shore in the strong southerly winds.<ref name=\"wreck\"/> After hitting the rocks, the steamer overturned, losing its engine, boilers, and cargo, and came to rest inverted on the beach. The barge was \"dashed to pieces\", littering the shore with timbers.<ref name=\"wreck\"/><ref name=\"pioneer\"/> All crew-members and passengers, totaling 24 people, were killed: ''Dorcas'' carried a crew of 10, plus the chief engineer's pregnant wife and 4 children in his care, while 8 crewmen and one passenger were on ''Etta Stewart''.<ref name=\"wreck\"/><ref name=\"carbondale\">{{cite news|title=Twenty-four are lost|date=August 24, 1893|page=1|newspaper=The Evening Herald|accessdate=April 9, 2020|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48299494/the-evening-herald/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> All bodies but one were recovered. The small community of [[Louisbourg]], home to 16 of the victims and many of their families, was left reeling, and a rare government inquiry into the disaster was opened; it concluded that the wreck was beyond the control of Captain Angus Ferguson of ''Dorcas'', who \"sacrificed his own life in his endeavour to save those on board the two vessels\". The commissioner of the inquiry acknowledged that cutting the barge free may have increased the chance of survival for the crew and passengers of ''Dorcas'', but dismissed this as a viable option:<ref name=\"wreck\"/> \n\n{{quote|text=\"It may be considered by some that it would have been more prudent and wise for the master of the ''Dorcas'' to have disconnected his steamer from the barge at some safe time before approaching the breakers, in order to enable his vessel to reach off shore and thus have made an effort to save the larger number of people on board the steamer at the sacrifice of the less number of people on board the barge.</br>\"Had Captain Ferguson, however, acted in such a manner and been successful in saving the steamer with those on board, he would have forever been branded as a coward when he reached the land and laid himself open to the serious charge of deliberately and wilfully sacrificing the lives of many human beings for the sake of saving his own. To a brave man this would have been intolerable and it must be acknowledged that in acting as he did he displayed the genuine characteristics of a noble seaman, when, amidst the dangers of such a hurricane and wild sea, he met death at the post of duty.\"}}\n\nDespite the tragedy at Shut-In Island, the loss of life in Nova Scotia was considered low relative to the large number of shipwrecks.<ref name=\"carbondale\"/><ref name=\"seventeen\"/>\n\nExtensive storm damage, including downed trees and telegraph wires, collapsed barns, and sunk vessels along the coast, was reported in parts of [[New Brunswick]].<ref name=\"gazette\"/> At [[Point Escuminac]], winds blew at {{convert|60|to|62|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} for three hours and many fishing boats were whisked ashore. A similar situation presented itself further north in [[Shippagan]].<ref name=\"canada\"/> The cyclone severed communications between [[Prince Edward Island]] and the mainland, and inflicted widespread damage upon the province. Streets in the capital city of [[Charlottetown]] were strewn with downed tree limbs; in rural sectors, barns were destroyed. A stretch of [[breakwater]] in [[Souris, Prince Edward Island|Souris]] was washed out.<ref name=\"gazette\"/> Fishing boats in [[Tignish, Prince Edward Island|Tignish]] were shattered.<ref name=\"canada\"/> In [[Perc\u00e9, Quebec|Perc\u00e9]], on the eastern tip of [[Quebec]]'s [[Gasp\u00e9 Peninsula]], 14 fishing vessels were destroyed.<ref name=\"canada\"/> The extratropical remnants of the cyclone continued to produce strong winds over [[Newfoundland (island)|Newfoundland]], ruining crops and damaging homes that were under construction. The sinking of a boat in [[Trinity Bay (Newfoundland and Labrador)|Trinity Bay]] resulted in the drowning deaths of two men, one of them a local politician.<ref name=\"seventeen\">{{cite news|title=Seventeen were drowned|date=August 24, 1893|page=1|newspaper=The Gazette|accessdate=April 9, 2020|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48299453/the-gazette/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> [[St. John's, Newfoundland and Labrador|St. John's]] reported powerful winds that prostrated trees.<ref name=\"canada\"/> \n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Tropical cyclones}}\n*[[1899 San Ciriaco hurricane]] \u2013 followed a similar path across Puerto Rico, becoming the deadliest hurricane in the island's history<ref name=\"las\">{{cite report|url=http://latinamericanstudies.org/puertorico/hurricane.pdf|title=The Hurricane of San Ciriaco: Disaster, Politics, Society in Puerto Rico, 1899\u20131901|author=Schwartz, Stuart B.|date=1992|work=Latin American Studies|publisher=[[Duke University Press]]|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Climate of Puerto Rico]]\n*[[Hurricane Juan]] \n*[[List of New England hurricanes]]\n*[[List of Canada hurricanes]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=nb}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.aoml.noaa.gov/general/lib/lib1/nhclib/mwreviews/1893.pdf Monthly Weather Review]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:San Roque}}\n[[Category:Category 3 Atlantic hurricanes]]\n[[Category:1893 Atlantic hurricane season|3]]\n[[Category:Hurricanes in Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:Hurricanes in Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:Hurricanes in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Hurricanes in Canada]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 1893]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toSt. Margaret's Bay(link changed toSt. Margarets Bay, Nova Scotia) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1893_Hurricane_San_Roque"}
